<DOCNO> AP880831-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrunkenDriver-Mother     08-31 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drunken Driver-Mother,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Urges Leniency For Driver Who Killed Her Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother said she asked the court for
leniency on behalf of the drunken driver who killed her son because
the 21-year-old former soldier deserved the chance to change his
ways.
   Jefferson Circuit Judge Ellen Ewing granted Margaret Smith's
request and ordered Richard Brinkley to serve 90 days in jail.
Ewing suspended the rest of a five-year prison term and placed him
on five years' probation.
   Ms. Smith said it had been hard to accept the loss of her
25-year-old son, Patrick, in such an accident.
   ``I feel like the most important thing in my life has been taken
away from me,'' she told the judge Monday. ``Every time I go by ...
I'll be reminded of where my son died, and that hurts very much.
   ``But I feel like Mr. Brinkley is very young, too, and he should
have the chance to maybe change his ways.''
   Brinkley, of Decatur, Ark., had been charged with second-degree
manslaughter. But in July he pleaded guilty to the reduced charge
of reckless homicide as part of an agreement with Assistant
Commonwealth's Attorney Tom Wine.
   The accident occurred Dec. 12 as Brinkley was driving the wrong
direction in the westbound lanes of the Gene Snyder Freeway.
Brinkley's pickup collided with Smith's car, and Smith died at the
scene of multiple injuries.
   A test showed Brinkley's blood-alcohol level was 0.14 percent,
above the state's 0.1 percent at which a person is presumed
intoxicated.
   At the urging of Smith's mother, Wine had recommended that
Brinkley be placed on probation so he could give public talks about
the dangers of drunken driving.
   Brinkley, who had been stationed at Fort Knox, was discharged
from the Army this month, primarily because of the accident, said
defense attorney Doug Miller.
</TEXT>
