<HEAD>On The Lght Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST WINTHROP, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Camp owners on Little Cobbossee Lake
discovered a new island, and it floats as the wind shifts.
   ``It's pretty wild to see,'' Tom Gordon, of the Cobbossee
Watershed District, said Tuesday. ``You can have a stretch of beach
one day and the next day have wetland.''
   The island, covered with cattails, grass and wild rice, is
apparently a chunk of wetland that broke off from the mainland and
floated out into the lake, Gordon said.
   ``It is a real inconvenience for property owners,'' Gordon said.
   One resident, Paul Kendall, said he thought he could push the
island, with help from other boaters, to shore in a less bothersome
area. There, he said, it would have to be tied down to prevent it
from floating back out.
   But Kendall also had another idea for getting rid of the island.
   ``Hey,'' he asked a visitor, ``you want some land?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beginning soon, the Jeep name will
be seen not only on the rear of the vehicles made by Chrysler
Corp., but on the rears of people.
   Chrysler has agreed to a licensing deal with Murjani, a New York
City-based clothing marketer, allowing the Jeep name to adorn blue
jeans and other sportswear.
   Robert Kirkwood, manager of Jeep licensing for the No. 3
automaker, said the clothing will be unveiled in March in
department stores, catalogs and ``Jeep gear'' stores.
