<HEAD>Eight Injured As Jet Hits Turbulence, Lands In Savannah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight passengers and two crew members were
injured Tuesday when a USAir jet, traveling from Pittsburgh to Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., encountered severe turbulence over South
Carolina, officials said.
   The plane made an unscheduled stop in Savannah, where the
injured were taken to Memorial Medical Center for treatment, mostly
of bruises and scrapes. One passenger, an unidentified pregnant
woman, was admitted for overnight observation, said Dave Shipley, a
spokesman for USAir in Washington.
   About 100 other passengers on the flight were put on other
planes to continue their travel, Shipley said. The National
Transportation Safety Board will investigate, he added.
   Shipley said the pilot of the Boeing 737-300 was passing some
thunderstorms when a sudden jolt hit the plane 30 miles south of
Columbia, S.C.
   ``There were thunderstorms in the area and none of them were
painted (reflected) on his radar,'' Shipley said. ``He was
maneuvering around them visually when it hit.''
