<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OrindaFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0405 08-31 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orinda Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0405,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Guts Five $1 Million Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT to Dashnor sted Dashner.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OAT3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grass and brush fire raged out of
control Tuesday afternoon, quickly destroyed five expensive homes
and badly damaged two others.
   The blaze was controlled about two hours after it began in this
rural community about 20 miles east of San Francisco, said Fire
Capt. Greg Holm.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   Orinda Police Chief John Dashnor said police and fire
investigators are canvassing the area to check out second-hand
reports that a teen-ager was seen shortly before the fire carrying
a bottle rocket, a homemade fireworks device.
   Several people reported hearing sounds like firecrackers minutes
before the blaze broke out, said Holm.
   ``We are investigating it as a suspicious fire, but the cause
has not been determined,'' he added.
   Five houses, each worth about $1 million, were destroyed and two
others had an undetermined amount of damage, said Fire Chief Ed
Lucas.
   Many residents were not at home when the fire broke out. The
flames rapidly spread through the dry brush and tree-covered hills,
destroying several houses in just minutes. About 10 acres were
burned, said firefighter Marty O'Connell.
   Beverly Hopp, whose 33-year-old home was destroyed in the blaze,
said several children helped her rescue her four dogs from the
flames. The only property she and husband, Al, were able to save
was a desk containing money and insurance papers.
   ``This has been the worst time of my life,'' she said ``What do
you do after all these years?''
   Nancy Artist, a homeowner and 18-year resident, said the fire
came within yards of her home.
   ``The hills are steep, and when the wind comes up, it makes
those hills like chimneys with flames just coming right up them,''
Artist said.
   Shifting winds, gusting up to 22 mph, made it difficult for
firefighters to contain the blaze. The fire shifted directions
several times because of the winds, officials said.
   ``One time it's going down the hills, then seconds later it's
going up the hills faster than it came down,'' Artist said.
   Lynne Cechettini, 16, was napping when her sister woke her up
and told her about the fire.
   ``I looked out the kitchen and there was this huge flame wall
and I thought for sure our house was gone,'' said Cechettini, whose
hair was filled with ashes. Only the roof of the Cechettini's home
burned.
   The homes were situated among grassland dotted by patches of
California scrub oaks, pine and eucalyptus trees and low-lying
bushes.
</TEXT>
