<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanAttitudes     08-31 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Attitudes,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Style Marriage and Divorce Criticized by Americans, Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese attitudes toward marriage, divorce
and the family are changing but the American model is an
unattractive one, young adults from both countries said at a
cultural exchange.
   Thirty university students from Japan and 30 from the United
States, ranging in age from 17 to 25, compared cultural and social
traditions at a gathering that produced strong criticism from both
sides of the high U.S. divorce rate.
   The United States in 1985 had five divorces and 10.2 marriages
per 1,000 people. Comparable Japanese figures were 1.39 divorces
and 6.2 marriages per 1,000.
   ``Americans seem so crazy about kids, but when they divorce
aren't they forgetting about the children?'' said Tadakatsu Tsuruno
of Tokyo at the daylong session last week in Washington
co-sponsored by Nihon Keizai, a Japanese economic newspaper, and
Konica, the photographic and electronics company. The Japanese,
from 11 universities, were winners of an essay contest on the two
countries' roles in the world. The Americans were engaged in
Japanese or other foreign studies at U.S. universities.
   University of Maryland student Scott Larson said the high U.S.
divorce rate ``is a sign of how individualism has gone out of
control'' in the United States. He called it ``individualism with
no altruism.''
   But despite their criticism of U.S. trends, Tsuruno and other
Japanese said things also are changing at home.
   ``The Japanese attitude to marriage is approaching the American
way ... with people thinking more for themselves,'' Tsuruno noted.
``We still have arranged marriages, but 99 percent of my generation
will find wives by themselves.''
   Noriko Takahashi, a Tokyo University medical student, said she
will make the final decision on her future husband although she
will consult with her parents.
   She said that if someone simply wants romance, ``you can have it
without marriage. But the reason for marriage is to have children
and propagate generation after generation'' of the family.
   Laura Pochop of Brown University said Japan's divorce rate is
likely to rise as Japanese women acquire the ability to support
themselves. Without it, she said, many Japanese wives are forced to
accept their husbands' liaisons with other women, ``a situation
American women would find intolerable.''
   A moderator, Prof. Martin Weinstein of the University of
Illinois and Washington's Center for Strategic and International
Studies, said Japan's divorce rate is rising, with more older women
divorcing after raising their children to adulthood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
