<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Housing-Homeless     08-31 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing-Homeless,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says HUD Must Consider Homeless When Selling Foreclosed
Houses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development must consider the needs of the homeless before the
agency auctions off government-owned, foreclosed homes to the
highest bidder, a federal judge says.
   U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene temporarily barred HUD on
Tuesday from selling 170 single-family homes in the metropolitan
Washington area. The sale was scheduled for today.
   Last week, another federal judge in Washington blocked HUD from
selling 200 foreclosed homes in Michigan.
   The actions are part of a broader effort to force the federal
government to make some of HUD's inventory of 47,000 foreclosed
houses available to the homeless.
   Greene, in issuing his temporary restraining order, said HUD had
violated federal laws by refusing to make a survey of its stock of
buildings and properties and determine which might be transferred
to non-profit groups that provide services for the homeless.
   He also said HUD has not complied with the law which calls for
``the realization as soon as feasible of the goal of a decent home
and a suitable living environment for every American family.''
   ``HUD cannot just sell to the highest bidder,'' he said. ``The
government cannot not just consider the amount of revenue coming
in.''
   Greene said his temporary restraining order would last until
Sept. 14 while Judge Oliver Gasch, who has jurisdiction over the
case, schedules further action.
   HUD is acquiring foreclosed properties at a rate of about 7,000
each month. Because it has been selling between 6,000 and 7,000 of
the properties monthly, the agency has accumulated a ``rolling
inventory'' of about 47,000 homes, the largest backlog in its
history.
   The surge in HUD's stock of properties reflects a rash of
foreclosures on properties in the oil-producing states, and an
increase in the overall volume of homes insured by HUD in the wake
of lower interest rates two years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
