<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-International-Drugs     08-31 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-International-Drugs,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Claim Success in Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say a 30-nation narcotics
crackdown resulted in more than 1,200 arrests in the past month and
should lead to further drug busts in this hemisphere.
   ``Some operations are still going on,'' Charles Gutensohn, head
of cocaine investigations at the Drug Enforcement Administration,
said Tuesday.
   Attorney General Richard L. Thornburgh and a host of other U.S.
and foreign officials said Tuesday that 30 countries had
participated in a series of anti-drug trafficking operations this
month, primarily in South and Central America.
   Thornburgh said authorities seized 11 tons of cocaine and
destroyed 244 tons of marijuana, 118,000 coca plants and 13 cocaine
laboratories. Authorities also demolished seven hidden airstrips
and seized $3.8 million in cash, he said.
   While Thornburgh said the effort did not represent victory in
the war against drugs, he said the ``cooperative nature'' of the
operations represented a new avenue in stamping out trafficking.
   ``Heretofore, each of the nations of the Americas has been
pursuing the war on drugs in a more or less unilateral or bilateral
fashion,'' he said.
   The participating countries, all members of the International
Drug Enforcement Conference, shared resources and intelligence and,
in a few cases, staged cross-border operations.
   Thornburgh said the United States did not orchestrate the drug
busts, though it did serve as a clearinghouse for data. Instead,
each country planned and executed its drug operations, often in
concert with other countries.
   ``By doing it all over at once, you disrupt the operation,''
Gutensohn said.
   Since many drug traffickers ignore national boundaries, it is
vital to close in on traffickers on many fronts, he said.
   In Peru, for instance, military authorities seized cocaine
laboratories in the Upper Huallaga Valley that are used by members
of the powerful Medellin and Calli drug cartels, based in Colombia.
Cocaine labs also were seized in Colombia itself, as well as
Bolivia.
   Among some other actions cited by the officials:
   _About 100 National Guardsmen in Arizona, Florida and Texas
helped border patrol officials inspect vehicles that crossed into
the United States.
   _As a result of information developed abroad, New York officials
seized two tons of cocaine and about $2 million in cash.
   _Military officers from Colombia and Venezuela operated along
the joint border.
   _Officials in Panama and Costa Rica worked together to seize
chemicals used for cocaine at points along the border. Panama
participated in the operation as a member of the conference, but
did not receive any ``centralized intelligence'' from the United
States, Thornburgh said.
   Panama's military dictator, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, has
been indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida on charges of
drug trafficking and money laundering. Washington has sought his
ouster since early this year, applying economic sanctions that have
hurt Panama's economy.
   _European nations and Canada stepped up monitoring of vessels,
cargo and aircraft arriving from South America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
