<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle-Press     08-31 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Press,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boos Follow Quayle On Campaign Trail, But They're For the Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are plenty of boos on the campaign trail
with Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle, but they're
not for the candidate. They're for the press entourage traveling
with him.
   The press is generally seen by pro-Quayle audiences as the skunk
at the picnic as he makes his way around the country, because of
reporters' questions about the National Guard, his academic record,
his resume and various other personal details Quayle has called
``side events.''
   ``Let him alone!'' the audience shouts as reporters try to
waylay the vice presidential nominee. Some of the shouts are less
polite.
   Signs like ``Media Beware,'' ``Cut Sam Donaldson's Tongue Out''
and ``Press Go Home'' greet the traveling press.
   Last week, on Quayle's seven-state trip, at almost every stop
were identical signs with the word ``Press'' encircled in red and
with a red slash mark through the word, leading some to suspect an
organized effort.
   At a stop in Columbia, Mo., one unidentified teen-ager held such
a sign and told reporters, ``Someone gave it to me when I came in
the door and I liked it.''
   David Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman, said he had no idea where
the signs came from.
   ``I'm quite confident that it is nobody affiliated with the
Bush-Quayle organization in any way, shape or form,'' he said.
``That's just not the way we do business.''
   Prosperi said Quayle does not intend to ``have a fight with the
press.''
   ``We're here to have a fight with the other guys on the
issues,'' he said.
   Quayle was asked Sunday as he flew home whether he felt at times
as if he were running against the news media, instead of the
Democrats.
   ``I'm running with George Bush,'' he replied.
   Quayle won't say whether he thinks the press is out to get him,
telling reporters ``only you can answer that question.'' But he
says he does not disagree with his wife, Marilyn, who last week
said she felt the press was biased against Quayle because he was a
conservative.
   But Quayle has made it clear he dislikes the intensive media
scrutiny that has followed him since he became Bush's running mate
and allegations surfaced that he pulled strings to get into the
National Guard during the Vietnam War and into law school after an
average performance in college.
   At the California State Fair in Sacramento, Quayle petted a
Labrador retriever guide dog and when the dog just lay there with
his eyes rolled up, Quayle said, ``Now I know how it feels to be
hounded.''
   He tends to make sarcastic references to the press in his stump
speech, often referring to ``my newfound friends in the news
media'' or ``my cheering section.''
   The references are not lost on the audiences. At one appearance
in West Carrollton, Ohio, reporters who tried to ask Quayle about
the National Guard issue as he made his way shaking hands were
dealt with roughly.
   A large woman hit one female reporter's arm and shoulder and
turned and dealt another one a hefty body block. She said the two
women were endangering a group of Scouts.
   ``I'm just trying to protect the children,'' she shouted.
   The hostility reached its peak at a rally in Quayle's hometown
of Huntington, Ind., as he and Bush campaigned together on their
first day after the Republican convention. At a news conference
that was piped to the crowd over the public address system, the
crowd cheered Quayle's answers and booed reporters' questions.
   ``B-o-r-i-n-g,'' they shouted.
   On Tuesday, Quayle couldn't resist another reference to the
press, when he spoke to the International Association of Fire
Chiefs. ``I feel that I am very accustomed to fighting fires these
last couple of weeks.''
   When he was presented with a fire chief's hat, Quayle said:
``This is going to be prominently displayed on my airplane ...
right in front of where the press is sitting.''
   The hat will join another memento. At a California stop last
week, Quayle's aides quickly grabbed up a bumper sticker which
stated: ``I Don't Love the Liberal Media.''
   It is affixed it to the cabin door that faces the press section
of the aircraft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
