<TEXT>
   circuits
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He no longer looks much like a ``splinter,'' but
to many of his fans baseball batting great Ted Williams is still
splendid at 70.
   ``He's a kid forever as far as I'm concerned,'' said Ed Stack,
president of the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y. ``Ted's
very much a young person. He's never going to be old; he's that
type of guy.''
   Williams, dubbed the ``Splendid Splinter'' when he played for
the Boston Red Sox at a lean 165 pounds, had some extra weight on
his frame as he celebrated his 70th birthday Tuesday, but the image
of major league baseball's last .400-season hitter was still fresh
in fans' minds.
   Williams, who retired in 1960, still shows up at Red Sox spring
training camp in Winter Haven, Fla., sharing his hitting philosophy
with players who heard about the legend of ``Teddy Ballgame'' from
their fathers.
   ``My dad talked about him a lot,'' said Red Sox outfielder Mike
Greenwell, a leading hitter in the American League this season.
``He was big when my dad was growing up.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TV cameraman suffered a cut to his head when
Houston Rockets star Akeem Olajuwon grabbed his equipment after
being questioned about a lawsuit filed against him by his former
girlfriend, a reporter said.
   The former girlfriend, Lita Spencer, claims the 6-11 National
Basketball Association center deserted her because he wanted a
taller woman to bear his sons.
   KHOU-TV reporter Mark Watts said he and cameraman Jim Shipley
had gone to Olajuwon's house Tuesday to get comment about the
lawsuit.
   ``He started shouting at us and told us to get away,'' Watts
said, adding that the two started to leave the house.
   But Olajuwon ran after the cameraman and grabbed his video
equipment, causing it to hit Shipley's forehead, Watts said.
Shipley was treated and released at a hospital without needing
stitches.
   In her lawsuit filed Friday in federal court, Ms. Spencer asks
for $9 million in damages on grounds that Olajuwon refused to marry
her after she became pregnant in an attempt to prove to him that
she could bear children.
   Ms. Spencer, a petite, University of Houston law school student,
contends Olajuwon left her for ``a taller woman who is more likely
to bear tall sons worthy of his genetic heritage.'' The suit says
Olajuwon breached a contract when he backed out of his promise to
marry Ms. Spencer.
   ``When basketball season starts, I will have something to say,''
Olajuwon said. ``Until then, I have no comment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The handmade duds of country singer
Holly Dunn have dazzled fans and led to requests for custom togs
from her band.
   Ms. Dunn, whose hit song, ``Daddy's Hands,'' was nominated for a
Grammy Award last year, creates trimmings for her Western-style
stage wear while the band tours.
   ``I'm going to get a sewing machine for the (tour) bus. Right
now I do everything by hand and it's tedious,'' the songwriter and
producer said recently. ``I Dale-Evans 'em up.''
   Ms. Dunn said she learned to sew in seventh grade home economics
class in Abilene, Texas, and prowls fabric shops in her spare time
along the tour.
