<NOTE>Eds: A longer version moved on the financial wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey gaming regulators have
thrown a roadblock in the way of entertainer Merv Griffin, who has
won approval to buy Resorts International Inc. from developer
Donald Trump.
   Griffin's proposed trust agreement _ needed before he can buy
the Resorts stock from Trump, the controlling stockholder, and
Class A shareholders _ failed to win approval Tuesday from the
state Casino Control Commission.
   The trust agreement is necessary in case the commission finds
Griffin ineligible for a New Jersey gaming license. In that case,
the trust would run the company until Griffin could appeal the
decision or sell off the company's assets.
   The commission voted 3-2 against the proposed trust agreement,
largely because it calls for a trustee to take control of The
Griffin Co. rather than just the Resorts stock.
   Griffin officials wanted the trust agreement to cover The
Griffin Co. to ensure the firm is able to take advantage of prior
tax losses of Resorts, potentially worth $100 million.
   The former talk show host, however, said he still expects the
deal to go through.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Prince Charles will be invited to
return here in 1991 to view the evolution of steelmaking towns
since he endorsed their revitalization at an urban planning
conference.
   David Lewis, an architect and organizer of the Remaking Cities
Conference, announced the plan Monday night at a meeting of the
Pittsburgh Institute for the Future.
   Following a whirlwind, five-day study of communities struggling
to survive the decline of steelmaking in the region, an
international team of 17 architects and planners recommended that
former mill sites be secured quickly for development in the coming
years.
   Prince Charles, who has become known as a critic of contemporary
city planning, endorsed a plan to revamp aging cities during a
keynote speech at March's conference.
</TEXT>
