<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HardRockSentence     08-31 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hard Rock Sentence,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hard Rock, Not Hard Time, For Convicted Cocaine Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite strong objections from the
prosecutor, a judge sentenced a cocaine dealer to stage benefit
rock n' roll concerts for juvenile drug treatment programs rather
than a prison term.
   The Santa Clara County prosecutor who tried the case had asked
the judge for a six-year sentence for 26-year-old Dan Nelson, a San
Jose concert promoter.
   ``This is a better deal for society,'' said Nelson, whom a jury
in April found guilty of offering cocaine for sale, possessing the
drug for sale and being armed during the undercover narcotics
transaction that incriminated him.
   Agents testified he carried a briefcase with 17 ounces of
cocaine and a loaded handgun.
   The sentence was handed down last week by Superior Court Judge
Paul R. Teilh. Nelson could avoid spending even a night in prison,
but must donate 1,820 hours of community service work and pay a
$5,000 fine.
   Nelson, who has no previous record, also was sentenced to a year
in the county jail, but would be allowed to work during the day and
spend his evenings at home with an electronic monitor clamped to
his ankle.
   ``I'm upset and very, very disappointed,'' said Deputy District
Attorney Margaret Dufreschou. ``We're trying to make a real
deterrent against drug sales, and I don't think this helps.
   ``Getting arrested and going to prison are part of the cost of
doing business for drug dealers. What this does is lower their cost
of doing business,'' she said.
   However, Vince Schiraldi of the National Center on Institutions
and Alternatives in San Francisco called the judge's sentence
``courageous and wise.''
   ``We're punishing the guy and getting a very needed community
service at the same time. There are winners all the way around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
