<HEAD>Large Lizard Lets Loose; Law Left Looking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAND HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents who reported seeing a
creature that resembled a crocodile were relieved to hear that
police caught a 2-foot lizard, but now a larger animal is out and
about.
   The unidentified owner retrieved the smaller lizard Sunday. But
on Tuesday, he returned to police in this Ocean County community
and admitted that another lizard, his ``golden tegu'' _ a
5-foot-long version _ has been on the loose for about a month.
   Acting Police Chief Robert T. Burger said Tuesday that workers
recently spotted the large lizard creeping near the town's garage,
located near a marsh, where it is feeding on rodents.
   The owner is a student who police won't identify because he is
being investigated by the state Department of Fish, Game &
Wildlife. But he has told police that the lizard is harmless unless
provoked.
