<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 4thLd-Writethru a0761 08-31 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0761,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Leaves For Warsaw For Talks with Polish Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with Walesa leaving for Warsaw. Pick up
10th graf pvs, `On Tuesday ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa left for
Warsaw on Wednesday for his first talks with Polish authorities
since Solidarity was banned. The government hoped the meeting would
end two weeks of labor unrest.
   Asked what he would discuss with Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczak during the talks, Walesa said: ``How to make up for the
past seven years.'' Solidarity was crushed in a 1981 military
crackdown.
   Walesa traveled by car with senior Solidarity adviser Tadeusz
Mazowiecki.
   The meeting Walesa's advisers said would be held Wednesday would
follow four days of maneuvering started by Kiszczak's proposal on
Friday that officials and worker representatives hold
``round-table'' discussions.
   A communique from the Communist Party's ruling Politburo,
distributed by the official news agency PAP, mentioned a
round-table meeting, endorsed it and said Kiszczak should ``carry
on with the mission entrusted to him.''
   It was not clear, however, whether the reference was to the
Wednesday meeting or the minister's original proposal on Friday. No
other official reference was made to Walesa-Kiszczak talks.
   Ten enterprises in Poland remained on strike. At its height, the
current labor trouble involved 20 sites employing 100,000 people
and was the worst since 1980.
   Solidarity spokesmen said there was no agreement for an
immediate end to the strikes, in which a central demand has been
making Solidarity legal again. Mazowiecki called the decision for
talks ``a historic moment.''
   Walesa last met with the government on behalf of the union in
late 1981.
   On Tuesday evening, Walesa left the strikebound Lenin shipyard,
where he works as an electrician, to confer with advisers and
Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski at nearby St. Brygida's church. He emerged
from the rectory with the bishop later to cheers and chants from
supporters.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said earlier in the day that
talks could begin as soon as Walesa called off the strike at the
Lenin shipyard, where the Soviet bloc's first free union was born
in the labor uprising of 1980, but aide Piotr Konopka said: ``For
the present, the strike is still on.''
   He said Walesa would attend the Wednesday meeting as president
of the Independent Self-Governing Trade Union Solidarity, the labor
federation's full name.
   While the government expressed its willingness to talk, strikers
at the Stalowa Wola steel mill in southeastern Poland said soldiers
had moved into the town and helicopters flew over the plant.
   Workers are occupying the shipyard and steel mill, as is
customary during strikes in Poland.
   In a reference to the Stalowa Wola strike, Kiszczak's ministry
and the armed forces general staff issued a statement saying: ``In
case of the continuation of the illegal strike action, appropriate
lawful measures will be taken.''
   Adam Michnik, a historian and senior Walesa adviser, said
Tuesday night: ``The talks begin exactly on the anniversary of the
August agreements'' that created Solidarity as a legal union in
1980.
   ``We want to believe that a new chance begins and it will be at
a time when Poles can make use of this chance,'' he said. ``The
results of this meeting tomorrow will be very important for the
fate of the country and the world.''
   Mazowiecki said: ``We hope that this meeting will serve the
purpose of dialogue and agreement and the most important issue,
which is trade union pluralism and the legalization of Solidarity.''
   Urban told his weekly news conference Tuesday: ``The stoppage of
strikes by Mr. Lech Walesa and the shipyard where he works would
mean automatically convening a round table.''
   He said no rules had been made for the agenda of the
``round-table'' talks with representatives of various segments of
society, to be moderated by Kiszczak, who suggested them last
Friday.
   ``We are ready for talks ... with all those who respect the law,
a significant symptom of which is avoiding participation in illegal
srikes and moreover contributing to their stoppage,'' Urban said.
   Walesa had said he would not call off the Lenin shipyard strike
unless Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's government promised to include
trade union pluralism in the discussion and he was allowed to take
part as the recognized leader of Solidarity.
   He traditionally marks the Aug. 31 date of the signing of the
Gdansk agreements by laying a wreath at a monument to workers
killed in labor unrest during 1970. It is near the Lenin shipyard's
main gate.
   Michnik said earlier that Urban's statement represented only a
``preliminary step'' because it ``does not say exactly what can be
understood by the term round table, who would sit at it, and the
subject of the talks.''
   Most strikers have demanded higher pay and better working
conditions in addition to legalization of Solidarity, but the
status of the outlawed union is the only demand at Stalowa Wola.
Piotr Niemczyk, a Solidarity spokesman in Warsaw, said the workers
had authoritized Walesa to negotiate for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
