<DOCNO> AP880831-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Buffalo Bjt   08-31 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Buffalo, Bjt,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Native Buffalo Weather Drought In Fine Fashion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAYES, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seemingly unaffected, buffalo roam the
parched South Dakota prairie on America's largest bison ranch while
crops wither and domestic livestock suffer and even die because of
the drought.
   ``Nature sure gave them about everything it takes to survive ...
except the bullet,'' said Roy Houck, who with his late wife,
Nellie, started the Houck Buffalo Ranch nearly three decades ago.
   The hardy bison, native to North America, were hunted to near
extinction in the late 1800s for its skins and meat.
   Houck's buffalo forage on brown grass and linger near water
holes. The ranch has more than 200 ponds, all of which have been
drawn down by the drought, and some are almost dry.
   Depending on the season, 3,000 to 4,500 buffalo inhabit the
50,000-acre ranch that's fenced into 35 pastures.
   After the various herds are allowed to graze in one pasture for
a few weeks, the gate to the next pasture is opened, and the huge
beasts move into the area to resume foraging.
   ``The main breeding herd, we don't feed them anything but
grass,'' said the 83-year-old Houck. ``We try to supplement the
calves a little the first year to give them a boost.''
   Although the drought seems not to have affected the herd, its
impact may show up next spring in a smaller calf crop, Houck said,
explaining that this is the mating season.
   ``These cows won't conceive if they're not in good shape,''
Houck said, glancing over at the rummaging animals about 30 yards
away. ``But so far these cows look pretty good. They're holding
their meat pretty well.''
   The ranch hasn't had a decent rain in more than a year, and
100-plus-degree temperatures have been common all summer.
   But the drought of 1988 is no match yet for the Dust Bowl days
of the 1930s, Houck said.
   ``The dry dust storms of the '30s still haunt me,'' he said.
``It was so dry in the spring of 1934 the grass never even
sprouted.''
   Not that Houck isn't concerned now.
   ``If we're forced into another year of drought, we'll probably
have to graze our pastures a lot longer than we'd like to,'' he
said. ``After going through those dry '30s, you wonder how long
it's going to last.
   ``We've got to be pretty cautious because you can't just load
buffalo on a truck and take them to the sale barn.''
   Buffalo enjoy their freedom, and are handled as little as
possible.
   ``When you get them in confinement, they've only got one thought
in mind and that's to get away,'' Houck said. ``If you happen to be
in the way, that's too bad.''
   Horses once were used to round up the buffalo. Four-wheel drive
trucks are now used.
   ``Buffaloes don't seem to like horses'' and besides can outrun
them, Houck said. One of his sons once ``got his horse knocked
right out from under him'' by an angry buffalo.
   When buffaloes are 2 years old, they are sorted for bulls and
heifers. Most bulls go to slaughter and heifers are kept for
breeding.
   Between 800 and 1,000 are butchered on the ranch each year,
Houck said.
   The market for buffalo meat, which is very low in fat, has been
good, Houck said. ``Right now, we're getting $2 a pound for dressed
buffalo meat.''
   Once an endangered species, buffalo have made a remarkable
comeback, said Mary Duvall, executive director of the National
Buffalo Association. Buffalo numbers are estimated at between
75,000 and 100,000, she said.
   Their numbers reached into the millions before pioneers began
forging westward and found them to be easy prey, dipping to a
historical low near 1,000 head in 1889, Duvall said.
   Realizing the common misconception that buffalo still are
endangered was a hindrance to marketing efforts, Houck helped form
the Fort Pierre-based association, whose members now number about
1,200 buffalo producers.
   The Houcks began ranching by raising cattle. They switched to
buffalo after a March 1966 blizzard that killed more than 200 of
their cattle but not a single buffalo.
   ``They'll just stick their noses down into the snow and eat this
grass, and they'll stay fat on it,'' Houck said. ``I wonder how
they do it, but they do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaliforniaSlug Bjt   08-31 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California Slug, Bjt,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Governor Squashes Proposed State Mollusk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to representing
California, the banana slug just won't do, Gov. George Deukmejian
said in vetoing a bill that designated the slimy, slothful creature
the state's official mollusk.
   The veto by the image-conscious governor, announced Tuesday,
squashed the hopes of a group of Blue Birds and Camp Fire girls
from the San Francisco Bay area who led the campaign to make the
banana slug a state mascot.
   ``I feel really bad that he vetoed it,'' says Grace Moses, 9,
whose Blue Bird troop worked six weeks lobbying. ``I mean, why did
he have to do that? He didn't know anything about it. I hope he
watched the news about it.''
   Deukmejian said he vetoed the bill because the large, brilliant
yellow mollusk, which can eat poison oak without getting a rash,
isn't a true Californian.
   ``If there is a need to designate a state mollusk, it would be
more appropriate to select one that is indigenous to California and
perhaps one that is more representative of the international
reputation that California enjoys,'' he said in his veto message.
   The governor added that the dubious honor of being the banana
slug's home state may belong to wetter neighbors to the north,
since the species was first identified near the mouth of the
Columbia River in Oregon and lives as far north as Alaska.
   But members of the Redwood City Dynamite Blue Birds and the
office of the legislator who carried their slug bill said the
governor is misinformed about the banana slug, which has the
scientific name Ariolimax columbianus and lives in damp coastal
forest areas throughout the Pacific Northwest.
   Janice Hopcraft, an aide to Democratic Assemblyman Bryon Sher,
said four of five kinds of banana slugs are native to California.
   ``I think basically the banana slug has gotten a bad rap,'' said
Hopcraft, who wore a yellow armband Tuesday in memory of Sher's
bill. ``They're obviously easy to look down upon and they do have
some odd habits. Perhaps, the governor looked too much at that and
not their good side.
   ``As far as its representative qualities, it's absolutely a
unique example of the diversity of California's wildlife.''
   Deukmejian, a Republican who's made a personal campaign of
promoting California trade nationally and overseas, suggested the
Golden State may not need an official slug at all.
   And if California must have a mollusk, he'd prefer the pismo
clam, black abalone, red abalone, turban shell, two-spotted
octupus, common squid or another breed of mussel unique to the
state.
   California has several official mascots, including a tree, a
fossil, a reptile, a fish, a rock and even a state insect in
addition to the usual bird, animal and flower. The Legislature sent
a bill to the governor Monday that would designate the square dance
as the official folk dance, and the West Coast swing, or jitterbug,
as the official dance.
   Deukmejian has not acted on that measure.
   The banana slug gained notoriety a few years ago when students
at the University of California, Santa Cruz chose it as the
official school mascot over the sea lion, despite the objections of
the university's president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wildfires-Health     08-31 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires-Health,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoky Conditions In Yellowstone Not Too Dangerous</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tek is cq in 9th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To firefighters on the
front lines, breathing the smoke is like going through four packs
of cigarettes a day, but for those elsewhere in Yellowstone, it
poses little danger, doctors say.
   ``I think the main thing is it's much more an irritant,'' said
Dr. Osman Sawyer, who works at the Old Faithful medical clinic in
the nation's oldest national park.
   Allan Pardee, a retiree from Casa Grande, Ariz., who spends
summers working in a general store at Old Faithful, can attest to
the irritation.
   ``Whenever we get these inversions, we'd get all choked up,''
Pardee said Monday when he came to the clinic seeking relief. ``The
last few days, it's been really bad.
   ``We like to walk back and forth to work,'' he continued. ``It's
about three-quarters of a mile, but it's gotten so bad that by the
time we got to work we could hardly talk to anybody.''
   Pardee's decision to turn to the clinic came on the second
straight day of a weather inversion that trapped smoke from fires
five miles away over the Old Faithful complex. At times during the
two-day period the smoke was so heavy that nearby ridges were
obscured.
   ``We tried bandanas and it worked better than nothing,'' he said.
   Tek Kilgore, a nurse, offered him some surgical masks.
   ``This may just let us stay a little longer,'' Pardee said on
the way back to work.
   Smoke conditions in the park were moderate to heavy throughout
the day Tuesday.
   While in past days the smoke has hung over Old Faithful like a
dense morning mist, Sawyer and Kilgore haven't seen a rise in the
number of patients.
   For one thing, said Kilgore, tourism has gone down as the fires
have churned up, and those tourists who have serious respiratory
conditions likely have stayed away.
   While there are no official figures for August, preliminary
statistics show a 15 to 20 percent decline in tourism during the
first two weeks of the month.
   The drop in patients has been noteable, Kilgore said. During
normal summers, 25-30 people seek help at the clinic each day,
compared with just two to five now, said Kilgore.
   Most who have come have had minor respiratory problems, said
Sawyer.
   For those people away from the fire lines, the smoke's biggest
harm is from irritating particulates, said Sawyer.
   ``It's not the same in terms of lung injuries,'' he said. ``It's
probably no different than living in Denver or L.A.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
