<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Shutdowns Bjt   08-31 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Shutdowns, Bjt,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shutdowns Disrupting Hopes For Palestinian State</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G.LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's shutdown of Arab labor federations
with 80,000 workers and an association of 108 charities is
disrupting institutions that Palestinians hope will form the basis
of a future state.
   Palestinians charge that destroying grassroots organizations is
the whole object of Israel's move, coming after the outlawing of
the so-called popular committees that have guided the 8-month-old
uprising against Israeli occupation.
   ``They want them closed so when a Palestinian state comes, it
will find no infrastructure,'' said Walid Asali, head of the
Palestinian Lawyers Association, one of seven professional groups
shut by the Israelis.
   Israeli authorities accuse the organizations involved of being
fronts for Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization. They
claim the groups distribute funds, recruit members or organize
protests against Israeli rule.
   An army order closed the Palestinians' Federation of Labor last
Thursday, the professional groups a day later and the Palestinian
charities association last Sunday. All were shut for one year.
   The professional organizations represent a total of 10,000
doctors, lawyers, dentists, pharmacists, veterinarians, engineers
and agricultural specialists. The labor federation groups 55 unions
with 70,000 members and covers almost the whole Palestinian work
force.
   Col. Renaan Gissin, deputy Israeli army spokesman, said the two
institutions and the charity association were ideal conduits for
the PLO underground, providing offices, workers and communications
links.
   ``In the past month, they became more and more active and were
being used by the PLO,'' he said.
   Gissin noted that the groups became more important when the
government recently outlawed so-called popular committees, which
had taken over local government functions such as street cleaning.
   The committees also organized demonstrations and enforced
compliance with general strike calls. The army arrested more than
300 of the groups' leaders.
   Gissin said the PLO also was trying to tighten its grip on
social groups that had been linked to Jordan until King Hussein
announced July 31 that he was cutting adminstrative ties with the
occupied West Bank.
   Ghassan Ayoub, a member of the labor federation's 13-member
executive committee, denied the group was working for the PLO, but
acknowledged that some of its activities furthered the uprising.
   The federation negotiated agreements with Palestinian factories
that guaranteed workers would be paid for days when they took part
in general strikes, Ayoub said.
   He said the group also guaranteed full or partial pay for people
unable to reach their work place because of curfews imposed by
Israel.
   Ayoub said the agreements had nothing to do with the PLO, but
were protections that any union would seek for its members: ``We
are unionists, not politicians.''
   He said the federations' main task was to provide health
insurance to members and assistance to families whose breadwinners
lost their jobs or were injured in the unrest, which has claimed
255 Palestinian lives since it began Dec. 8. Four Israelis also
have died.
   Raed Abu Sabra, another federation official, said the union
group also makes monthly payments of about $120 to families of
workers jailed by Israel.
   Clayton Yeutter, the U.S. trade representative, said last week
that the United States was reviewing Israel's special trade status
after the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee complained of
indiscriminate closures of Palestinian unions.
   But Israeli officials said the complaint did not recognize
Israel's security concerns, and Gissin said the government tried to
be sensitive to the social functions of the institutions.
   ``We have to think twice, because (the groups) serve other
functions such as improving social conditions and social welfare,''
he said. ``We don't want to stop those activities, but when it
involves the PLO we have no choice.''
   Both Ayoub and Asali of the lawyers' association said the
closing down of their offices would not stop their work on behalf
of laborers and professionals. Ayoub said offices of the
federation's various unions remained open throughout the West Bank.
   But the two said seizure of union documents from the offices
would impede their organizations' work.
   Ayoub also said workers' committees were afraid to meet because
of earlier arrests of labor leaders
   He also said he Israel might close union medical clinics. Gissin
said no such action would be taken.
   The 42-year-old Ayoub was released three weeks ago after more
than four months in jail. He was held under a law that does not
require charges to be filed, but he said he was accused of being a
member of Fatah, the mainstream PLO faction.
   He said neither he nor the federation was connected to Fatah,
but added: ``We want our independent state and we feel it's our
right to say so.''
</TEXT>
