<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EmergencyLanding 1stLd-Writethru a0415 08-31 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0415,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Makes Emergency Landing After Crew Smells Gasoline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st and 8th grafs, `He said he ...' to CORRECT that
plane took off from San Francisco, sted Seattle; ADDS graf to
explain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines flight en route from
San Francisco to Detroit made an emergency landing here Tuesday
after fumes from a West German tourist's empty gasoline can filled
the cabin, authorities said.
   Cal Clegg, FBI special agent for Utah, said the flight was
diverted after the crew smelled the fumes.
   ``Without knowing the full details, they decided to divert the
plane to Salt Lake,'' Clegg said.
   He said a West German tourist, whose name and hometown were not
available, was interviewed and authorities determined it was an
innocent mistake.
   ``In a nutshell, one of the passengers, a West German who had
been touring the United States, had taken on board with him what
was an apparently empty gas can that still had vapors in it,''
Clegg said. ``During compression and decompression, the vapors
emitted into the cabin area.''
   Clegg said the tourist, who was traveling alone, had rented a
car earlier and ran out of gas.
   ``He had purchased this can and then decided to take it home to
West Germany with him because he had paid for it and apparently
they don't have metal gasoline cans in West Germany, just
plastic,'' Clegg said.
   He said he was unsure how the man got past security guards
before boarding the plane. The can was in carry-on luggage in a
plastic bag with souvenirs, he said.
   ``According to everybody we interviewed out there, the
individual was totally cooperative,'' Clegg said. ``He apologized
and everything else. There were no threats made. No hostile action
on his part in any way.''
   Frank Ratliff, airport operations manager, said the flight left
Salt Lake City about 5:30 p.m. MDT and the man was released,
although he was not on the flight.
   ``He will be on another flight,'' Ratliff said. ``We will not
file charges and it will be turned over to the FAA.''
   Clegg said the flight had originated in Seattle, but Al Stuart,
airport operations supervisor, said the flight began in San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
