<HEAD>Vietnam Again Willing To Help With MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is again willing to cooperate with the
United States in accounting for the more than 1,700 American
military personnel still missing in the Vietnam War, the State
Department says.
   Vietnamese officials had suspended cooperation Aug. 3 in
retaliation against U.S. unwillingness to improve diplomatic
relations until Hanoi withdraws troops from Cambodia.
   A U.S. technical team will meet next month with Vietnamese
authorities in Hanoi to work out details for a joint field survey
and excavation activities in Vietnam, department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley said on Tuesday. She said a U.S. team also will
visit Hanoi on Sept. 5-8 to discuss a plan to allow private
American organizations to treat Vietnamese with war-related
disabilities.
   Mrs. Oakley said Vietnam has not agreed to resume discussions on
resettlement in the United States of former political detainees who
were associated with the former U.S.-backed government in Saigon.
</TEXT>
