<HEAD>`Pink Lady' Of Broadway Dies At Age 98</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazel Dawn, whose singing and acting career in
the early 1900s included a starring role in the original ``Ziegfeld
Follies,'' has died. She was 98.
   Miss Dawn died Sunday at the home of her daughter in Manhattan.
   She began her career in London musical comedies and made her
Broadway stage debut in 1911 in a hit musical, ``The Pink Lady.''
   Miss Dawn went on to become a celebrated singer and actress
until her marriage in 1927 to a Montana mining engineer, Charles
Gruwell, after which she largely gave up her career.
   After Gruwell, reportedly ``one of the richest men in the
West,'' died in 1941, she went to work in the casting department of
the J. Walter Thompson advertising agency. She retired from there
about 25 years ago.
   Miss Dawn is survived by her daughter, Dawn Gruwell Kaufman, and
her son, Charles E. Gruwell, both of New York, five grandsons and
seven great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
