<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Space     08-31 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Space,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Capsule Docks With Orbiting Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviets and the first Afghan in space docked
their Soyuz-TM 6 capsule with the Mir orbiting space station today,
joining two Soviet cosmonauts who have been in space more than
eight months, Tass reported.
   The state-run news agency said the capsule linked up with the
space station at 9:41 a.m. Moscow time (1:41 a.m. EDT).
   ``The cosmonauts feel well,'' Tass said in a brief dispatch.
   The capsule, launched two days ago from the Baikonur Space
Center in Soviet Central Asia, carried a veteran cosmonaut, a
doctor and an Afghan air force pilot.
   Soviet television showed a live transmission of the crew
entering the space station and meeting with the cosmonauts already
on board.
   Afghan cosmonaut Abdul Ahad Mohmand was shown reading portions
of the Koran, the Moslem holy book.
   The cosmonauts who have been aboard Mir for eight months have
been reported in good health, but Dr. Valery Polyakov will stay on
to monitor their health as they try to set an endurance record.
   Tass did not say how long Mohmand and the third new arrival,
Vladimir Lyakhov, would remain aboard the station with its crew.
   Polyakov, an expert on space endurance, is to monitor the health
of Vladimir Titov, 40, and Musa Manarov, 37, who have been in space
since Dec., 21 and are hoping to break a 326-day endurance record
set by Yuri Romanenko.
   Tass said Polyakov had bone marrow removed before the flight.
When he returns to Earth, more marrow is to be removed and the
samples compared.
   Scientists are trying to determine how to counter bone marrow
depletion, which results from prolonged space flight. Polyakov also
will study motion sickness.
   Space officials say the endurance tests are a step toward
determining whether a manned flight to Mars, which they estimate
would take three years, is feasible.
   Mohmand, 29, is to take part in experiments to identify oil, gas
and other mineral deposits in Afghanistan and to predict runoff of
snow and ice in efforts to alleviate water shortages.
   His presence represents efforts by the Kremlin to boost the
prestige of Afghanistan's pro-Soviet government as Soviet troops
withdraw. The Soviets have agreed to withdraw all their troops by
Feb. 15. Half of the 100,000 soldiers have left Afghanistan since
withdrawal began in May.
   The flight is the 47-year-old Lyakhov's third space mission. He
was in space for 175 days in 1979 and took part in a 150-day
mission in 1983.
</TEXT>
