<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesignatedDriver     08-31 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Designated Driver,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard In Pact With TV Networks, Writers To Fight Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime time TV characters this fall will begin
turning down drinks in a coordinated assault on drunken driving
initiated by Harvard University health researchers.
   Make-believe wives will designate make-believe husbands as
non-drinking drivers. Teen-agers who drink will take taxis. And for
the next few years polltakers will be trying to find out if viewers
are coming under the influence of the push for a ``designated
driver.''
   ``The goal of the project is to achieve a fundamental change in
American social norms regarding drinking and driving,'' Jay
Winsten, assistant dean of Harvard's School of Public Health and
director of its Center for Health Communication, said Tuesday night.
   ``In attempting to achieve that change, we're asking the
entertainment, communication and advertising industries to work
with us to add momentum behind changes that are already beginning
to occur in America,'' he said of the Harvard Alcohol Project.
   Winsten said the commitment was made by 13 television studios in
Los Angeles that are responsible for more than 70 percent of prime
time weekly programming on ABC, CBS and NBC.
   The executives pledged to ask their writers and producers to
introduce in their scripts the notion that drinking and driving is
taboo, through devices as simple as having drinkers take taxis or
saying, ``No thanks, I'm driving.''
   Winsten said if the television campaign succeeds, others will be
tried. But drunken driving was the priority, he said, reciting
these statistics: drunken driving kills 24,000 people each year;
studies show as few as two drinks can make a fatal accident twice
as likely; two of five Americans will be victims of a drunken
driver.
   In January, Winsten began meeting with Hollywood executives to
forge the agreements. In April, he won a unanimous endorsement from
the board of the Writers Guild of America-West, whose members write
for prime time TV.
   The networks also agreed to run public service announcements in
December to encourage the ``designated driver'' idea, The New York
Times reported today.
   The New York advertising firm, Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Compton,
has provided advertising research on the designated driver idea,
and the Gallup Organization said it will donate its services to
poll the public to find out whether the TV campaign is working, the
newspaper said.
   Gallup research shows that 78 percent of all drivers would be
willing to serve occasionally as designated drivers.
   Winsten said the campaign will continue for at least three to
five years before its real impact will be known.
   The campaign has precedents, he said. Television networks during
the past year or two have been using their characters to encourage
the use of seatbelts and to try to take the glamour out of alcohol.
But Winsten said he believed this was the first such effort
mobilized by a school of public health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YonkersDeseg     08-31 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Charges to Be Filed if High Court Reinstates Fines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four councilmen refused a third time to
change their votes against a housing desegregation plan, as
requests from them and the city to continue a stay of contempt
fines went to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Unless the Supreme Court takes their side, the defiant
councilmen will be hit with criminal charges, the state agency that
has taken over Yonkers' finances warned Tuesday.
   `It's the city councilmen who are defying the law and putting
the city's financial profile at risk, who are putting all the
citizens of Yonkers at risk,'' said Gail Shaffer, head of the
state's Emergency Financial Control Board.
   The $500-a-day fines against the councilmen, along with
potentially devastating fines against the city that could reach $1
million a day, were imposed by federal Judge Leonard Sand. He found
them in contempt Aug. 2, the day after the council's first 4-3
rejection of the court-ordered plan.
   On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld the contempt finding
but gave Yonkers a week to take the case to the Supreme Court
before reinstating the penalties.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall on Tuesday referred the four
applications from the councilmen and one from the city to the full
Supreme Court, according to a court spokesman who gave no
indication when the court might rule on a stay.
   Only after a stay is granted would the court consider the appeal
of Sand's contempt finding.
   At the City Council's regular meeting Tuesday night, Councilmen
Henry Spallone, Nicholas Longo, Edward Fagan and Peter Chema again
rejected a zoning amendment needed to carry out a housing plan that
the council had accepted last January.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, during a visit to Yonkers, said the city
must ``end its illegal resistance'' to the plan. He added that he
would be willing to meet with the four but would not specify when
that would happen.
   Three of the four said they would be happy to meet with Jackson,
while Spallone said, ``Have him call me.''
   Sand ordered the plan to remedy what he determined in a 1985
ruling to have been 40 years of deliberate segregation in housing
and education in the city.
   The plan calls for 200 low-income public housing units to be
built in the predominantly white east side of Yonkers, with 800
moderate-income apartments to be built throughout the city.
   Unless a stay is granted, the fines, currently suspended, will
be reimposed Friday. The councilmen have paid $3,500 each. The city
has paid $12,700. Its daily payment would resume at $12,800 and
double daily until it reaches $1 million a day, when it will be
capped.
   That would give the city an estimated 70 days until bankruptcy.
   Shaffer said that if the Supreme Court appeal is turned down,
she will notify District Attorney Carl Vergari that the councilmen
are breaking state law by endangering the city's fiscal stability.
   The four already face possible imprisonment as early as Sunday
for contempt.
   ``I feel it is unfortunate that people elected to uphold the law
and defend the law are breaking and defying the law,'' Shaffer said.
   Her remarks came a day after Gov. Mario Cuomo said he would
initiate removal proceedings and urge the councilmen's jailing if
the Supreme Court refused the stay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Chronology     08-31 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Chronology,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology Of Main Political Events Under Pinochet Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the main
political events in Chile since Gen. Augusto Pinochet seized power
in a coup 15 years ago:
   Sept. 11, 1973 _ Pinochet leads the armed forces in a bloody
coup that overthrows President Salvador Allende, a Marxist elected
in 1970. Allende dies in the coup and the new government says he
committed suicide. His supporters say he was killed. A four-men
Military Junta led by Pinochet takes power and represses supporters
of the ousted leftist government. Hundreds of leftists are killed
or disappear after being arrested, thousands are sent to
concentration camps or into exile. Congress is closed and political
activity prohibited.
   June 20, 1974 _ Pinochet becomes supreme chief of the nation,
retaining his post as president of the military junta.
   Oct. 29, 1974 _ Exiled former army commander Gen. Carlos Prats
and his wife are killed by a bomb in Buenos Aires, Argentina, and
involvement by Chilean secret police is suspected. The same charge
arises when an exiled former foreign minister, Orlando Letelier, is
killed in a Sept 21, 1976, bombing in Washington. A U.S. court
indicts three high-ranking chilean army officers in the case, but
Chile refuses to extradite them.
   July 9, 1977 _ Pinochet outlines a far-reaching political and
institutional program calling for the military to remain in power
at least 11 more years.
   Jan. 4, 1978 _ Pinochet, faced with growing international and
domestic comdemnation of human rights abuse, calls a national
referendum to seek support from the Chilean people. He wins the
ballot, but opposition leaders charge widespread fraud.
   June. 20, 1978 _ Air force commander Gen. Gustavo Leigh, a
member of the military junta, publicly challenges Pinochet's
authority by disagreeing with the government political program.
Pinochet ousts Leigh from the junta and forces him into retirement.
   Sept. 11, 1980 _ Pinochet wins approval in a referendum for a
new constitution that confirms his presidency until March 11, 1989.
It also allows him to seek a new period of rule until 1997. The
opposition again charges massive fraud in the ballot.
   March 11, 1981 _ The new constitution goes into effect.
   May 11, 1983 _ Amid a deep economic crisis, the opposition
stages the first of a series of mass protests against the
government that left hundreds of dead and thousands arrested.
   Sept. 6, 1986 _ Pinochet survives an assassination attempt by a
leftist urban guerrilla commando. Five of his bodyguards were
killed and 11 wounded when the presidential motorcade is ambushed
on a mountain road outside Santiago.
   Aug. 30, 1988 _ The military junta nominates Pinochet as the
sole candidate in an Oct. 5 presidential referendum, sparking
widespread protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-31 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo today, while share prices fell back.
   The dollar opened at 134.93 yen and inched up to close the day
at 134.97 yen, up 0.58 yen from Tuesday's close of 134.39 yen. It
moved between 134.80 yen and 135.13 yen, with spot trading
estimated at $5.9 billion.
   ``The dollar rose because investors started selling the yen,
realizing that interest rates in Japan have become the lowest,''
said a foreign exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
   ``The rise in interest rates in Europe last week is finally
affecting us,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 132.55 points Tuesday, lost 145.70
points, or 0.53 percent, closing the day at 27,365.95.
   Although the market opened higher, the Nikkei index then
reversed direction and lost its earlier gains.
   The weakening yen was the main cause of the stock market's
decline, a trader with a major securities firm in Tokyo said.
   ``Investors got discouraged by the weakening yen, and the
trading was very thin,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. Volume on the market's first section was estimated at
400 million shares.
   Stock prices were lower almost across the board except for a few
high-tech issues, such as Sony and Matsushita, which some investors
bought shortly before the closing of the market, the trader said.
</TEXT>
