<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContinentalSentencings     08-31 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Sentencings,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Continental Illinois Officials Sentenced To Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two ex-bank officers sentenced to prison
for crimes that contributed to the near-collapse of Continental
Illinois National Bank and Trust Co. held his head and wept as he
apologized for the people he had hurt.
   Sentenced Tuesday were John R. Lytle, a former Continental vice
president, and William G. Patterson, the head of energy lending at
the now-defunct Penn Square Bank of Oklahoma City.
   Lytle, 53, and Patterson, 38, pleaded guilty June 30 to one
criminal charge each for a scheme in which Lytle allegedly took
kickbacks in exchange for arranging to have Continental buy
millions of dollars in risky energy loans from Penn Square.
   Penn Square failed in 1982, and Continental Illinois nearly
collapsed two years later after an unprecedented run on its
deposits. Continental was kept afloat by a $4.5 billion government
bailout.
   U.S. District Judge Milton Shadur sentenced Lytle to 3{ years in
prison, despite Lytle's pleas for probation. Shadur sentenced
Patterson to a 2-year term. The maximum sentence allowed under
their plea bargain was five years.
   Patterson, who held his head and choked back tears as he spoke
in his own defense, said he was sorry for his actions and was
concerned about his family. He had sought a sentence of probation
and community service.
   ``I'm sorry for the people in Chicago and Oklahoma,'' he said.
``I think of that a lot.''
   Patterson's attorney, Burck Bailey, said after the sentencing,
``We're relieved to have it behind us.''
   Lytle, testifying before his sentencing, said he accepted
responsibility for his actions. He asked the judge to sentence him
to no more than six months in prison and assign him to work with
the poor on Chicago's West Side.
   But the judge said Lytle seemed, at times, ``unwilling to
confront the realities'' of what he had done.
   ``You allowed your conduct as a bank officer ... to be driven
impermissibly by your desire for personal benefits,'' Shadur said.
   Lytle pleaded guilty to misapplication of bank funds, while
Patterson pleaded guilty to a charge that he aided and abetted
Lytle. The pleas came two months after a trial of the two ended
with a deadlocked jury.
   Prosecutors said Patterson had manipulated Lytle and a third
man, Oklahoma drilling contractor Jere Sturgis, in schemes to save
his own failing bank. Sturgis was acquitted of wire fraud charges.
   Defense attorneys contended that Continental Illinois was
saddled with the troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive
lending policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
