<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0504 08-31 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0560</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS obit on Pates; a PM separate on Prude moved as a0466 and
on Dawn as a0478.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Hazel Dawn</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazel Dawn, whose singing and acting career in
the early 1900s included a starring role in the original ``Ziegfeld
Follies,'' died Sunday. She was 98.
   She began her career in London musical comedies and made her
Broadway stage debut in 1911 in a hit musical, ``The Pink Lady.''
   Miss Dawn went on to become a celebrated singer and actress
until her marriage in 1927 to a Montana mining engineer, Charles
Gruwell, after which she largely gave up her career.
   After Gruwell, reportedly one of the richest men in the West,
died in 1941, she went to work in the casting department of the J.
Walter Thompson advertising agency. She retired about 25 years ago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Walter Foy Prude</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Foy Prude, who helped direct the careers
of violinist Isaac Stern, opera singer Marian Anderson, pianist
Artur Rubinstein and others during his 40 years in concert
management, died Monday. He was 78.
   Prude, who lived in Manhattan with his wife, choreographer Agnes
de Mille, died of heart failure after a long bout with emphysema.
   He began his work in management in the late 1930s in Chicago,
overseeing dancer-choreographer Martha Graham's career.
   After serving as an Air Force officer in Europe during World II,
he joined Hurok Concerts in 1945. He remained with the organization
for 31 years, becoming a vice president.
   In 1976, he joined ICM Artists as a vice president and later
became executive vice president. He retired in 1981.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Durey Peterson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Durey Peterson, a former scientist with
Upjohn Co. who helped develop an inexpensive production process for
cortisone, died Sunday at age 79.
   Peterson teamed with other scientists to use microorganisms to
produce the steroid, used to treat a variety of infections. Before
that development, cortisone had to be extracted from animals'
adrenal glands, an expensive process.
   He held 74 patents and introduced the use of a cold hair-setting
process that became the Toni home permanent. Peterson worked for
the pharmaceutical company for nearly 30 years before retiring in
1975.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Richardson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George S. Richardson, an engineer who designed
some of the most prominent bridges in Pittsburgh, died Friday of a
heart attack. He was 92.
   Richardson's designs included the Fort Pitt and Fort Duquesne
bridges and numerous other spans over Pittsburgh's Ohio,
Monongahela and Allegheny rivers.
   In all, Richardson designed 20 major bridges and hundreds of
smaller ones.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gordon Pates</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALNUT CREEK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former San Francisco Chronicle
executive editor Gordon Pates, who won awards from the National
Headliners Club during his career, died Monday of cancer. He was 71.
   Pates, who started his career as a copy boy with the Chronicle
in 1939, retired from the paper in 1979.
   He was honored by the club in 1948 for outstanding domestic news
reporting for two articles about racial prejudice.
   Pates, a University of Washington graduate, was managing editor
at the Chronicle for 23 years and executive editor for two. He
served in World War II as a sergeant in the Army Air Force.
</TEXT>
