<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-31 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Drench Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A sluggish cold front dumped heavy rain over portions of the
Southeast today, causing some street flooding, while the northern
half of the nation remained dry.
   The heaviest rain was reported at Columbia, S.C., where more
than 2 inches fell in an hour and a total of 4 inches fell in three
hours.
   Galveston, Texas, also was drenched this morning when 1{ inches
of rain fell in 45 minutes, flooding streets.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included more than 2{ inches in Tampa, Fla., and more than 2 inches
at Savannah, Ga.
   In the Southwest, showers and thunderstorms diminished Tuesday
night. The northern half of the nation was dry this morning.
   Tropical storm Uleki became Hurricane Uleki on Tuesday night.
Uleki was 385 miles south of Hilo, on the island of Hawaii, and was
moving to the west and northwest at 10-15 mph. The present course
will keep the hurricane well to the south of Hawaii.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the eastern Carolinas across Georgia and Florida to the
central Gulf Coast region, and over extreme southern Texas;
scattered showers and thunderstorms from western Texas across the
southern Rockies to the mountains and deserts of southern
California; widely scattered thunderstorms over portions of South
Dakota and Minnesota; smoky skies over Wyoming and southeast
Montana due to forest fires; and mostly sunny skies in the rest of
the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s along portions
of the Pacific Coast, and from the Great Lakes region across the
upper Ohio Valley and the northern and central Appalachians to New
England; in the 90s over the central and southern intermountain
region; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest and inland
valleys of California; in the 90s over much of the central and
southern Plains and central Florida; and in the 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 93 at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 foggy; Boston 62 fair; Buffalo 56 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 72 rain; Cincinnati 55 fair; Cleveland 52 fair;
Detroit 55 fair; Miami 79 fair; New York 63 fair; Philadelphia 61
fair; Pittsburgh 55 fair; Portland, Maine 56 fair; Washington 61
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 69 fair; Denver 67
partly cloudy; Des Moines 63 fair; Indianapolis 56 fair; Kansas
City 69 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 61 fair; Nashville 62 fair; New
Orleans 78 foggy; St. Louis 66 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 partly cloudy; Anchorage 51 cloudy; Las
Vegas 83 fair; Los Angeles 62 foggy; Phoenix 85 fair; Salt Lake
City 70 fair; San Diego 68 fair; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 59
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 fair; Toronto 48 fair.
</TEXT>
