<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-31 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Modest Trading, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in European trading this morning
after senior Japanese officials said their country is leaving its
base rate unchanged in keeping with international policy
commitments.
   Gold prices fell because of the stronger dollar, dealers said.
   Foreign exchange dealers predicted a relatively quiet session as
the market waits for Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures.
   Traders in Italy said they expected the dollar to register
further gains against the Japanese yen because of the decision not
to raise interest rates.
   ``It's logical that if interest rates rise in the U.S. and most
of Europe and not in Japan, then the yen has to suffer. The only
surprise is that the effect was delayed,'' said a trader with an
Italian commercial bank in Milan.
   The trader cautioned, however, that the dollar's rise against
the yen could be blocked by profit-taking or fears of intervention
by the Bank of Japan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.58 yen to a closing 134.97 yen. Later, in
London, it rose to 136.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with the rates late
Tuesday:
   _1.8745 West German marks, up from 1.8678
   _1.5828 Swiss francs, up from 1.5760
   _6.3635 French francs, up from 6.3385
   _2.1180 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080
   _1,391.60 Italian lire, up from 1,387.50
   _1.2395 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2386
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.683 from $1.691 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.00 a troy ounce. At
midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $426.35. Both were down from Tuesday's late
bid of $428.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price for gold was $427.10, down from $428.50
late Tuesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.60 to close at $429.96.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.45 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.55.
</TEXT>
