<DOCNO> AP880831-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Khomeini     08-31 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Khomeini,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Says Persian Gulf War Not Over Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini declared that
Iran's war with Iraq is not over and accused the United States and
the Soviet Union of plotting against the Islamic Republic, Tehran
Radio reported.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati, meanwhile, accused
Iraq of seeking to wreck peace talks in Geneva by raising
``unnecessary or out-of-place issues.'' Both men spoke Tuesday.
   In Baghdad, the Al-Thawra daily, mouthpiece of the ruling Baath
Socialist Party, charged that Iran's insistence it share the vital
Shatt-al-Arab waterway with Iraq was hampering the negotiations.
   It accused Tehran of seeking to string out the talks to ``buy
time'' to rebuild its military forces.
   Iran and Iraq have been observing a cease-fire since Aug. 20.
The war began in September 1980.
   Khomeini's comments came as the Geneva talks under U.N. auspices
were suspended because of differences over troop withdrawals and
Shatt-al-Arab, Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said Khomeini urged Iranians
to man the front lines in the now-dormant Persian Gulf war, but
also called for a national effort in Iran's post-war reconstruction.
   ``We must take it that we are still at war,'' the 88-year-old
religious patriarch declared.
   He added: ``Our enemy, be it big enemies such as America and the
Soviet Union or their surrogates such as (Iraqi President) Saddam
(Hussein) and others, are constantly plotting because they have
seen how Islam has become a major force in the world. We must never
lose sight of that fact.''
   Iran's state-run television network, also monitored in Nicosia,
showed Khomeini sitting on a sofa at his home in the north Tehran
suburb of Jamaran meeting with President Ali Khamenei, Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi and other senior figures.
   Khomeini noted: ``It is possible that the enemy pretends now
that the problem has been solved. But it's not true. People who are
against us still exist and their numbers are large. We should not
trust anything.''
   Khomeini said that reconstruction of Iran's missile-battered
cities and damaged industrial centers could not be accomplished in
a short time.
   ``They pounded us for eight years and destroyed our cities. We
must persevere so that, God willing, we may be able to do the job
in a few years ... The people should cooperate and bring all their
power to bear on this major issue.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, said in a commentary that Baghdad's claim of sovereignty
over the 120-mile Shatt-al-Arab waterway, the southern border
between the two countries before the war, was the main stumbling
block in the Geneva talks.
   The Iraqis have said they consider the 1975 Algiers agreement,
which drew the boundary down the middle of the waterway, as invalid
and claim the frontier should be on the eastern, Iranian, bank.
   Saddam tore up the Algiers document during a television
appearance five days before the Iraqi Army invaded Iran on Sept.
22, 1980.
   Iran insists that the Algiers agreement is still valid.
</TEXT>
