<HEAD>Jackson And Koch Move To Set Aside Bad Feelings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Meeting scheduled for 12:30 p.m.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson and Mayor Edward I. Koch,
invoking Democratic unity in November, moved to set aside bad
feelings stemming from Koch's criticism of the former presidential
candidate in the New York primary.
   The two were scheduled to meet today at the New York City office
of Gov. Mario Cuomo, who arranged the meeting apparently to unify
their support for the Democratic presidential nominee,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   Koch, noting that Dukakis has slipped in the polls since the
Republican convention, said Tuesday, ``We've got to get that surge
back.
   ``In fact, it may very well be that the surge will start with
the meeting that Jesse Jackson and I have tomorrow if we jointly
come out of that meeting united,'' the mayor said. But, he added,
``we have issues that separate us, no question about it.''
   Jackson, during a visit Tuesday to homeless people maintaining a
vigil at City Hall Park, said there would be no discussion at
today's meeting about Koch's strong criticism of him in April's New
York primary.
   Koch strongly endorsed Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee in the
Democratic presidential primary and just as strongly opposed
Jackson, suggesting that Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jackson because of his support for Palestinian self-determination
in the Middle East. Blacks all over the country reacted with
outrage, as did many Jews.
   On Monday, Jackson said that although the mayor ``operated
beneath the dignity of that office,'' the need for Democratic unity
in November overrode other considerations.
