<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steroids     08-31 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steroids,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Warns of Steroid Addiction in Athletes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A 6 p.m. EDT embargo has been broken. The story is for use
now.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Athletes who take high doses of steroids may risk
addiction similar to narcotic abuse, doctors warn.
   In a letter in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine,
doctors report a case of steroid dependence in a man who regularly
took four kinds of steroids.
   The 23-year-old body-builder told doctors he could not stop
taking anabolic steroids without experiencing withdrawal symptoms,
depression and disabling fatigue. He said he sometimes felt
uncontrollably violent, paranoid and suicidal.
   After a week off steroids, he told doctors that he couldn't bear
his depression, fatigue and drug craving and intended to resume
taking the drugs.
   ``Some of the clinical features of this patient resemble those
frequently observed in cases of opioid dependence,'' the doctors
wrote.
   The letter was written by Drs. Forest Tennant of Community
Health Projects Medical Group in West Covina, Calif., David L.
Black of Vanderbilt Child and Adolescent Psychiatric Hospital in
Nashville and Robert O. Voy of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
   Other researchers have also pointed out that people who abuse
steroids may suffer hallucinations, delusions, manic episodes and
other temporary mental illness.
   According to one estimate, as many as 1 million athletes in the
United States may be using steroids to build up their muscles. The
drugs retard the tendency of muscle to break down.
   Steroids can also cause a variety of other side effects,
including liver damage, sterility and testicular shrinking.
</TEXT>
