<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan     08-31 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil War, Food Shortages, Flooding Starving Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people are fleeing civil war
and food shortages in the southern Sudan, and many die during the
trek northward or in flood-ravaged refugee camps, an opposition
party said.
   An Irish relief official says millions of people face starvation
in the south.
   A statement issued by the Union of Sudanese African Parties, a
grouping of southern political parties, did not specify how many
people who fled the fierce fighting and famine in the south were
dying.
   ``I would not say by the thousands, but they are dying,'' said a
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anomymity.
   The statement quoted the Bishop of el-Obeid, capital of
Kordofan, 225 miles southwest of Khartoum, as saying people were
flocking by the hundreds every day asking for food and help to
continue their journey northward.
   ``This shows you how the food shortages and the long journey,
which in some cases is done on foot, can kill women, children and
old people,'' the statement said.
   The Rev. Aengus Finucane, director of the Dublin-based aid
agency Concern, called for airlifts of food to regions of the
country made inaccessible by the 5-year-old war.
   ``Two million people are facing death from the ravages of war
and starvation,'' Finucane said at Dublin Airport after returning
from a two-week visit to Khartoum, Sudan's capital.
   Trains carrying thousands of ``living skeletons'' were arriving
in the north every few days, and hundreds of other refugees trekked
on foot to camps, he said.
   About 40 people per day were dying at refugee camps at El
Meriam, 500 miles from Khartoum, said Finucane. His organization
has 34 workers in Sudan.
   In 1983, the Sudan People's Liberation Army _ made up mainly of
Christians and animists _ took up arms against the Moslem majority
government in the north. The SPLA claims to control 90 percent of
the countryside in the south, with the army in command only in the
major cities.
   Fighting between the army and the rebels has forced an estimated
820,000 southerners to leave their crops and cattle behind and seek
shelter around the cities in Sudan and neighboring Ethiopia, where
they become totally dependent on relief food for their livelihood.
   In Khartoum, about 400,000 refugees live in extreme poverty in
tin and canvas shacks around the city. These shantytowns were among
the hardest hit areas in the worst floods in the country's history
this month that sent the Nile River over its banks.
   The floods have left 1.5 million people homeless, at least 91
dead, tens of thousands of homes destroyed and some of Sudan's most
fertile farmland inundated.
</TEXT>
