<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeggarHoax     08-31 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beggar Hoax,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Happy Hoaxer' Strikes Again; Miami Herald, BBC Duped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prankster who specializes in duping the news
media has struck again, inventing a tale of a school for beggars
that was reported by The Miami Herald, New York magazine and the
British Broadcasting Corp.
   The Herald on Sunday published a story about Omar Rockford's
school for panhandlers in New York, where beggars are taught to
trick people out of their money.
   There is no school, the newspaper reported today. Alan Abel,
also known as ``the Happy Hoaxer,'' posed as Omar and got a few
actor friends to play beggar-students.
   ``I do it to shake up the natives,'' Abel, 62, said Tuesday
after confirming the hoax from his home in Westport, Conn.
``Between the latest ax murders and hostages being taken, it
provides levity in the news and a social commentary on the poor.''
   His Omar the beggar scam isn't new. Last year, Abel duped a
Newsday reporter into writing a detailed story about it, with
pictures. The Herald and the BBC heard of Omar in an Aug. 29 cover
story about beggars in New York magazine.
   The Omar School is listed in the telephone book, and someone
purporting to be an answering service took the calls. Abel showed
up for the Herald interview with an array of news clippings about
his top ``graduates.''
   Abel's scams go back to the 1950s with a widely reported bogus
campaign to clothe horses. ``A nude horse is a rude horse,'' he
said.
   He engineered a mass swoon-in on the ``Donahue'' show, a hoax he
later said was sponsored by FAINT _ the Fight Against Idiotic
Neurotic TV.
   He once got The New York Times to run his premature obituary. He
said he ``died'' in Utah while scouting scenes for his horror movie
_ ``Who's Going to Bite Your Neck, My Dear, When All of My Teeth
Are Gone?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
