<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GunNote     08-31 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gun Note,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suicide Note Makes Case For Gun Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who killed himself with a pistol
he bought less than a week earlier said in a suicide note ``it's
actually scary'' how easy it is to obtain a handgun in Florida, his
mother says.
   Robert Edward Park, 31, who suffered from depression and had
been disfigured in an auto accident, shot himself in a Marietta,
Ga., hotel last week after mailing the note, dated Aug. 22, to his
mother.
   Park had left his Boca Raton home for Marietta after buying the
gun, said his mother, Elsie Banting.
   Mrs. Banting said Monday she was sure he bought the weapon
within a week of his suicide. She added that showed the need for
gun control.
   ``I'm hoping people will read about the death and pay attention
and get angry,'' she said. ``I think it's terrible.''
   Park was critically injured in a 1984 accident that severed an
ear and broke his jaw in eight places. Reconstructive surgery
helped, but he still was depressed, family members said. He was a
waiter at the time of his death.
   ``I found out very recently how simple it is to buy a gun in
Florida,'' Park wrote, according to his mother. ``It's actually
scary. No wonder the crime rate is so high. This may be an
interesting case for gun control.''
   Last year Florida reduced to two days ``cooling-off'' periods of
up to a few weeks for buying a gun and eliminated other
restrictions on handgun ownership. Critics, including police
agencies, say the change has led to increased violence.
   Clark had been arrested twice for drunken driving and was facing
a court appearance when he disappeared. He also attempted suicide
previously, slashing his wrists with a meat cleaver, said his
brother-in-law, Timothy Babbitt.
</TEXT>
