<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0445 08-31 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis And Aides Attack Bush On Judgment, Iran-Contra Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Dukakis campaign chairman's remarks
today. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, He spent.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has resurrected the Iran-Contra
scandal as a campaign issue against George Bush, and the
Massachusetts governor's top adviser said today Bush had yet to
explain his role in the arms-for-hostages affair.
   ``His role and participation in Iran-Contra and exchange of arms
with the Ayatollah (Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran) for hostages is a
very serious issue,'' Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas said
on ``CBS This Morning.'' ``He hasn't answered that question.''
   Brountas said ``there's a very serious issue of George Bush's
judgment. When he was supposed to be in charge of fighting the
battle against terrorism ... he apparently endorsed a decision ...
to trade arms with the ayatollah for hostages, which happens to be
one of the most disastrous events in foreign policy history.''
   Dukakis on Tuesday questioned whether Bush's failure to block
the arms deal showed he lacked the judgment to be president.
Dukakis noted that Bush was head of an anti-terrorism task force
that shortly before the 1985 arms deal with Iran issued a report
warning against concessions to terrorist nations.
   The Democratic presidential nominee was spending most of today
at the Massachusetts Statehouse before flying to California for
three days of campaigning in Western states.
   He spent Tuesday in Western Massachusetts on a gubernatorial
trip, but took time to launch his harshest attack on Bush to date
and declare that he was going to respond aggressively to Republican
criticism.
   Dukakis, in a meeting with area editors and later at a news
conference, noted Bush's position as head of an anti-terrorism task
force that shortly before the 1985 arms deal with Iran issued a
report warning against concessions to terrorist nations.
   ``The president and the vice president and a number of other
people, over the opposition of the secretary of state and the
secretary of defense by the way, proceeded to do precisely what
that commission said you should never do,'' Dukakis said.
   ``How can you possibly sit there and do nothing while we traded
arms to a terrorist nation?'' he asked.
   At the news conference, Dukakis cited a new book by Maine Sens.
William Cohen and George Mitchell in which they said the Republican
nominee appeared to have endorsed the arms-for-hostages deal.
   ``Making tough decisions is a test of leadership,'' Dukakis
said. ``George Bush endorsed the decision to sell arms to Iran and
in doing so he failed that test.''
   Cohen, a Republican, and Mitchell, a Democrat, were members of
the congressional Iran-Contra investigating panel. Mitchell was
visiting with Dukakis today.
   Dukakis, asked to respond to Bush's charges that he was too
willing to make concession to the Soviets in arms negotiations,
said the American people should match his record of making tough
decisions with that of the vice president.
   Dukakis mentioned the Iran-Contra affair, the Reagan
administration's dealings with Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega and Bush's support of deposed Philippine President
Ferdinand Marcos in the early 1980s.
   ``I would be very concerned about someone with that kind of
judgment negotiating with the Soviet Union,'' Dukakis said.
   The Massachusetts governor also returned Bush's rhetorical
salvos that Dukakis was soft on defense, and reiterated his
opposition to the Star Wars anti-missile system, two new
supercarrier task forces and rail-based MX missiles.
   ``Mr. Bush says he wants them all,'' Dukakis said. ``You can't
have them all, not if you're serious about providing the resources
our conventional forces need and not if you're serious about
getting that deficit down.''
   Dukakis, characterizing Bush as irresponsible on fiscal matters,
mentioned Bush's support of the ``exotic'' weapons systems,
increased education spending, a tax-credit for child care and a $40
billion cut in the capital gains tax.
   ``That is not a responsible approach to the basic fiscal
problems, or for that matter the national security problems, which
face our country,'' the Democratic nominee said.
   Dukakis also lashed out against Bush's record on crime.
   ``What's the Bush record? What's the Dukakis record? I don't
know what the Bush record is,'' Dukakis said. ``It's a blank. On
the rare occasions when the vice president has been asked to do
something on this subject, it's been a failure.''
   Dukakis said he wished the campaign rhetoric was focused more on
major issues but he adopted a more aggressive stance against GOP
attacks, which have included questions about Dukakis' patriotism
and jokes about his height.
   ``If it continues, you have to respond,'' he said. ``I think
that's unfortunate, but I think it's very clear what kind of
campaign the Republicans are running and I think we're going to
have to deal with it.''
</TEXT>
