<2ND_LINE>PM-Time Con,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Posed As Executive's Son Sent to Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A con man accused of posing as the son of a
Time Inc. executive to get a hotel room and VIP treatment was
sentenced to three years in prison.
   ``Most of the criminals I've dealt with are stupid, but not this
guy,'' Assistant District Attorney Jim Costello said of 29-year-old
David Lee Geiken of Gothenburg, Neb. ``He showed real brains and
intelligence.''
   Geiken accepted a plea bargain in which he pleaded guilty to
defrauding an innkeeper.
   Geiken told the San Francisco Chronicle he was in Los Angeles in
May when he decided on conning the magazine. He said a telephone
call to a Time Inc. operator provided him with the name of chairman
J. Richard Munro.
   He phoned Time offices in San Francisco and said Munro's son
needed a plane ticket from Los Angeles to San Francisco, spending
money and ``a nice room.''
   He received the ticket, a room at an elegant hotel and $400 in
cash. A chauffered limousine was waiting when he arrived in San
Francisco.
   Geiken served more than four years in prison for obtaining a
yacht and crew by pretending to be the son of the chief executive
of 20th Century Studios.
</TEXT>
