<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-US     08-31 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam To Resume Joint Search For Missing Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam told the United States it is
willing to resume joint searches for American servicemen missing in
the Vietnam War.
   The decision was revealed in an Aug. 27 letter from Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach to retired Gen. John W. Vessey, a special
U.S. presidential envoy. A text of the letter, carried Tuesday by
Radio Hanoi, was seen today in Bangkok.
   Thach told Vessey in an Aug. 3 letter that Vietnam was
temporarily suspending full cooperation because of what he called
America's ``hostile policy'' toward Vietnam. Thach cited Assistant
Secretary of State Gaston Sigur's testimony before a congressional
committee in July in which Sigur urged the continued isolation of
Vietnam.
   Vessey, President Reagan's envoy on humanitarian issues relating
to Vietnam, replied to Thach two days later that Sigur's testimony
merely reflected the U.S. administration's ``longstanding viewpoint
on relations with Vietnam.''
   He said the United States would continue implementing previous
agreements with Vietnam and its humanitarian aid.
   Thach replied in his Aug. 27 letter that the U.S. ``declaration
that it will make the normalization of bilateral relations
conditional upon the settlement of the MIA issues is at variance
with the agreement between ... (Vessey) and myself.''
   But he said settlement of humanitarian issues ``should be
separated from political issues.''
   ``With the desire that the U.S. government will adopt a suitable
attitude ... the Vietnamese side agrees to let the U.S. side
participate in joint investigation and survey activities as
concerns the issue of American MIAs and is prepared to hold
meetings of specialists from the two sides to discuss specific
plans from 9 to 12 September 1988,'' Thach wrote.
   Thach and Vessey agreed in August 1987 that Vietnam would
accelerate its accounting of nearly 1,800 Americans listed as
missing in action, or MIA, in the Vietnam War, and the United
States would give Vietnam humanitarian aid.
   Thach told Vessey in July that Vietnam would try to resolve 70
top priority MIA cases by the end of this year, and welcomed joint
excavations and other searches for remains until October. There
have been no joint excavations since the first was conducted in
late 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
