<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GeorgiaElection     08-31 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Georgia Election,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Lawmakers Fall To Runoff Challengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 32-year-old political newcomer has won the
Republican nomination to challenge Democratic Rep. George ``Buddy''
Darden for a northwestern Georgia seat, while two state legislators
lost runoff elections.
   Cobb County businessman Robert Lamutt defeated Roswell planner
Kevin Johns for the GOP nod to run against Darden in the 7th
District, which includes Atlanta's northwestern suburbs, in
November. Darden was unopposed in Tuesday's primary.
   The unofficial vote, with returns from all 207 precincts was:
Lamutt, 6,220 votes, or 52 percent; Johns, 5,691 votes, or 48
percent.
   State Rep. Ken Workman, a DeKalb County Democrat, lost 938-864
to Decatur lawyer Thurbert Baker, according to unofficial results.
It was Workman's first bid for re-election following charges, later
dropped, that he beat his wife. Baker faces Republican Hugh Wright
in November.
   Another incumbent, freshman state Rep. Ron Pittman, a Gwinnett
County Republican, lost to businessman Keith Breedlove 1,261 to
1,142, according to unofficial results. Breedlove will take on
Democrat Pat Brown in November.
   A Fulton County legislative race raised the possibility of a
father-daughter pairing in the Georgia House.
   Cynthia Ann McKinney, daughter of Rep. Billy McKinney, defeated
AFL-CIO state President Herb Mabry. The unofficial vote, in returns
from all but one of 281 precincts: Ms. McKinney, 15,163, or 53
percent; Mabry, 13,509, or 47 percent.
   In the only statewide runoff on Tuesday's ballot, former state
Sen. Bobby Rowan captured the Democratic nomination for a seat on
Georgia's utility-regulating Public Service Commission despite
Election Day reports that Georgia Power Co. managers were pressured
to contribute to his campaign.
   Rowan defeated state Rep. Cathey Steinberg.
</TEXT>
