<HEAD>Four Survivors of West German Disaster Arrive In U.S. For
Treatment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with American family also en
route to Texas for treatment; Picks up 5th graf, `The four ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three American servicemen and an
Italian soldier burned during an air show crash in West Germany
that killed 49 arrived here today in critical condition, officials
said.
   The four were taken off a C-141 cargo plane at Kelly Air Force
Base after a flight from Ramstein, West Germany. They were taken to
the burn unit at Brooke Army Medical Center.
   Today in Landstuhl, West Germany, an American couple and their
2-year-old-son were put on a flight to Kelly for treatment of burns
and other injuries suffered in the air show crash, an Army
spokeswoman said.
   Jeffrey McCanch, his wife, Tammy, and their son, Jeffrey Jr.,
had been undergoing treatment at Landstuhl Army hospital. The boy
was in serious condition, but the parents were in good condition,
spokeswoman Marie Shaw said.
   Ms. Shaw did not know the McCanch's hometown.
   The four who arrived early today suffered second- and
third-degree burns and would be listed in critical condition until
their injuries could be assessed by specialists, said Ray Dery, a
Brooke spokesman.
   The four were identified as Air Force Master Sgt. Stephen Hull,
32, stationed at Kelly Air Force Base; Army 1st Lt. Kim Strader,
30, of Salt Lake City; and Army Pfc. Myron Riggs, 24, of
Pittsburgh; and Anderea DelaRosa, 33, a sergeant major.
   Hull, of Covina, Calif., is assigned to the Air Force
Broadcasting Service, and was in West Germany as part of a tour
visiting broadcasting units in Europe, said Kelly spokeswoman Phebe
Brown.
   The victims were among the hundreds injured Sunday when three
Italian jets crashed during an air show at Ramstein Air Force Base.
   On Monday, a five-member team of burn specialists from Brooke
flew to West Germany to help treat the victims, and decided to
bring the four to the United States.
   The 40-bed burn unit at Brooke is staffed by 240 physicians,
nurses and support personnel.
   Sailors injured during attacks in the Persian Gulf during the
last 15 months were among those treated at the center, which is run
by the Army Institute of Surgical Research.
