<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Eastern-Unions     08-31 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Unions,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Union Chief Says Eastern Sought To Break Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' stalled plan to lay off
4,000 workers is part of a broader Eastern effort to ``break the
unions'' and gradually dismember the airline, the president of the
Air Line Pilots Association charged today.
   Henry Duffy, whose group represents most unionized U.S. pilots,
expressed satisfaction with a federal judge's ruling Tuesday
blocking Eastern from carrying out the layoffs.
   The financially strapped carrier said it would file an emergency
appeal of the ruling.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker also ruled that Eastern
could go ahead with plans to eliminate service to 14 cities and
close its Kansas City, Mo., hub.
   ``It's an important decision because what the judge found was a
series of transactions that Eastern has been going through (that)
hasn't been for legitimate business purposes,'' Duffy said on
NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``It's been to break the unions.''
   NBC said Eastern declined an invitation to appear with Duffy on
the program.
   On Tuesday the Miami-based carrier issued a statement by its
president, Phil Bakes, calling the court ruling ``gravely wrong''
and saying it would appeal on grounds that any business must be
allowed to ``prune money-losing operations.''
   ``We must be able to take prudent, although sometimes painful,
measures in the best interests of the company and our employees,''
Bakes said.
   Asked if his union believed Eastern's cutbacks in service and
proposed layoffs were aimed at eventually doing away with the
airline altogether, Duffy said:
   ``As a matter of fact, that's what the judge found. He found
they've been siphoning assets off and transferring them over to
Continental (Airlines).''
   Both Eastern and Continental are subsidiaries of Texas Air Corp.
   In his ruling, Parker wrote that Texas Air, which bought Eastern
in 1986, ``has exerted every effort to curb union influence at
Eastern ...'' He also wrote that Eastern's management had
contributed to the carrier's financial instability through a series
of decisions that led to ``a number of questionable loans and
questionable ventures.''
</TEXT>
