<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     08-31 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Confirm Sending Fighter Jets Into Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman today confirmed that
Soviet-based fighter aircraft were used recently to aid Afghan
ground troops as they battled for control of the northern
Afghanistan city of Kunduz.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov denied, however,
a U.S. charge that the action violated the Geneva accords on an
Afghan settlement.
   He told reporters at a regular briefing that the Kremlin
responded to an ``urgent situation'' when it sent the aircraft.
   Gerasimov denied another U.S. allegation that the Kremlin had
sent troops back to Kunduz, about 30 miles from the Soviet border,
after recently withdrawing them.
   Under the Geneva accords signed earlier this year, the Soviets
have pulled out half of their 100,000 soldiers from Afghanistan
since May 15, and the remainder is scheduled to be withdrawn by
Feb. 15.
   Phyllis Oakley, U.S. State Department spokeswoman, said earlier
this week that the Soviets had directed aircraft into Afghanistan
and moved some Red Army troops into Kunduz from elsewhere within
the country. She said the dispatch of aircraft from the Soviet
Union was a violation of the Geneva accords.
   Gerasimov said the dispatch of aircraft was justified.
   ``When the Soviet troops left and part of the troops were still
there, counterrevolutionary, anti-governmental gangs began to
operate, so countermeasures were required,'' he said.
   He said he could not give specifics of the operations, declining
to say how many fighters were dispatched to the area and whether
the aircraft carried out any bombing. But he said the aircraft were
there mainly as support.
   Gerasimov did not respond directly when asked whether the Afghan
government requested the assistance, or whether the Soviets
volunteered it.
   ``When in the area around Kunduz, a critical situation emerged,
then with the consent of the Afghan government, aircraft were used
from Soviet territory for rendering urgent support including a
Soviet unit fighting counterrevolutionary formations,'' Gerasimov
said.
   The Soviets have persistently accused Pakistan of violating the
Geneva accords.
   The spokesman today reinterated the list of Soviet complaints,
accusing Pakistan of permitting guerrillas to operate bases inside
the Pakistani border and blaming the United States for its
involvement.
   ``Nothing of this kind would have happened had Pakistan, with
the support of the United States, not supplied arms to the rebels,
including advisers,'' he said.
   The United States has said it will continue supplying Pakistan
with weapons for the rebels as long as the Soviets continue arming
the Kabul government.
   Gerasimov said the rebels conducted a bloody fight in and around
Kunduz.
   ``They burned down three hospitals; they destroyed all
governmental institutions, they destroyed several mosques, those
freedom fighters. They blew up the power supply station, so Kunduz
remained without electric power. They killed officials, including
members of their family. They killed traders, merchants and they
took 200 schoolgirls and college students and away from Kunduz,''
Gerasimov said.
   Rebel commanders have said their strategy is to take the
provincial seats before an assault on Kabul, the capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
