<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bennett     08-31 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bennett,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Says Fourth Graders Faulter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of Education William Bennett said
today that American school children get off to a good start but
start falling behind their foreign counterparts in fourth grade.
   Bennett, interviewed on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' said,
``There's something very real called the fourth grade slump. Our
schools seem to do a pretty good job up to grade three.''
   The problems continue ``right through twelfth grade,'' said
Bennett. ``The longer you stay in school in America, the further
you fall behind your counterparts from other countries.''
   Bennett, who leaves office in three weeks, released a model
elementary school curriculum Tuesday that calls for a rigorous
course of study for all children in kindergarten through eighth
grade, including foreign languages, literary classics, pre-algebra
or algebra and introductory science courses.
</TEXT>
