<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CPACommissions     08-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CPA Commissions,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CPAs Vote to Drop Ethics Ban on Accepting Commissions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under pressure from the Federal Trade Commission,
the nation's largest organization of certified public accountants
lifted its 82-year-old ban on CPAs' accepting certain fees and
commissions.
   The ruling council of the 272,000-member American Institute of
Certified Pubic Accountants voted 191-5 Tuesday to drop the
prohibition against compensation for non-audit financial planning
services.
   The ban was intended to avoid conflicts of interest among
accountants, but officials said that dropping the restriction will
benefit the consumer by allowing CPAs to compete against bankers
and stockbrokers.
   ``We've been working on this change for five years, and we're
just delighted that it occurred,'' said H.D. Vest, an Irving,
Texas, accountant who threatened to sue the institute if it didn't
drop the ban.
   The FTC last year issued a letter of complaint against the CPA
group, threatening legal action unless it allowed accountants to
accept commissions for non-audit work. The FTC contended the ban
violated antitrust law.
   The FTC said the ban effectively prevented CPAs from competing
in the financial services market. Since they could not accept
commissions, they had no incentive to provide the services.
   Under the ban, accountants in most states could take no part in
financial planning.
   ``(The change) allows consumers to go to one person who knows
their situation best, and that one person, the CPA, will make the
recommendation,'' Vest said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   Vest said consumers will benefit most from the change because it
will allow them to get business done ``under one roof.''
   Licensing authority is actually held by the individual states,
but the institute's code of ethics serves as a model for many state
regulatory boards.
   The FTC had no immediate comment on the vote, said a woman at
the commission's Washington offices who did not give her name.
   Critics of the change focused on the conflict of interest issue,
saying accountants could give biased advice to get a bigger fee,
Vest said.
   The institute's policy change allows accountants to earn
commissions in several areas, such as helping clients obtain loans,
make acquisitions or mergers and devise cost-cutting plans, Vest
said.
   Five states _ Maryland, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Texas, and West
Virginia _ already allow such commissions.
   The National Association of State Boards of Accountancy, whose
members regulate CPAs, is expected to vote on a similar measure on
Sept. 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
