<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     08-31 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiites Rally, Stage Strike To Mark Disappearance of Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bursts of gunfire resounded in Beirut's
southern suburbs today as Shiite Moslem factions rallied to mark
the 10th anniversary of the disappearance of their spiritual
leader, Imam Mousa Sadr.
   A daylong general strike also was observed to mark the occasion.
   In a separate development, acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, an
American-educated, moderate politician, was rushed to the American
University Hospital in west Beirut after a severe asthma attack.
   Gunmen of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, dashed
out of the Bir el-Abed mosque where they were holding their rally
as the firing began.
   They ordered reporters to leave the district.
   Syrian troops manning checkpoints around the mosque said the
firing came from another neighborhood, five blocks to the west. The
mainstream Shiite Amal faction was holding a separate rally in that
area.
   ``Some militiamen fired their automatic rifles in the air,'' a
Syrian officer who spoke on condition of anonymity told reporters.
``We are searching the area for them.''
   No casualties were reported.
   Government offices, banks, shops, restaurants and other
businesses were closed in west Beirut and other towns and cities in
south and east Lebanon as the Shiites observed the strike.
   The stoppage was called by Amal, which was founded by Sadr in
1974 as a social movement seeking better living conditions for the
downtrodden Shiite community.
   The group took up arms a year later, when the Christian-Moslem
civil war broke out.
   Sadr, who also headed the Supreme Shiite Islamic Council,
vanished on Aug. 31, 1978, while on visit to Libya. Libyan
authorities said he left for Rome, but Italian authorities denied
he ever landed in Italy.
   Amal has accused the Libyans of holding Sadr.
   The Islamic Amal, another Iranian-backed militia based in east
Lebanon, sponsored a third rally in the city of Baalbek. There were
no reports of any problems there.
   The 1.2 million Shiites form the largest single sect in Lebanon,
and their three militant groups are divided mainly over regional
alliances and local politics.
   Amal, headed by Justice Minister Nabih Berri, is seeking
Christian-Moslem coexistence in Lebanon on the basis of political
reforms distributing power equally between the two communities. The
other two advocate the establishment of an Iran-style Islamic
republic.
   Hezbollah also is believed to be an umbrella for underground
factions who hold most of the 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   Hoss was admitted to the hospital's intensive care unit and was
recovering quickly, an attending doctor said.
   The Sunni Moslem became acting prime minister in June 1987, when
Prime Minister Rashid Karami was killed in a helicopter explosion.
   Hoss was scheduled to hold a news conference Thursday to
elaborate on a political deadlock that has prevented the election
of a new Lebanese president.
   President Amin Gemayel's six-year term expires on Sept. 23 and
he cannot run for another term.
   Christian parliament members boycotted an Aug. 18 election
session because the only candidate was former President Suleiman
Franjieh, a Maronite Catholic who is a staunch ally of Syria.
   Christian militias, backed by Israel, are violently opposed to
Syria.
   Under an unwritten 1943 ``national covenant,'' the president
must be a Christian, the prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the
parliament speaker a Shiite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
