<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HongKongCrash 4thLd-Writethru a0550 08-31 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong Crash, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0550,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Jetliner Skids Off Runway Into Sea; Seven Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with six crew members and one
passenger killed. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Earlier, small...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese jetliner with 89 people aboard
skidded off a runway while landing in heavy rain today and broke
apart in the sea. Officials said seven people were killed,
including six crew members trapped in the submerged nose section.
   Fifteen people were reported injured, and 13 of them were
hospitalized in fair or satisfactory condition. The airline said
two of 12 Americans on board were injured.
   A rescue operation at Hong Kong's airport involving divers, a
flotilla of boats and five helicopters began after Flight 301
plunged into Victoria Harbor at 9:19 a.m. Later in the day, a huge
floating crane lifted the crumpled jetliner from the water, and an
investigation into the crash began.
   The bodies of the six crew members were found in the front part
of the plane, according to Tsui Hin-cheuk, divisional commander of
the fire services department.
   Officials said a passenger, a Hong Kong resident identified only
by his surname Fung, died of head injuries.
   Earlier, small rubber rafts with rescue personnel bobbed around
the partially submerged wreckage of the British-made Trident jet,
which had arrived from Canton, capital of China's Guangdong
province 90 miles to the northwest.
   Fire engines crowded onto Kai Tak Airport's solitary runway,
which juts into the harbor. ``It fell into the sea at the end of
the runway,'' police spokesman Tony Leung said of the jetliner.
   Tsui Hin-Cheuk, one of those overseeing the search and rescue
operation, told reporters the six who died were trapped in the
plane's nose section, which was submerged in shallow water just off
the end of the runway.
   The plane, carrying an 11-member Chinese crew, is owned by the
Civil Aviation Administration of China, that nation's flag-carrier.
   Tsui said one of the plane's engines was on fire when rescue
workers arrived, but he did not elaborate.
   Government-run Radio Television Hong Kong interviewed one
unidentified passenger who said some of the plane's safety belts
did not work.
   ``That's why when the plane landed so hard, people simply were
flying,'' the woman told the station. ``I was in the back. It
didn't dawn on me that we were really out of control. I was
thinking more of ... how I was going to get out.''
   Kiyotaka Fukasawa, a 60-year-old Japanese passenger, told
reporters that as soon as the plane hit the water, a flight
attendant opened an emergency door so passengers could scramble out
onto the wing and wait for rescue crews.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency said bad weather caused the
crash. Airline spokesman Chen Zhengyou, when asked about the cause,
said only, ``You know, today the weather is not very good.''
   Heavy showers reduced visibility for much of the morning.
   The nationalities of most of the injured were not known. The
airline did not release a passenger list from the plane, which can
carry up to 100 people.
   Hospital officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
identified two of the injured as Heung Cheuk-Wu, a 38-year-old
Chinese-American, and Jean Allegre of France.
   The airline said the uninjured included 10 Americans, 12
Japanese, 10 Chinese, 10 Hong Kong Chinese, and nationals from
Taiwan, Indonesia, Finland, France, New Zealand, Switzerland,
Germany, Great Britain, the Philippines and Singapore.
   All incoming and outgoing flights at Kai Tak, a major
transportation hub for Southeast Asia, were delayed for nearly
seven hours after the crash.
   It was the worst airline crash at Kai Tak since 1967, when a
Thai International flight crashed into the harbor, killing 24 of 73
people on board.
   Two cargo planes have crashed at Kai Tak since, but no one was
killed in those accidents.
</TEXT>
