<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-IRA 2ndLd-Writethru   08-31 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-IRA, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0527,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio: Two IRA Members Caught, Car Filled with Explosives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with authorities saying suspects might
be IRA guerrillas. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said today they
caught two suspected Irish Republican Army members as they tried to
cross the border from the Netherlands with weapons.
   Suspected IRA guerrillas have carried out several attacks
against British Army bases in West Germany over the past few months.
   In the last such attack, a bomb exploded at a British forces
army barracks in Duesseldorf on Aug. 5. Five people were injured.
   ``There are grounds to believe that they belong to the IRA,''
chief federal prosecutor spokesman Alexander Prechtel told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview. ``An investigation is
now under way,'' Prechtel said.
   Suedwestfunk Radio in Stuttgart reported earlier that the two
men caught late Tuesday night carried a load of guns and
explosives. The officials, however, said they could not confirm
that the men had explosives.
   ``Two rifles and two pistols were found in the suspects' car. As
far as I know, there were no explosives,'' Prechtel said.
   Prechtel declined to release the mens' names, but said one of
them had a British passport. Police found no documents on the other
man.
   Officials said the two men were arrested around midnight.
   Prechtel confirmed the radio report that the suspects were
caught near Waldfeucht near a British army base. Waldfeucht is 45
miles northwest of Cologne on the Dutch border.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and to unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
