<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Crash-727     08-31 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-727,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing 727 Profile</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing 727, involved in a Delta Airlines
crash Wednesday at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport, was initially
designed for short to medium routes and was one of the most popular
commercial jetliners ever made.
   The three-engine plane with the distinctive T-tail, no longer
manufactured, made its first flight Feb. 9, 1963. It was designed
for a maximum passenger capacity of about 130, though later models
could carry 189 passengers.
   The plane has a range of more than 2,500 statute miles.
Production ended Aug. 14, 1984, with 1,831 delivered. It is flown
by more than 170 carriers.
   There are various models, all powered by Pratt & Whitney JT8D
turbofans.
   Models include:
   727-100, standard passenger seating 94. Length 133'2'', wingspan
108'. In service Feb. 1, 1964.
   727-100C, same size, convertible to all cargo. In service April
23, 1966.
   727-100QC, same thing, designed for quick conversions to
passenger or cargo.
   727-200, Length 153'2'', wingspan 108', 134 passengers. In
service Dec. 14, 1967.
   727-200 advanced version, same size, 145 passengers. In service
July 1972.
   727-200F, all freight version, same size, in service August 1983.
</TEXT>
