<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AirShow-Italy     08-31 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Show-Italy,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral Service for Italian Pilots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Air Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UDINE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of townspeople, family members,
dignitaries and fellow aviators crowded into a small church today
to pay last respects to the three Italian pilots killed in the West
German air show disaster.
   Defense Minister Valerio Zanone and Senate President Giovanni
Spadolini headed the government delegation at the funeral service
for Lt. Col. Mario Naldini, 38; Lt. Col. Ivo Nutarelli, 41; and
Capt. Giorgio Alessio, 31.
   The three members of the Frecce Tricolori (Tri-Color Arrows)
acrobatic team were killed when their jets collided during an air
show Sunday at a U.S. military base in Ramstein, West Germany. One
of the planes hurtled into the crowd of spectators. At least 49
people were killed in the disaster.
   In addition to Air Force chief Gen. Franco Pisano and other
Italian military officials, members of precision flight teams from
France and Canada attended the service in the Ossario Temple church.
   The ceremony was led by a military chaplain, Archbishop Gaetano
Bonicelli, who read a message of blessing and condolence from Pope
John Paul II.
   In his homily, Bonicelli said the destiny of the three pilots
``invites us once again to grasp the meaning of the message of
Luke, accepting divine will, which we often can not comprehend, as
children often don't understand the will of their parents.''
   One pilot offered a prayer in which he urged Zanone to ``do all
you can so the Arrows remain. They are the most beautiful thing we
have.'' Zanone sobbed quietly.
   Some politicians in Italy have demanded the squadron be
disbanded, but Zanone and Pisano said earlier this week the team
would continue to fly.
</TEXT>
