<DOCNO> AP880831-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SeditionTrial     08-31 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sedition Trial,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sedition Charges Dropped Against Two Defendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department today dropped sedition and
racketeering charges against two of seven avowed revolutionaries
accused of plotting the violent overthrow of the U.S. government.
   The charges against Thomas William Manning, 42, and Jaan Karl
Laaman, 38, were dismissed to expedite the trial being held in
Springfield, acting U.S. Attorney Richard G. Stearns said.
   The seven were charged with seditious conspiracy and
racketeering in connection with 10 bank robberies and several
bombings, including a 1976 blast that injured 22 people at Suffolk
County Courthouse in Boston.
   U.S. District Judge William G. Young in Springfield approved the
dismissal of charges.
   Manning and Laaman already have been sentenced to long prison
terms for related crimes.
   ``In light of the lengthy consecutive sentences now imposed on
both Manning and Laaman, it is not in the interests of justice to
prosecute either man further,'' Stearns said in a statement.
   Dropping the charges ``will, by effectively shortening the jury
selection process, allow the remaining defendants to proceed more
expeditiously to trial, without substantially compromising any
public interest,'' the statement said.
   Manning and Laaman were named in a 1986 indictment charging them
with violating the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations
statute and federal seditious conspiracy laws.
   Laaman's 53-year federal sentence and additional 39- to 45-year
state sentence were upheld on appeal earlier this year. He was
convicted of six bombing charges and one charge of conspiracy. The
Massachusetts convictions involved the attempted murder of two
state troopers.
   Laaman will not be eligible for parole until Dec. 22, 2008.
   Manning also faces a 53-year sentence that has been upheld on
appeal. He was also sentenced to 25 years to life for the murder of
a New Jersey State Trooper.
   Laaman's attorney, Steven Schlang, said the defense team would
file motions asking that Laaman and Manning be allowed to stay at
the Hartford jail where the defendants are housed to help them in
the defense.
</TEXT>
