<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DroughtInsurance     08-31 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Insurance,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chubb Agrees To Refunds, Payments; Won't Extend Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Midwestern farmers who claim an
insurance company reneged on its summer drought insurance must meet
today's deadline if they want to apply for premium refunds, lawyers
said.
   Farmers can apply for the refunds or even double refunds without
forfeiting the right to sue the Chubb Group of insurers for
damages, according to an agreement filed Tuesday between lawyers
for farmers and Chubb.
   A federal court here is hearing a class-action suit on behalf of
farmers who bought drought insurance from the Federal Insurance
Company, a Chubb subsidiary.
   ``It is simply stating that the double-payment is not going to
prejudice anyone,'' said Stanley M. Chesley of Cincinnati, one of
four lawyers representing the farmers. He declined to comment
further.
   The insurance companies ``have agreed that farmers may accept
premium refunds and matching payments without jeopardizing any
claim for payments due under the policies,'' said Terry
Geibelstein, a Davenport, Iowa, lawyer who also represents the
farmers in the suit.
   But the statement, issued by Geibelstein, Chesley and lawyers
Robert A. Van of Davenport and Michael J. Freed of Chicago, noted
that Chubb refused to extend its Aug. 31 deadline for accepting
refunds and double-premium reimbursements to farmers who bought
drought insurance coverage that was subsequently denied. Farmers
must apply in letters postmarked no later than today to Chubb for
the refunds.
   Farmers in Ohio, Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee, Michigan,
Illinois, Missouri, Minnesota, Iowa and Wisconsin say Chubb sold
them drought insurance but failed to pay their claims for damage
from this year's drought.
   Chubb announced in July that agents had oversold the insurance
and began to return premium checks. Chubb then issued some policies
and offered other farmers a double-premium bonus payment, but some
state insurance regulators have called the offer inadequate.
</TEXT>
