<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis-Strategy 1stLd-Writethru a0433 08-31 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Strategy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Team Braces For Post-Holiday Push</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with briefing; pick up 2nd graf pvs bgng
``Dukakis who...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' campaign manager said today the
Democrats would use the selection of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle as the
Republican vice presidential nominee to question George Bush's
judgment and leadership in the upcoming fall campaign.
   ``Dan Quayle is going to emerge not only as an issue, but as a
liability on the Republican side because it goes to judgment and it
goes to leadership,'' top campaign aide Susan Estrich said at a
briefing on Dukakis campaign stragegy.
   ``We start this campaign on a solid footing in a close
competitive race,'' said Estrich.
   She said both the Dukakis campaign and the Democratic National
Committee were preparing separate advertising campaigns to air
Labor Day week.
   The party's advertising campaign will highlight the theme
``bringing prosperity home,'' while the initial campaign ads would
focus on Dukakis' record as governor of Massachusetts, portraying
him as a skilled administrator capable of implementing his goals of
an improved economy and better jobs.
   ``It's our sense right now that voters have only scant
information of what Dukakis has accomplished,'' she said.
   ``There is a lot of misinformation out there and we're going to
correct it,'' said Estrich, an indirect acknowledgment that
Republican nominee Bush has scored well in recent weeks with
attacks on Dukakis on such issues as his veto of legislation to
require the recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance in Massachusetts
schools.
   Estrich and Dukakis aide Jack Corrigon flatly denied they had
ever suggested to Jesse Jackson that he avoid campaigning in such
states as Michigan, Louisiana, Georgia, Mississippi and Texas.
   A source close to Jackson said such a request was made and then
withdrawn when Jackson objected to the suggestion he ought to stay
out of states where he outpolled Dukakis in the Democratic
primaries. Jackson finished ahead of Dukakis in all of those states
except Texas.
   Jackson's role in the fall campaign has not yet been settled.
   Dukakis, who has been dividing his time between Statehouse
duties and campaigning as the Democratic presidential nominee, will
stay on the road five to six days a week after the holiday.
   Dukakis was traveling today to the West Coast, and after Labor
Day he will start a trip through the Midwest and East Coast that
will include a joint appearance with running mate Lloyd Bentsen at
a labor rally in Detroit.
   Bentsen, a Texan, will carry much of the burden of the attacks
on his Senate colleague from Indiana.
   Still unresolved, however, was what onetime presidential
contender Jackson would do, especially when and where Dukakis and
Jackson would make joint appearances.
   Jackson met in Washington on Thursday with Dukakis aides and
Democratic Party chairman Paul Kirk to discuss the campaign, but
very little was settled, according to one participant who asked not
to be identified.
   The source described Jackson as upset by a request, later
dropped, that he avoid appearances in several states, including
three that he carried in the Democratic primaries.
   Dayton Duncan, a Dukakis campaign spokesman, confirmed the
Jackson meeting took place but was unable to provide details.
   A Jackson supporter said the Dukakis aides had a list of states
_ Michigan, Louisiana, Mississippi, Georgia and Texas _ where they
did not want him to campaign. They said they were concerned that
his negative ratings were so high in those states that he might
hurt the ticket.
   Duncan said there was no such list.
   Jackson and his supporters said he beat Dukakis in the
Democratic primaries or primary-like caucuses in all of those
states but Texas. That dispute reportedly ended with the Dukakis
aides dropping their objections and Jackson saying he would
campaign in all but Texas.
   On Tuesday, officials of the Dukakis campaign met with their
counterparts in Bush's campaign to negotiate a debate schedule and
format.
   After a meeting with Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker III
in Washington, Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas said the two
camps were far apart on arrangements for candidate debates.
   ``We want more debates, they want fewer,'' said Brountas. ``We
want to start them earlier, they want to start them later.
   ``We want to continue them up until the election takes place.
They would like to end them much earlier.''
</TEXT>
