<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HorrorMovie 1stLd-Writethru a0531 08-31 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Horror Movie, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bloody Script for Witch Movie Turns Off Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with council rejecting mayor's
request; Picks up 4th graf, `The mayor ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT DORA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early enthusiasm for the filming of a
horror movie in this town with a New England flavor has given way
to, well, expressions of horror.
   The film's ``purpose is to see how many people can be killed and
how gruesomely they can be killed, and I just don't think the city
wants to cooperate with any of that,'' said Mayor Jeff Book.
   Book called on City Council to declare a moratorium on
movie-making here because of plans for the filming by an
Italian-American company of ``Witch Story.''
   But the council rejected the mayor's request after dozens of
residents and business people supported the filmmakers at a special
meeting Tuesday night.
   ``The last thing this city council wants to do is try to
legislate morality,'' said Vice President Al Liveright of the Mount
Dora Chamber of Commerce.
   The mayor would like to see ground rules established for any
future movie projects in this central Florida town.
   In 1980, many downtown businesses were painted pink for the
movie ``Honky Tonk Freeway.''
   That was fun, many residents agreed, although the movie was a
box-office flop. So town officials were excited last week when
United Entertainment Corp. said it wanted to film a witch story
here because of Mount Dora's New England-style architecture and
ambiance.
   That enthusiasm lasted only until the mayor got a look at the
script.
   The low-budget ``splatter'' film is ``revolting and offensive,''
Book said.
   The script calls for a gang rape, a crushed skull, an exploding
child, a couple pureed in bed, a decapitation, a blood bath, an
exploding stomach and an exploding teen-ager, among other nasty
business.
   The witch would be dragged through city streets, repeatedly
raped and then burned at the stake.
   ``Some horror films, like some of Hitchcock's or `The Shining,'
are made with great style,'' said Book. ``But this is just garbage.
I don't think the city wants to be part of it.''
   Clara Pascal, a spokeswoman for the production company, said
company executives talked to Book about his concerns and would meet
with city officials. The film is in the planning stage, and no
production has begun.
   ``There are some things we might be able to do with the script.
We'd love to stay in Mount Dora,'' Ms. Pascal said. ``But it is a
horror movie.''
   Book said changing a few scenes would not help. ``If you deleted
all the offending scenes in this script, you'd have to start all
over with a new script,'' he said.
   ``We want to improve on `Honky Tonk Freeway,' not go down in
quality,'' the mayor added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
