<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATOExercise     08-31 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO Exercise,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanks, Trucks Shipped For Six-Nation NATO Maneuvers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,000 tanks, trucks, armored
personnel carriers and other military equipment rolled off a U.S.
Navy ship today for a key NATO exercise in southern West Germany.
   Two other ships earlier brought 2,000 pieces of equipment for
the Certain Challenge exercise on Sept. 12-23. About 125,000
personnel from the United States, Canada, Denmark, France, Britain
and West Germany will take part.
   U.S. Gen. John R. Galvin, the top commander of North Atlantic
Treaty Organization forces in Europe, inspected the equipment
aboard the USS Denebola when it docked today in Antwerp, 30 miles
north of Brussels.
   ``I'm quite satisfied with what I see,'' he told reporters after
a tour of the 946-foot long ship, which left Savannah, Ga., on Aug.
22.
   ``We do not have enough military force in Europe to be able to
truly defend Western Europe, and we are absolutely dependent on
fighting long enough over here with what we have in place in order
to wait for reinforcements to arrive,'' he said.
   ``This is what I'm going to need if, God forbid, we ever have a
war in Europe,'' he said. ``But the mere fact that we can do this
(provide equipment) ... is a very powerful deterrent that would
suppress any ideas of aggression.''
  
</TEXT>
