<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Bowman     08-31 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Bowman,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP World Service Editor James D. Bowman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James D. Bowman, a senior editor in the World
Services division of The Associated Press and a former AP foreign
correspondent, died Tuesday night. He was 63.
   Bowman, whose AP career spanned 33 years, underwent abdominal
surgery in late July at Phelps Memorial Hospital in North
Tarrytown, New York, and had been in intensive care since then.
   He joined the AP in Dallas in 1955 as a newsman, transferred to
the Houston bureau in 1958 and to the World Desk in New York in
1960 as an editor of news transmitted to the AP's subscribers
outside the United States.
   Bowman, who was fluent in Spanish, was named chief of bureau in
Bogota, Colombia, in 1963, and reported from that country during a
period of civil unrest. He also covered news assignments elsewhere
in Latin America.
   Bowman returned to the World Desk in 1965, and in recent years
worked as North American editor, responsible for stories
transmitted overseas on U.S. and Canadian politics, economics and
social trends.
   Born Oct. 18, 1924, in Manor, Texas, Bowman earned a degree from
the University of Texas and served in the U.S. Army Signal Corps in
Europe during World War II.
   Before joining the AP, he was a communications supervisor at the
U.S. embassies in Moscow and Madrid. He left government service in
1953 to join the San Angelo, Texas, Standard-Times, joining the
news cooperative two years later.
   Bowman is survived by his wife, Ruthanne, a son, Bryan, and a
daughter, Sherry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
