<HEAD>UNDATED: are justified.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 24
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on George Bush-Dan Quayle:
   The circus that the Dan Quayle campaign has become may be the
media's show, but it's not our fault.
   The people responsible include a Republican presidential
candidate who should know better, but nonetheless sprung a
virtually unknown and untested U.S. Senator on the public and can't
understand why we're interested in virtually every minute of the
curious past that led to his surprising elevation.
   Who is he and where did he come from?
   These are legitimate questions, and if the pursuit of them
reminds (George) Bush of a ``feeding frenzy'' among fish, it's a
possibility that should have occurred to an experienced politician
with five months to think about his running mate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 28
   The Post-Crescent, Appleton-Neenah-Menasha, Wis., on Oliver
North:
   There's something discomforting about an indicted felon stumping
for a political candidate for a $25,000 fee.
   It seems surreal to hear of 1,000 people, some in $500 front-row
seats, pay homage to a former Marine lieutenant colonel who fell
from grace as he spoke of patriotism and salvation coming only from
the Republican ranks. ...
   Last summer, Ollie North was the darling of the airwaves as he
survived four days of congressional grilling before a live,
television audience.
   His rhetoric and flag-waving clouded the charges and almost
turned the tables on his interrogators.
   But in the end he was indicted and now faces charges of
obstruction of justice, tax fraud and personal enrichment for his
role in the Iran-Contra affair.
   To raise money for his defense, he has taken to the road,
commanding large fees for a small dose of pseudo-patriotic talk.
   He's unrepentant for his role in the sordid sales of arms to
Iran and in illegally delivering those profits to the Contras. ...
   He may retain some popular appeal as an anti-communist zealot
but his days are over as a credible foot-soldier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 24
   New Jersey Herald, Newton, N.J., on John Zaccaro's jail
conditions:
   Few convicted cocaine dealers are lucky enough to face the kind
of music John Zaccaro Jr. is listening to these days after being
convicted on a felony drug charge.
   Punishment for the son of former Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro isn't a deservedly long sentence in a
tiny cell in a bleak jail.
   He is enjoying a four-month stay in a $1,500 (a month) luxury
apartment in Burlington, Vt., which comes with cable television and
maid service.
   Addison County State's Attorney John Quinn, who prosecuted
Zaccaro, ... calls it a joke, as though Zaccaro were merely
grounded. We agree.
   Where prisons and jails are dangerously overcrowded, such
alternative criminal justice programs can have a place.
   But permitting a drug dealer such house arrest luxuries hardly
sends the right message about justice being blind, especially when
the pampered ``prisoner'' is the son of an influential politician.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 28
   The Knoxville (Tenn.) News-Sentinel on profiting from the
drought:
   ``Hey, haven't you heard about the drought?'' That's a standard
reply these days to complaints about the high cost of putting food
on the table.
   Cost-of-living statistics for July showed that the overall
inflation rate for that month was 0.4 percent, but the jump in
supermarket prices was 1.4 percent.
   The price of bread made from wheat harvested before the drought
has gone up sharply. Cereals made from pre-drought grain have
climbed.
   What about beef? Prices were supposed to go down because cattle
raisers and many dairy farmers have been dumping animals on the
market to avoid having to feed them. But ... beef prices in stores
haven't dipped and some have gone up.
   Donald Ratajczak of the Georgia State University's economic
forecasting center says that ``perhaps half'' the increased prices
recorded on supermarket shelves can be traced to the drought.
   If he is right, the other half can be laid to efforts to cash in
on a drought psychology that has prepared consumers to expect
higher prices.
   Shoppers can pass up purchases of items they suspect have been
deliberately overpriced. Unsold foodstuffs piling up in stores
would send a message all along the food chain that consumers are
tired of taking it in the neck.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 30
   Decatur (Ill.) Herald and Review on landfill regulations:
   There is certain to be plenty of opposition to proposed federal
Environmental Protection Agency rules for future landfill
operations.
   Requiring bottom liners, waterproof covers and detection and
monitoring systems to prevent ground water damage will be expensive.
   If anything, however, these rules do not go far enough.
   At this point in mankind's history, we are becoming painfully
aware of the damage civilization is doing to our planet and its
ecology. ...
   We need:
   _Mandatory recycling of all non-biodegradable materials. ...
   _Ending our dependence on plastics. ...
   _Confinement of hazardous liquids and other materials to special
sites. ...
   At stake is the kind of world our children and grandchildren
will inherit.
   Someday, adventurers in space may find or create new habitats
for human civilization and development. Until then, this is the
only planet we have. We must start taking better care of it.
</TEXT>
