<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru   08-31 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0541,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Two in Londonderry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details on Londonderry
bombing. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Northern Ireland...'' Trims
thereafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb exploded today in
an apartment in a Roman Catholic section of Londonderry, killing a
man and a woman who accidentally triggered the blast by climbing
through a window, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army apologized for the killings and said
the bomb was intended for British soldiers known to be checking
houses in the area.
   Also today, the IRA said three of its members killed by British
soldiers on Tuesday were ``on active service,'' the IRA's term for
a guerrilla mission.
   In West Germany, officials said they caught two men believed to
be IRA guerrillas as they tried to cross the border from the
Netherlands with weapons. The pair was apprehended around midnight
near a British air base.
   Police said another man was injured when the bomb demolished the
apartment in Londonderry, Northern Ireland's second-biggest city.
   A police spokesman, Sgt. Winston Winters, said the victims were
innocent neighbors who were worried that a young man living in the
apartment had not been seen for several days.
   Winters said the man who climbed inside accidentally triggered
the bomb, demolishing the apartment in the mainly Roman Catholic
Creggan area. He said police were investigating reports that the
IRA had kidnapped two occupants of the home several days ago and
held them at gunpoint while planting the bomb.
   The IRA's Londonderry unit circulated an apology to local news
media saying the bomb was intended for an army search squad.
   ``Although the operation was carefully planned, it went
tragically wrong. At no stage, unfortunately, was it anticipated
that a member of the public would enter the flat (apartment)
through a front window and open a booby-trapped door.''
   Northern Ireland police and the British army released few
details of Tuesday's ambush and killing of the three IRA guerrillas
on a country road at Drumnakilly in County Tyrone.
   The spot was only eight miles from Ballygawley, where an IRA
bomb blew up a military bus Aug. 20, killing eight soldiers and
injuring 27.
   British media reports said commandos of the British Army's elite
Special Air Services regiment ambushed and killed the three men as
they prepared to attack a soldier of the locally recruited Ulster
Defense Regiment. The police and army refused to comment on the
reports.
   Sinn Fein, legal political wing of the outlawed IRA, said
Tuesday the slain men were IRA members. It identified them as Brian
Mullen and brothers Gerard and Martin Harte.
   Today, it released a statement from the IRA's Mid-Ulster
battalion saying the men were killed while ``on active service.''
   The killings were seen as the start of a tougher British policy
to combat increased IRA attacks.
   So far this year, the IRA has killed 27 members of the British
security forces in gun and bomb attacks in Northern Ireland,
mainland Britain and continental Europe in its fight to end British
rule in Northern Ireland.
   With Tuesday's deaths, the IRA has lost 11 members so far this
year.
   British news reports said Mullen was one of eight men questioned
by police after the Aug. 20 bus bombing.
   The government's Northern Ireland Office refused to say if the
shootings were a result of new security measures in the British
province.
   Security forces have denied accusations they operate a so-called
shoot-to-kill policy, in which suspects are gunned down without
being given a chance to surrender. On March 6, British commandos
killed three unarmed IRA guerrillas on a bombing mission in
Gibraltar.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
the predominantly Protestant province and to unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
