<HEAD>Doctors to Decide This Week if Greek Prime Minister Needs Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou underwent
tests Wednesday to determine if he needs surgery for his heart
condition, an embassy official said.
   Doctors at St. Thomas' Hospital will decide Thursday or Friday
if Papandreou, 69, will need an operation for a narrowing of his
aorta, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Papandreou flew to London on Aug. 25 from Greece but the tests
were postponed because of a holiday weekend, he said.
   He said Papandreou's son, Nicholas, and his daughter, Sophia,
and her husband had flown from Greece to visit him.
