<HEAD>1st Suit Stemming from Crash Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has approved the first settlement
of a lawsuit stemming from the crash last year of a Northwest
Airlines airplane that killed 156 people.
   U.S. District Judge Julian Cook approved the settlement Monday.
Details were withheld by court order.
   The lawsuit was filed by Richard Shero of Phoenix, whose wife
Patricia died in the Aug. 16 crash of Flight 255 near Detroit
Metropolitan Airport. His was one of 110 lawsuits filed because of
the crash.
   The lawsuits have been consolidated for pretrial purposes in
Detroit. A progress hearing is scheduled later this year.
   The crash was the second-deadliest in the nation's history
behind the crash of an American Airlines DC-10 May 25, 1979, at
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport that killed 275 people.
</TEXT>
