<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Religion     08-31 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Religion,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Schools to Offer Religion or Mandatory Study Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public school children who don't want to take daily
religion class will have to replace that hour with ``equivalent
alternative material,'' the Council of State has ruled.
   Tuesday's ruling by the supreme administrative court that
advises the government on prospective legislation reversed a 1987
decision by the Regional Administrative Court of Lazio in which
students were given three choices: an hour of religion, an hour of
an alternative study or the option not to attend either.
   Just what subjects might be offered for the ``equivalent
alternative'' hour and who would be responsible for teaching them
is still undecided. The ruling was criticized for not first
legislating national guidelines for the alternative hour. Each
school can decide the content of the alternative study.
   Religious instruction in this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic
country was made optional in a 1984 revision of the Concordat, or
Italian-Vatican treaty, but there has been no standard formula for
how such classes should be scheduled or what to do with students
not taking it.
   The issue developed into a church-state struggle last year. The
Vatican pushed for a mandatory alternative class, saying students
would be discouraged from attending religious classes if allowed to
leave school. ``Lay'' political forces objected, saying it would
compromise the optional future of religious instruction.
   In 1987 more than 90 percent of public school students
reportedly had signed up for Catholic teaching.
</TEXT>
