<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Biaggi-Ballot     08-31 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Ballot,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Leaves Biaggi On Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's top court today refused to hear
an appeal seeking to remove from the ballot U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi,
who resigned earlier this month after being convicted on corruption
charges.
   The refusal by the New York Court of Appeals to hear the appeal
of lower court rulings means that Biaggi's name likely will be on
the Sept. 15 Democratic primary ballot even though he has said he's
not a candidate.
   The only way Biaggi, D-N.Y., can now get off the ballot is by
death, being nominated for a state judgeship or moving out of the
state.
   Because of Biaggi's popularity, Bronx Democratic leaders believe
there's a strong possibility he could win the primary election. In
the heavily Democratic district, a Democratic primary victory
virtually guarantees a general election victory.
</TEXT>
