<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PeoplePower Bjt   08-31 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People Power, Bjt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Latest Example of `People Power' Against Authoritarians in
Asia</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is happening again in Asia: masses of people
mounting a sustained campaign of demonstration and protest against
an authoritarian government.
   For several weeks it has been Burma. A year ago it was South
Korea. In February 1986, ``people power'' in the Philippines ended
the 20-year presidency of Ferdinand E. Marcos and drove him into
exile.
   Popular protest developed differently in each case, under
markedly different circumstances, but brought changes that were
breathtaking for all three nations.
   There were signs that crowds of demonstrators in both South
Korea and Burma drew inspiration from the Philippine example.
   Some South Korean protesters cited the Philippines as a model of
an Asian nation throwing off oppressive rule without upsetting the
entire basis of society or destroying the economy.
   Foreign tourists emerging from Burma told reporters that many
Burmese, repressed for 26 years, found parallels with the
Philippines.
   The United States, which had close ties with the former regimes
in the Philippines and South Korea, says it welcomes more
representative government in Asia.
   After Burmese authorities lifted martial law last Wednesday and
said they would consider holding free elections, State Department
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said: ``Certainly we welcome this
movement toward democracy.''
   Gaston J. Sigur, an assistant secretary of state, told a Senate
committee in May: ``Politically, progress toward increasingly
representative government continues apace in the Republic of Korea
and the Philippines. In short, events in the region have been going
our way.''
   Nonetheless, anti-American demonstrations have occurred as those
who demonstrated against their governments turned to protests of
U.S. military forces stationed in the two countries and American
support for the former leaders.
   American officials say Washington will face more difficult
relations with countries whose governments become more democratic.
   Burma followed an isolationist course under the ``Burmese way to
socialism'' of Ne Win, who seized power in a coup in 1962. He
resigned late in July and students led protests for democracy,
economic reform and release of prisoners.
   Ne Win's successor, Sein Lwin, jailed dissidents and soldiers
shot to kill in an unsuccessful attempt to stop demonstrations by
hundreds of thousands of people. Buddhist monks joined students in
reading pro-democracy proclamations.
   Sein Lwin resigned after 17 days, to be replaced by civilian
attorney Maung Maung, and the turmoil continues.
   Gregory Clark, professor of Japanese studies at Sophia
University in Tokyo and a widely published commentator on Asian
politics, said it was ``encouraging and remarkable that such latent
people power existed'' in Burma.
   ``We had thought they were a demoralized and docile population,
unhappy about governmental inefficiency but tolerating it,'' he
said. ``It turned out they had as much guts and bravery as the
people in the Philippines.''
   The Burmese did not have leaders to provide a focus as, for
instance, the Filipinos had in Corazon Aquino. She is the widow of
Benigno Aquino, who was assassinated when he returned home to
oppose Marcos, and became president when Marcos fled.
   Another difference was that a military revolt against Marcos
coincided with the popular uprising, while the Burmese military was
used against protesters.
   In South Korea, street battles last summer between huge crowds
and riot police led to major concessions toward democracy from the
military-backed government but did not overthrow it.
   Chun Doo-hwan, the outgoing president, accepted opposition
demands that included direct presidential elections, greater
freedom of speech and release of many political prisoners.
   Whether the revolt in Burma will bring greater democracy is not
yet clear, but Asians have shown that great potentional power lies
in coordinated mass effort in a region of 3 billion people.
   Asia's most noted proponent of mass action was Mohandas K.
Gandhi. He led vast throngs in demonstrations against British
colonial rule in India, which became independent in 1947.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Thorson is the Asia news editor of The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
