<HEAD>Dominican Stowaways in Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven stowaways from the Dominican
Republic were in custody Wednesday and authorities searched for an
eighth who jumped into the water at the Port Newark-Elizabeth
marine complex.
   Port Authority police began searching around 9 a.m. after
getting a report that up to 12 stowaways were in the area, said
spokesman Bill Cahill.
   When authorities arrived, six men were taken into custody and
two jumped into the water. One was rescued but the other, described
only as wearing a blue shirt, was not immediately found, said Coast
Guard Petty Officer David Santos.
   Santos said it was believed that four other stowaways fled.
   They had hidden in containers aboard the ship Discovery, which
arrived early Wednesday from the Dominican Republic, said a
spokeswoman for Sea-Land, the shipping company.
   ``The company is working with immigration, local police and Port
Authority officials to determine if there are any additional
stowaways and to coordinate their safe and expeditious return to
the Dominican Republic,'' said the spokeswoman.
