<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mayor-Impeach 1stLd-Writethru a0500 08-31 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor-Impeach, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Voodoo Mayor' Accused Of Undermining Police; Blames Satan For
Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with jury impeaching mayor;
Picks up 3rd graf, `Prosecution witnesses ...'; SUBS 10th graf,
`Mathis attorney ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today impeached Florala Mayor H.T.
Mathis on charges of neglect of duty and incompetence, removing him
from an office he used to publicize ``voodoo'' antics and to pardon
scores of drunken drivers.
   The 85-year-old mayor ran out of the Covington County courtroom
after the circuit court jury announced its verdict. His attorney,
James Prestwood, said he would seek a new trial for the mayor, who
testified that he pardoned dozens of convicted offenders because
he's ``soft hearted.''
   After one hour of deliberation this morning, the jury ruled that
Mathis should be removed from office because he's incompetent and
neglected his duty. The verdict means he was immediately ousted,
Circuit Judge William Baldwin said.
   Prosecution witnesses have depicted Mathis as a man who
undermined the law by abusing his pardon power during the last four
years. He is accused of pardoning more than 100 traffic offenders,
including 27 drunken drivers.
   But Mathis, taking the stand Tuesday to defend his performance
in office, said people came to him with sad stories and he was just
trying to help them.
   ``I'm just a little soft hearted,'' the former tire store owner
testified.
   The mayor of Florala, a town of about 5,000 on the Florida
border 20 miles south of Andalusia, drew national attention with
his July proclamation of ``National Voodoo Week'' and his earlier
purported attempt to scare the police chief by sprinkling so-called
``voodoo powder'' around City Hall, council chambers and down
corridors to the jail.
   However, Mathis testified that he did not believe in voodoo and
the yellow powder he spread at City Hall was sulfur powder not
meant to harm anyone physically. After the media reported the
incident, the mayor said he decided to capitalize on publicity.
   ``I don't even know what voodoo means,'' he testified. ``I made
a mistake in the way I did it.''
   Before taking the stand Tuesday, he told reporters: ``Satan is
trying to destroy Florala's government. I love Florala.''
   Prestwood said during closing arguments on the second day of the
trial that it would be cruel to impeach Mathis, whose term ends
Oct. 3. ``They've done everything in the book to make H.T. Mathis
look bad.''
   Mathis was depicted by prosecution witnesses as a man who
undermined the law by abusing his power to pardon drunken drivers.
   ``I have more power than Ronald Reagan,'' Mathis was quoted as
saying by City Clerk Betty Hooten.
   In the state's closing arguments, Assistant Attorney General Don
Valeska said no one in Florala expected Mathis ``would go power
crazy.''
   ``For him to have one more hour in office flies in the face of
our system of government,'' Valeska said.
   Later, state Attorney General Don Siegelman described the
situation in Florala as ``the most abusive case I've ever heard of
in the United States.''
</TEXT>
