<DOCNO> AP880831-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Pardons     08-31 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Pardons,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Criticize Dukakis on Pardons But Records Show GOP Not
as Tough</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
has come under Republican fire for granting pardons to more than
230 ex-convicts since 1983, but records show he has been tougher on
the issue than his GOP predecessors.
   The Massachusetts Civic Interest Council, in a report released
Tuesday, said the governor pardoned 232 people between 1983 and
1987, clearing their records of crimes ranging from manslaughter _
five cases _ to breaking and entering _ 136 cases.
   Twenty-one of Dukakis' pardons _ nearly one out of 10 _ were
granted to people convicted of selling or possessing with intent to
sell drugs.
   The council, a non-profit, research organization founded and
initially funded by state GOP Chairman Ray Shamie, claims no ties
to the Republican leader. And Bull Purdun, president of the
council, said it was not trying to make ``an overall judgment''
about Dukakis.
   But state GOP Executive Director Alexander Tennant said the
report ``is a clear indication that Mike Dukakis is a very liberal,
left-wing person. He says one thing about being tough on crime and
he does another.''
   However, figures provided by the governor's statehouse press
office show that Dukakis has granted fewer pardons than his
predecessors.
   Republican governor John Volpe granted 1,324 pardons between
1965 and 1968, and GOP Frank Sargent granted 1,755 pardons between
1969 and 1974.
   Dukakis granted 552 pardons during his first term from 1975 to
1978. He was followed by Democrat-later-to-turn-Republican Edward
King, who granted 211 pardons from 1979 to 1982.
   Although Dukakis granted more pardons between 1983 and 1987 than
King did during his administration, the number of pardons Dukakis
allowed during a comparable four-year period was actually less _
192.
   The 232 pardons granted by Dukakis between 1983 and 1987 came
from 550 requests submitted to the Advisory Board of Pardons, a
committee of the state Parole Board. The full parole board
recommended 247 of those be granted, and Dukakis rejected 15 of
them.
   David McGrath, executive assistant to the state Parole Board,
said the board considers a pardon ``an extraordinary form of
relief.''
   ``It is founded on the principle that people ought to be able to
put their problems behind them if they have exhibited extended
periods of good citizenship and deserve forgiveness by the
commonwealth,'' he said.
   The pardoning process is an extensive one that includes input
from the courts, the police and the prosecutors familiar with each
applicant. Besides the Parole Board, the governor's legal counsel
and the eight-member elected Governor's Council review the
applications.
   While the number of pardons has been decreasing, the number of
criminals being sent to state prisons has increased by 40 percent
between 1983 and 1987 and the crime rate has dropped 13.4 percent,
said Dave Wood, a Dukakis press aide.
   In 1983, 2,035 people were sent to state prisons. In 1987, there
were 2,853. Of that increase in 818 inmates, 72 percent of them
were convicted of drug-related crimes, Wood said.
   ``Very simply there are more people going to jail and there are
hard clear increases in the number of drug offenders going to
jail,'' Wood said. ``And by same token, we are looking at fewer
pardons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
