<DOCNO> AP880831-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AirShow 3rdLd-Writethru a0535 08-31 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Show, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0535,0935</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Search for Loved Ones As Officials Try To Identify Crash
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with Germans lowering death
toll to 48, U.S. raising it to 52; 25 identified, nationalities.
Pick up 5th pvs, `It was...' Edits thereafter to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family members searched for loved
ones missing after an air show crash killed at least 48 people.
Injured children lay unclaimed in hospitals as officials tried to
determine if their parents were among the dead.
   Earlier, officials said the death toll was 49.
Rhineland-Palatinate state spokesman Juergen Dietzen said today a
4-year-old boy in serious condition was erroneously listed as dead.
   But U.S. Air Force spokeswoman Maj. Kathy White said revised
figures showed 52 people were dead. On Tuesday, the Pentagon
announced 40 people died, six of them U.S. citizens.
   On Sunday, three of 10 jets in an Italian air force stunt team
collided, one careening into the crowd at the annual air show at
the U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein.
   By this evening, 25 of the dead were identified, said Dietzen.
He said 166 injured were being treated at hospitals.
   The identified dead included the three pilots, 20 West Germans,
a Dutchman and a Frenchman, he said.
   Dietzen said no Americans were among the identified dead. But
chief Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said six Americans were known
to be among those killed.
   The Italian air force official who coordinated the team's stunts
said one plane caused the crash by flying into an intersecting
maneuver at the wrong altitude and speed.
   It was that pilot's jet, having crossed solo through two passing
formations, that tumbled into the crowd.
   A local prosecutor said today he started a probe into the crash
as required by West German law, but said it probably would not lead
to a criminal trial.
   Wilhelm Sattler, chief prosecutor in the neighboring town of
Kaiserlautern, said legal restrictions virtually bar bringing U.S.
and Italian officers before a German court in a criminal trial in a
case like the Ramstein crash. He also said West Germany has no
jurisdiction over the base.
   The Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung daily newspaper reported
today that the leftist Greens party filed a criminal complaint
against the base commander ``for negligent manslaughter and
negligent bodily harm.''Greens are known for their anti-NATO stance.
   Seven Americans remained hospitalized today in the U.S. Army
hospital in Landstuhl, spokeswoman Marie Shaw said, with an
undetermined number at other hospitals.
   Ms. Shaw said Jeffrey McCanch, his wife, Tammy, and their
2{-year-old son, Jeffrey Jr., were taken from the hospital today
and placed on a flight to Brooke Army Medical Center in San
Antonio, Texas.
   Arriving at the center today were Air Force Master Sgt. Stephen
Hull, 32, of Covina, Calif.; Army 1st Lt. Kim Strader, 30, of Salt
Lake City; Army Pfc. Myron Riggs, 24, of Pittsburgh; and Anderea
DelaRosa, 33, an Italian sergeant major.
   Sgt. Barry Grossman, a Ramstein base spokesman, said today that
U.S. officials were still not ready to release the names of the
dead and injured.
   Opposition to military air shows mushroomed. NATO allies
suspended future air shows as they tried to figure out how to make
them safer. Many West Germans _ including some of those injured
Sunday _ demanded the shows be banned.
   ``Now I take warnings about the dangers of air shows seriously.
I didn't before,'' said Karl Eggenweiler of Rothenberg-am-Neckar,
whose back and arms were severely burned and who will likely be
scarred for life.
   ``Now I think these shows should be forbidden,'' he said from
his bed at Kaiserslautern hospital.
   In a poll by the respected Wickert Institute, 82 percent of the
2,710 West Germans surveyed said they want all military air shows
stopped. Only 18 percent said they did not want the shows stopped,
the institute said.
   Dietzen said police received scores of reports of missing people
after the crash.
   ``There are even cases of people from as far away as America who
have said `my relative has been on vacation there for three weeks,
and we haven't heard a word. Is it possible they were at
Ramstein?','' he said.
   West Germany's ARD television showed pictures of a special
missing persons bureau set up after the disaster in Kaiserslautern.
   ``I'm looking for my sister,'' said one unidentified German man.
``The whole family didn't come home.''
   The West German newspaper Bild said authorities searched in vain
for the parents of two badly burned girls _ 6-year-old Nadine and
10-year-old Melanie _ who were taken to a hospital in Oggersheim.
   One unconscious boy thought to be about 13 also had not been
identified, the Frankfurt Abendpost newspaper said. Doctors at a
hospital in Offenbach near Frankfurt said he was burned over 95
percent of his body.
   Meanwhile, some criticized rescue operations at the show.
   ``One eyewitness said that he held one of the injured in his
arms for 20 minutes waiting for help,'' the Frankfurter Allgemeine
newspaper said. ``A doctor said the organization of the air show
was not prepared for such a catastrophe.'' The newspaper did not
identify the sources.
   Wolfgang Herbig, director of the Kaiserslautern hospital, told
reporters he felt there were not enough mobile medical teams
available at the air show.
   But the Rhineland-Palatinate state Interior Ministry defended
the rescue efforts as ``quick, level-headed'' and praised the
cooperation between the Americans and Germans.
</TEXT>
