<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PacificDefenses     08-31 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pacific Defenses,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Doesn't Expect Asian Policy Change Under Bush, Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. defense policy toward Asia will change
very little regardless of who is elected the next president, a
senior Pentagon official predicted Wednesday.
   ``Whether it is President (George) Bush or President (Michael)
Dukakis, policies toward Asia will more or less stay on the same
course,'' said Carl Jackson, deputy assistant secretary of defense
for international security affairs. He also declared it unlikely
the United States would end its military presence in either South
Korea or the Southeast Asian region.
   Rejecting contentions that the United States provides Japan ``a
free ride'' on defense burdens, Jackson told a news conference that
lingering hostility in Asia from World War II provides ``real
limits beyond which Japan would be well-advised not to go'' in
military spending.
   There may be some ``fine tuning'' of policy, but under a
traditional American principle that ``if it ain't broke, don't fix
it,'' the next U.S. president would make few if any basic changes,
Jackson said.
   This is because ``basically our relationships with China, Japan,
the Philippines, with Korea have been great successes through the
last 10 years,'' he said.
   He also predicted both the current review of the agreement on
U.S. bases in the Philippines and its eventual renegotiation will
conclude with a new arrangement because that ``is in the best
interest of the Republic of the Philippines and in the best
interests of the United States ....''
   Jackson said he rules out withdrawal of the approximately 42,000
U.S. military personnel from South Korea because their presence has
been ``a great success'' in deterring any major outbreak of war
since the 1953 Korean armistice.
</TEXT>
