<HEAD>Hundreds Strike Briefly, Demand Reinstatement of Manager</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 250 workers at a regional optical
instruments plant went on strike for several hours Wednesday and
won the reinstatement of a fired manager, a news agency reported.
   Isvan Toth, the manager of the Visorama plant in the northern
town of Esztergom, was dismissed Tuesday, the official MTI news
agency reported without giving any reasons for the decision. It
said the Visorama strikers described Toth's dismissal as ``unfair''
and rejected the newly appointed manager.
   Defending Toth, the strikers said he fulfilled his duties for
four years ``to their satisfaction'' and requested that the
Esztergom facility be left independent from the financially
troubled Granvisus parent company in Budapest.
   The report said that after some seven hours of talks with a
representative of the Ministry of Industry and local Communist
Party and trade union officials, ``the employees came to an
agreement with the (general) manager of the parent company, who
announced that he restored Istvan Toth to his former managerial
post.''
   According to MTI, the representative promised the workers that
his office would study the request for independence of their plant
from the parent company.
   Although labor unrest is rare in Hungary, more than 300 workers
at a mine in the southern part of the country went on strike for 20
hours on Aug. 25 that represented the first worker challenge to the
stringent economic policies of premier Karoly Grosz.
   The miners at Kolmo, some 100 miles south of Budapest, had
complained that because of a quirk in tax laws introduced at the
beginning of this year, workers on sick leave could earn more than
those working regularly.
</TEXT>
