<DOCNO> AP880831-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Writers     08-31 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Writers,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Prosecution Against Writers Continues In 29 Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Persecution against writers continues
in at least 29 nations despite notable improvements in the Soviet
Union, with an estimated 305 authors imprisoned worldwide, a report
said Wednesday.
   ``In all parts of the world, there are cases of censorship or
attempts at censorship,'' said Francis King, president of P.E.N.,
the London-based association of writers and literary figures that
is meeting in Seoul and issued the report.
   The report from P.E.N.'s influential ``Writers in Prison''
committee said the number of novelists, poets, playwrights and
journalists known to be imprisoned in 1988 was 305, or 35 less than
one year ago.
   ``The decrease is almost entirely explained by the new policy
against dissidents in the U.S.S.R.,'' the report said. ``In 1983,
93 Soviet writers and journalists were reported imprisoned, in
forced psychiatric confinement or internal exile. Today the
corresponding number is 20.''
   ``Despite the fact that numbers in prison are diminishing and
there are improvements in the treatment of writers in the Soviet
Union, Argentina and Chile,'' King said conditions worsened in
countries such as North Korea, Vietnam, Iran and South Africa.
   ``There is no solution,'' said King, a British novelist and
playwright, ``because there is no solution to human wickedness.''
He said the figures may be too low in some cases because
information is not available from every country.
   King said P.E.N. would continue pressing for the release of
those denied freedom of expression, in particular South Korea.
   Thomas von Vegesack, a publisher in Stockholm and chairman of
the ``Writers in Prison'' committee, which includes delegates from
20 nations, visited two of five literary figures in South Korean
jails this week.
   Von Vegesack said the 20-minute visits with journalist Kim
Hyon-jang and poet Kim Nam-ju were moving and emotional. He said
P.E.N. plans to ask South Korea's government to release the two,
plus publisher Lee Tae-bok and poet Lee San-ha, with whom visits
were denied.
   The Swedish publisher said he did not know enough about a fifth
prisoner, journalist Lee Pu-kyong, to comment on his case and his
committee had not asked to visit Lee.
   Von Vegesack also said P.E.N. would demand that the imprisoned
writers be immediately given the rights to write, to read all books
readily available in South Korea, and to see their lawyers.
   The committee examines in detail all cases involving imprisoned
writers, journalists and publishers, von Vegesack said.
   ``The quality of writing is not a factor,'' he said. ``The
committee deals with whoever gets in jail trying to express
opinion. P.E.N. is an apolitical organization, but we believe it's
not a crime to have political opinions.'' P.E.N. does not support
those arrested for criminal or violent activities, he added.
   Controversy has surrounded the Seoul meeting because it's
unusual to hold a P.E.N. congress in a country where writers are in
prison. The last time that occurred was 1979 in Brazil.
   The East German delegation boycotted the meeting. Some Korean
writers also have boycotted the meeting, saying they would not
attend until their colleagues were released from jail.
   ``Many members think it's not nice to go to banquets when there
are colleagues in prison,'' von Vegesack said.
   The ``Writers in Prison'' committee was even approached, he
said, by representatives from North Korea ``who wanted to give us
information not about the situation in their own country, but about
the situation in South Korea.'' He said the committee ignored the
overture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
