<HEAD>US Calls for Peaceful Plebiscite in Chile</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday called on
the Chilean government to create conditions to ensure that the
national plebiscite set for Oct. 5 is carried out peacefully.
   Deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Chilean authorities must
``create an atmosphere in which citizens can exercise their freedom
of choice without fear or intimidation so that Chile can take its
rightful place in the community of democratic nations.''
   The statement came a day after Chile's military commanders
nominated President Augusto Pinochet as the only candidate in a
presidential referendum. He will remain as president until 1997 if
he receives majority support but an open election will take place
within a year if the voters reject him.
   Mrs. Oakley urged the Chilean government to take additional
steps to ensure that both sides in the upcoming plebiscite have
equal access to the media. She said a new law authorizing free
television time to opposing views improves conditions for a free
and fair plebiscite.
   ``The government of Chile and especially its armed forces have
an important responsibility to assure its citizens that there will
be a free plebiscite under peaceful conditions,'' she said.
