<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Official Contacts with Walesa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department praised on Wednesday the
Polish government's decision to open contacts with Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa, calling the move a ``welcome and significant
step forward.''
   Deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley noted that the United States
has long encouraged Polish authorities to ``take the path of
dialogue and national reconciliation.''
   Mrs. Oakley spoke shortly after Walesa concluded a three-hour
meeting with communist officials, the first encounter of its kind
since Solidarity was banned in 1982.
   ``Economic and political reforms can succeed if they enjoy the
confidence of the Polish people,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   She expressed hope the government of Poland is prepared to work
with leaders such a Walesa, who are ``widely admired and trusted by
the Polish people.''
   The United States is also hopeful, she said, that this initial
meeting will lead to further steps and to ``substantial progress,
with all sides working constructively together. In a process of
real national reconciliation and reform, there are no losers, only
winners.''
