<DOCNO> AP880831-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Stakhanov     08-31 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stakhanov,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper says Hero Worker's Life Ruined by Soviet Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Josef Stalin and his successor, Nikita Khrushchev,
drove the nation's showcase hard worker to drink and ruined his
family by promoting him to paper-shuffling jobs, a newspaper
reported Wednesday.
   Alexei Stakhanov was quickly ignored after his record-breaking
coal mining feat in the 1930s that made him a hero worker, the
labor newspaper Trud said.
   ``Stakhanov was thrown out and forgotten,'' Trud said. ``That is
how short the administrative-command (system's) memory turned out
to be. The Stalinist system needed a symbol, a poster, and not a
living person.''
   Stakhanov became a legend in the Soviet Union for setting a
world production record for coal. On Aug. 31, 1935, he drilled 102
tons of coal in six hours, 14 times the norm for one shift.
   Western historians say the feat, performed at a Donetsk basin
mine, was contrived. They say all other work was stopped in
Stakhanov's section of the mine and that a whole gang performed
auxiliary work that normally had to be done by the man at the coal
face. This explanation has not been reported in Soviet media,
apparently so as not to diminish the value of the feat.
   The achievement started a nationwide ``speed-up'' movement in
which workers, nicknamed ``Stakhanovites,'' competed for bonuses
and privileges by setting fantastic output records.
   Wednesday's article represented another attempt under Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, to
recount history more accurately.
   It also was another blow to Stalin, who is widely criticized in
the official media now for developing a ``cult of personality,''
killing millions of people including loyal Communist Party members
in bloody purges, and overcentralizing the Soviet economy.
   Like other Soviet leaders recalling the hard-working spirit of
Stakhanov, Gorbachev has stressed the need to increase
productivity. But _ in addition to working harder _ he has promised
people a program of improved technology and accompanied the calls
for higher quantity production with a drive for better quality
goods.
   Stakhanov received many awards, a better apartment and was wined
and dined by Soviet officials including Stalin. He did not,
however, fare well in the long term, Trud said.
   The newspaper said that in 1936, Stakhanov was torn away from
his favorite work and brought to Moscow to become a bureaucrat. He
was made section chief of socialist competitions and awards.
   ``For 25 whole years after that, his name disappeared from
newspaper and magazine pages, from documentary films. His voice
wasn't heard from a speaker's stand,'' Trud said.
   The new job turned Stakhanov into an alcoholic, the newspaper
said.
   ``He didn't do anything in particular. With the strong hands
that were created for a man's real work, he was shuffling paper and
in the evening not infrequently poured himself vodka of
bitterness,'' Trud said.
   His lot did not improve under Khrushchev, who came to power in
1953. When a foreign visitor asked the Soviet leader in 1957 what
had become of Stakhanov, he said the hero worker was still in
Donbass, the area where he set the production record, according to
Trud.
   But Stakhanov actually was in Moscow, and when Khrushchev
learned of this later, he had the miner sent back to the region.
Stakhanov only had 24 hours' notice of the move and left his wife
and children behind in the capital. Local officials ignored him.
   He died a lonely and depressed man in 1977, Trud said.
   Stakhanov still serves as an example for Soviet workers, Trud
said, and for that ``will remain in the people's memory as an
outstanding worker and patriot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
