<DOCNO> AP880831-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     08-31 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warring Moslems, Christians Offer Differing Solutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The warring Moslem and Christian
communities of Lebanon proposed contradictory solutions Wednesday
to the 13-year-old conflict that has claimed 130,000 lives.
   Justice Minister Nabih Berri, head of the Syrian-backed
mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal movement, called for an end to the
``First Republic'' that has given Maronite Catholics dominance over
Lebanon since independence was gained from France 45 years ago.
   ``I hereby declare the end of the First Republic in Lebanon by
burying the system of the 1943 covenant and the creation of the
Second Lebanese Republic based on Lebanon's Arab calling,
sovereignty, independence and justice,'' Berri said.
   Berri was referring to an unwritten covenant under which the
Maronites controlled the presidency, the army, Parliament and the
judiciary. The charter gave the Shiites the post of Parliament
speaker and the Sunni Moslems the prime minister's portfolio.
   Berri threatened that Syrian-backed Moslem and leftist factions
would not permit presidential elections if the demanded reforms
were not accepted before Sept. 23, when the six-year term of
President Amin Gemayel expires.
   But Samir Geagea, commander of the right-wing Christian Lebanese
forces militia, rejected Berri's proposals.
   ``We are ready, after the presidential elections, to meet with
all the Lebanese factions anywhere in Lebanon to discuss `entente.'
Presidential elections should be held first,'' Geagea said.
   Entente, in Lebanese political parlance, refers to a formula of
coexistence accepted by the various warring factions.
   Parliament failed Aug. 18 to muster a quorum to elect a
president to succeed Gemayel when only 38 deputies showed up at
Parliament's headquarters in Beirut. The only serious candidate was
Syrian-backed former President Suleiman Franjieh.
   Moslem and leftist factions accused the Lebanese Forces of
preventing parliamentary deputies from taking part in the session,
in order to block the election of Franjieh, a personal friend of
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Franjieh, 78, holds Geagea responsible for the June 1978 killing
of his elder son, Tony; Tony's wife; and 3-year-old daughter, along
with 30 followers in a raid on the family's summer mansion in the
northern town of Ehden.
   Gegea made his remark at a news conference in Christian east
Beirut as Berri addressed a mass rally in south Beirut to
commemorate the 10th anniversary of the disappearance of the
Shiites' religious leader in Lebanon, Imam Moussa Sadr.
   Sadr, who founded Amal in 1974 and headed the Supreme Shiite
Islamic Council, disappeared Aug. 31, 1978, during a visit to
Libya. Amal has accused the Libyans of holding him. Libya denied
the charge.
   Berri called on Moslem and leftist militias to ``jointly
confront the threat and achieve victory.''
   ``We should have the closest possible ties with Syria,'' Berri
added.
   Geagea called on Franjieh to withdraw his candidacy because
``the Syrians want to ruin Lebanon.''
   The Lebanese Forces, known for their close ties with Israel, are
Syria's main foe in Lebanon. Syria, the principal power broker in
Lebanon, has about 40,000 troops in eastern and northern parts of
the country and in west and south Beirut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
