<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PlaneCrash 13thLd-Writethru a0658 08-31 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash, 13th Ld - Writethru, a0658,0923</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plane Crash Kills At Least 11 At Dallas-Fort Worth Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with witnesses reporting passengers chanted `Get up'
from another plane, survivor saying wing was red-hot. EDITS
throughout to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DN4,5, NY35, LaserColor DN6, LaserGraphic NY29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delta Air Lines jetliner carrying more
than 100 people crashed and burned on takeoff today at Dallas-Fort
Worth Airport, killing at least nine and injuring more than 30,
officials said.
   The Boeing 727 en route to Salt Lake City went down in hazy
sunshine, broke in two and burst into flames on a flat, grassy
field near the runway. Many passengers climbed to safety through a
blackened hole in the top of the cabin.
   Passengers on another flight who watched in horror as the plane
tipped to one side and went down chanted ``Get up! Get up!,'' a
witness said.
   ``There was pandemonium. People were jumping on the plane's wing
and burning themselves on it because it was so red hot,'' said a
survivor, Jim Hammack. ``We got out of the way fast because we
thought it was going to explode.''
   ``You could see the fuel running down the window and down the
wing, and I wasn't going to get burned,'' he said.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said at least nine people were killed
and that about 60 survivors were healthy enough to continue on
their way. The three pilots survived, although one suffered a
severe back injury, he said.
   At least 32 people were admitted to seven hospitals, hospital
officials said, but their condition was not immediately known.
Other passengers were treated and released. Most of the injured
suffered burns, cuts or broken bones.
   ``The plane had slid sideways about the last 100 yards on the
ground. It wasn't a violent crash. It wasn't cartwheeling or
anything like that,'' said Jerry Weeks, who works for an airport
shuttle bus service and talked to some of the injured.
   ``They had no idea what happened,'' Weeks said.
   The fire was brought under control quickly, but the partially
blackened, split-open fuselage smoldered more than an hour after
the 9:03 a.m. accident.
   Flight 1141, which originated in Jackson, Miss., carried more
than 97 passengers and seven crew members, but the exact number was
not known because infants are not on passenger lists, Berry said.
   ``The important thing is that the airplane was 1,000 feet from
the end of the runway,'' Berry said. ``This had to aid rescue
efforts.''
   Berry earlier reported 15 and then 11. He said those figures
were based on erroneous reports from hospital officials and people
at the scene.
   Investigators had no immediate indication of the cause of the
crash, said Michael Benson, a spokesman for the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   However, a source involved in the federal investigation said
early indications were that the jet took an unusually long time to
become airborne, that it climbed to only about 80 feet, and that
the left wing struck the runway first. The source spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   An NTSB team of investigators was sent to the scene. The Boeing
727 is one of the most popular commercial jetliners ever made,
flown by more than 170 carriers.
   Penn Waugh, an uninjured passenger, said the plane ``never got
in the air.''
   ``I heard a noise _ I knew something was wrong,'' Waugh said.
Within a minute, the plane was in flames, he said. The plane broke
in two, and passengers began scrambling through the roof, he said.
   Rick Arnett, an attorney from Austin, said he was on a Delta
flight that had just landed when the plane went down.
   ``It was tipping as it was taking off. It was already tipping to
the right and then, as it crossed in front of us, it never was able
to get altitude,'' he said. ``A lot of people on the left side of
our plane we're saying, `Get up, get up' when they saw it coming
right in front of us.''
   Clive Lane said he saw the plane from his window before it
crashed.
   ``I noticed the tail was sort of hanging down, like, you know,
it shouldn't have been,'' he said. ``And then I saw red sparks
starting at the back of the tail, and I thought that's not its
light, that's a fire. Then I watched it put its tail into the
ground and exploded in a huge ball of fire.''
   Ambulances took injured from the site, and fire trucks sprayed
foam on the wreckage.
   Rescue teams in asbestos suits walked through the wreckage,
looking for passengers and spraying water on sections still aflame.
Ambulances drove onto and off the field where the jet crashed.
Several helicopters also flew in and out.
   The accident is the second at DFW involving Delta in three years.
   On Aug. 2, 1985, Delta Flight 191 crashed as it approached a
runway during a violent thunderstorm, killing 137 people, including
a motorist. The crash injured 25 others. The L-1011 jet was on a
flight from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Investigators determined that there was a wind shear, a violent
change in wind direction that can rob a plane of lift.
   On May 24, a Boeing 727 of the Costa Rican airline LACSA
exploded in flames on takeoff from San Jose, Costa Rica. No one was
seriously injured.
</TEXT>
