<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     08-31 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Threatens Action Against Occupiers of State Buildings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government threatened protesters who
have occupied government buildings, and striking public employees
planned a huge march Thursday against 26 years of authoritarian
rule.
   Organizers said four columns of demonstrators marching from
different areas would converge on Bandoola Gardens, Rangoon's
largest park, for a rally.
   Employees of more than 120 government departments and
state-owned corporations formed the All Services General Strike
Committee on Tuesday. It was the fourth illegal association created
in three days.
   Students and dock workers have formed illegal unions and 21
elder statesmen created a Committee for Democracy led by Win Maung,
72, who was president in Prime Minister U Nu's government.
   U Nu, 81, was the man ousted in the 1962 military coup that
ended Burmese democracy. He has been named ``patron'' of the group.
   Rangoon radio broadcast an official statement that said the
government has allowed peaceful assembly and marches, but added:
   ``In some towns, People's Council (local government) offices and
other government buildings are illegally occupied by the people.
Illegal occupants must vacate the People's Council offices and
government buildings immediately or face the consequences.''
   It did not describe the consequences. The statement was signed
by Maung Ko, secretary to the Council of Ministers, as the Cabinet
is called.
   President Maung Maung's government has said a special session of
the Burma Socialist Program Party, the nation's only legal
political group, will be held Sept. 12 to consider holding a
referendum on one-party rule.
   Protesters from all segments of Burmese society have rejected
that and demand formation of an interim government to bring back
democracy.
   A general strike has paralyzed Rangoon and other cities.
Protesters apparently have taken over the local adminsitrations of
Victoria Point in southernmost Mergui state and some other towns.
   Local adminstrations _ the People's Councils _ and officers of
the ruling party have resigned in some areas, with security and
other duties being taken up by residents and Buddhist monks.
   One Burmese analyst described the situation as anarchic. He said
Wednesday that people live in daily fear and suspense amid rumors
of bombings, arson, looting and impending coups.
   Turmoil began when Burmese leader Ne Win resigned July 23, after
imposing more than a quarter-century of isolation and economic ruin
after the coup. He was succeeded by Sein Lwin, a hardliner held
responsible for bloody repression of previous protests.
   Soldiers shot into crowds of demonstrators and at least 112
people were killed in Rangoon alone, according to official figures.
Unofficial estimates put the number at several times that.
   Maung Maung, a civilian lawyer, replaced Sein Lwin after 17 days
and the violence abated, but protests continued.
   Rangoon radio said more than 1,500 prisoners were released
Tuesday and Wednesday from Insein jail in Rangoon and a prison at
Mandalay in central Burma. That brings to about 8,700 the number
reported freed from the two jails.
   Riots were reported last week at those and five other jails,
where smaller numbers of prisoners have been released.
   The official radio urged striking workers to resume their jobs
at the nation's two oil refineries, at Syriam 10 miles southeast of
Rangoon and Mann in central Burma.
   ``As petrol and diesel oil cannot be refined and sold,
transportation of commodities by car and rail and commuter
transport services will no longer be possible,'' it said. ``Hence
the working people will have to bear the high cost of goods.''
   Officials accompanied by soldiers began house-to-house searches
Tuesday for engineers of the Syriam refinery to force them back to
work, but an engineer told the Associated Press on Wednesday none
had been found.
   He said he and his colleagues were in hiding and would continue
the strike until an interim government was formed. About 150
refinery engineers, technicians and chemists are on strike, he said.
   Sources said more than 5,000 employees of the Syriam refinery,
led by the plant manager, marched in the town Sunday shouting
anti-government slogans.
   Workers at Syriam, which had produced 26,000 barrels of
petroleum products a day, walked out in mid-August when student
protesters called for a nationwide general strike. Military
engineers tried unsuccessfully to operate the plant.
</TEXT>
