<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsBonds     08-31 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Bonds,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Scrapping Bond-by-Phone Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department said Wednesday it is
scrapping a 4-month-old program that offered investors a 24-hour,
toll-free telephone number for buying U.S. Savings Bonds with a
credit card.
   Investors used the program to buy $4.5 million in bonds from its
inception on May 3 through mid-August.
   When it was announced in April, Jerrold B. Speers, executive
director of Treasury's U.S. Savings Bonds Division, predicted sales
would ``surge as people learn they can buy bonds at any time, from
any phone.''
   However, in a statement Wednesday, he said the program ``proved
not cost-effective'' and will end Sept. 30.
   Stephen Meyerhardt, a spokesman for the division, said the
per-bond costs of selling bonds by telephone were more than the
traditional methods of selling through banks and payroll deduction
plans.
   The budget for the five-month program was $800,000, he said.
   Customers may still use the toll-free line, 1-800-US-BONDS, to
listen to a recording with rate and other information on the bonds.
</TEXT>
