<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-31 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital and a home for runaways won big in
a shampoo giveaway by a hotel that replaced packets with plastic
bottles of the bubbly. But creativity also counted.
   Nearly 3,000 individuals or groups responded when the Fairmont
Hotel invited people to ask in an imaginative way for the 97,900
packets of shampoo, hair conditioner and bubble bath it was giving
away, said hotel spokesman John DeMers.
   Pam Farmer, of Knoxville, Tenn., won 2,000 packets with this
entry:
   ``In Tennessee it's hot as hell,
   ``We take a lot of showers;
   ``Please send shampoo and bath gel,
   ``So we can smell like flowers.''
   The Fairmont had decided to switch to plastic bottles of
toiletries as part of its spruicing-up effort in advance of the
Republican National Convention.
   In all, about 70,000 packets of bath stuff went to charities,
officials said. New Orleans Charity Hospital, the largest in
Louisiana's system of public hospitals, and Covenant House, a
French Quarter home for runaways, each received 10,000 packets.
   The hospital's letter said state budget cuts kept it from
providing soap or shampoo to even its poorest patients, said DeMers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first blush, it sounds like a pretty
good deal. If you don't mow your lawn in Hempstead, the town will
do it for you.
   Ah, but there are strings attached to the new lawn law, which
was approved by town supervisors Tuesday. For starters, the town
will charge errant landowners a fee for municipal mowing. And town
officials have the right to tack on a $250 fine and throw the
offender in jail.
   The fee hasn't been determined.
   The beautification law, which goes into effect this fall,
specifies that the town will cut any lawn in which the grass is
more than 8 inches high. It also empowers the town to remove
abandoned vehicles from private property.
   Officials won't prowl through neighborhoods with tape measures,
said Presiding Supervisor Joseph Mondello. But action will be taken
against people whose neighbors complain enough, or whose lawn is
obviously high enough to be unsightly, he said.
</TEXT>
