<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     08-31 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Foreign Minister Proposes Meeting Counterparts to Talk
Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union sent fighter planes to the
northern Afghanistan city of Kunduz to support government forces,
but this did not violate the Geneva peace agreement, a Kremlin
spokesman said Wednesday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said fighter
aircraft based on Soviet territory were dispatched to Kunduz, but
declined to provide details of the type of planes or of the
operations.
   In another development, Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil
proposed meeting with his counterparts from Pakistan, the Soviet
Union and the United States for new efforts to bring peace to his
country, Tass reported.
   U.S. State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said this week
that the Soviets had directed aircraft into Afghanistan and moved
some Red Army troops into Kunduz from elsewhere within the country.
She said this violated the Geneva accords.
   At a news briefing, Gerasimov denied this charge and another
U.S. allegation that the Kremlin had sent ground troops back to
Kunduz, about 30 miles from the Soviet border, after withdrawing
them recently.
   Gerasimov said Soviet aircraft had to be sent in to help Afghan
forces repel rebels fighting trying to overthrow Kabul's Marxist
government.
   ``When the Soviet troops left and part of the troops were still
there, counterrevolutionary, anti-governmental gangs began to
operate, so countermeasures were required,'' he said.
   Asked whether the Afghan government requested the assistance, or
whether the Soviets volunteered it, the spokesman said: ``When in
the area around Kunduz, a critical situation emerged, then with the
consent of the Afghan government, aircraft were used from Soviet
territory for rendering urgent support including a Soviet unit
fighting counter-revolutionary formations.''
   Gerasimov reinterated the Soviet complaints against Pakistan and
also lashed out at the United States.
   ``Nothing of this kind would have happened had Pakistan, with
the support of the United States, not supplied arms to the rebels,
including advisers,'' he said.
   Wakil said in a letter that U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar should also participate in the talks, according to the
official news agency.
   The United Nations oversaw indirect peace talks between
Afghanistan and Pakistan that culminated in April with the signing
of an international agreement aimed at ending the 9-year-old Afghan
civil war and Soviet involvement in it.
   Wakil said the foreign ministers' meeting could be arranged with
the U.N. secretary-general's help ``as soon as possible'' to review
compliance with the Geneva agreement, Tass said. Letters proposing
the session were sent to the United Nations and the countries
invited.
   The message repeated Soviet and Afghan charges that Pakistan is
violating the agreement by interfering in Afghanistan's affairs,
and noted that 73 complaints about this have been filed with the
United Nations.
   Pakistan has rebel bases and helps funnel U.S.-supplied arms to
the insurgents.
   The Afghan government is hoping a leadership change in Pakistan
will mean more cooperation in peace efforts.
   ``We hope that the new Pakistani government, realizing the need
for an above-board approach to the international agreements signed
by the country, will take steps toward improving relations between
the two neighboring Moslem states and normalizing the situation in
the region as a whole,'' Wakil said.
   Pakistan President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, a strong backer of the
rebels, was killed in a plane crash Aug. 17. He was succeeded by
Ghulam Ishaq Khan, chairman of the Senate.
   Under the Geneva accords, the Soviets have pulled out half of
their 100,000 soldiers from Afghanistan since May 15, and the
remainder is scheduled to be withdrawn by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
