<HEAD>Relatives Await Word On Fate of Texas Plane Passengers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Delta spokesman' to UPDATE death count to 13
and survivors to 94</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ERTELT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a handful of friends and relatives
were waiting here for passengers from Delta Air Lines Flight 1141,
and chaplains said they were dealing well with news that the
jetliner had crashed today in Texas.
   ``The mood is anxious, but it's better than it could have
been,'' said Cliff Higbee, a volunteer police chaplain and Mormon
bishop. He said there were only two relatives among those taken
into a lounge to await news.
   ``We've seen few family members here. Most of the people inside
are Delta officials,'' Higbee said. ``It's unbelievable that there
were not more people on the plane who were from Salt Lake City.''
   None of six people in the lounge lost a loved one, said another
chaplain, Kent Goble. ``Frankly, there's no one in there that's
been traumatized.''
   Higbee said one man who was picking up a business associate
learned from the man's office in Arkansas that he had survived.
woman learned four hours after the crash that her sister and
brother-in-law, too, had survived.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry in Atlanta said 13 people were killed
and more than 94 of the passengeropen int n.a.            
 

