<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PotomacView     08-31 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Potomac View,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Indicts Homeowner Saying He Got River View By Cutting Its
Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isaac Fogel advertised his house on the Potomac
River as having a ``river view,'' but the federal government
contends he got the view by chopping down trees in a national park.
   Fogel was indicted by a federal grand jury for allegedly
destroying timber in Potomac in the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal
National Historical Park. The two-count indictment, handed down
Tuesday, charges that 138 trees valued at more than $30,000 were
cut down.
   ``We will not stand idly by while homeowners bordering on
federal parks take it upon themselves to improve their view or
otherwise enhance the value of their property by destroying park
land,'' said Breckinridge L. Willcox, the U.S. attorney for
Maryland.
   Fogel faces a maximum sentence of 11 years in prison and a
$350,000 fine. He also could be ordered to make restitution by
planting trees in the affected area.
   Destruction of government timber is a minor misdemeanor, but the
second count, disposing of government property, is a felony.
   Fogel and his wife put the house and four acres up for sale
several years ago, advertising it as having a ``river view,'' the
indictment said. It never sold, according to Fogel's attorney,
Joshua R. Treem.
   The indictment says the trees were cut in 1985 and Treem accused
the government of ``sitting on its hands,'' in not acting before
now. He said it ``seemed a little disingenuous'' for Willcox to say
prosecutors ``won't `stand idly by' when the alleged events
happened 3{ years ago.''
   David P. King, an assistant U.S. attorney, said his office
received the case several months ago and proceeded
``expeditiously.''
</TEXT>
