<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Strategy 1stLd-Writethru a0629 08-31 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Strategy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Will Use Quayle to Question Bush's Leadership, Judgment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 8th graf with Quayle reax bgng ``Campaigning
in...; pick up pvs bgng ``She said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis plans to portray the selection of
embattled Republican running mate Dan Quayle as an example of
George Bush's lack of judgment and leadership, a theme that will
play a major role in Democratic strategy for the fall campaign, the
Dukakis campaign said Wednesday.
   ``We start this campaign on a solid footing in a close
competitive race,'' Susan Estrich, Dukakis campaign manager, said
at a briefing on strategy for the final two months of the White
House race.
   She said Dukakis would continue stressing two themes: his goal
of extending economic prosperity to all Americans and the need for
leadership at the top.
   Reflecting a tougher tone from Dukakis in recent days, Estrich
said, ``We will be aggressive, but we will be aggressive on the
issues.''
   Estrich said the campaign would ``contrast the record of
accomplishment of our ticket of Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen with
the record of accomplishment or lack thereof, the record of lack of
leadership on the Republican side.''
   ``One issue we are certain to hear more of from Democrats across
the board is the selection of Sen. Quayle and his record and
qualifications,'' she said.
   Estrich predicted that ``Dan Quayle is going to emerge not only
as an issue but a liability because it goes to judgment and it goes
to leadership.''
   Campaigning in Louisiana, Quayle retorted, ``This is the first
real sign that you are seeing a crumbling campaign. I've been in
politics a long time. Fair play. Fair enough. I can stand the heat
and I'll stay in the kitchen.''
   She said the Democratic presidential campaign has paid staff in
every state and is getting strong assistance from state parties as
well. She cited the crucial states of California with 75 Democratic
Party field organizers and Texas with 50, as examples.
   ``We believe we go into the Labor Day beginning with one of the
best organized campaigns that a Democrat has been able to mount,''
she said.
   Dukakis and Bentsen will appear together at a traditional Labor
Day rally in Detroit and then go their separate campaign ways.
   The Dukakis campaign and the Democratic National Committee are
preparing separate advertising campaigns to air Labor Day week.
   The party's advertising campaign will highlight the theme
``bringing prosperity home,'' while the initial campaign aids will
focus on Dukakis' record as governor of Massachusetts, portraying
him as a skilled administrator capable of implementing the goals
his goals of an improved economy and better jobs, she said.
   ``It's our sense right now that voters have only scant
information of what Dukakis has accomplished,'' she said.
   `There is a lot of misinformation out there and we're going to
correct it,'' said Estrich, an indirect acknowledgment that
Republican nominee Bush has scored well in recent weeks with
attacks on Dukakis on such issues as military buildup, crime and
the Pledge of Allegiance.
   Estrich also sought to counter the Republican characterization
of the Democrats as the party of ``gloom and doom.''
   She said Dukakis' emphasis on the economy ``reflects the concern
of middle class Americans that what you have in this country is not
gloom and doom, but it is two people, both working, in millions of
families to make what one person made 20 years ago.''
   She brushed aside concerns that Dukakis has spent an unusual
amount of time the past two weeks campaigning in his home state.
   ``It's not an issue,'' she said. ``It's a responsibility that
comes with being governor. ... With those responsibilities come a
real record of accomplishment and experience.''
   Asked to cite specific differences between Bentsen and Quayle,
Estrich said, ``Mike Dukakis chose as his vice president the man
who led the fight for plant closing legislation. George Bush chose
as his vice president the man who led the fight against it.''
   She referred to a billthat would require companies to give
advance notice to workers and communities before shutting down
plants.
   Bush has said he would place his vice president in charge of
coordinating an administration war against drugs, but Estrich noted
that in a recent interview, the Indiana senator admitted he did not
know that Bush headed an administration task force to block the
flow of drugs into Florida.
   ``Believe me, when I get into it, I will know a lot about that
program,'' Quayle told the Boston Globe in an interview published
Monday.
</TEXT>
