<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     08-31 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Soviets to Stop Cross-Border Bombing Of Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Wednesday urged the
Soviet Union to stop sending planes from its territory to strike at
U.S.-backed guerrillas in Afghanistan.
   The call came on the eve of a meeting in Moscow between
Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost and Soviet Deputy Foreign
Minister Yuli Vorontsov.
   The two diplomats are meeting to discuss a series of regional
issues affecting the superpowers' client states around the world,
but the Afghanistan question is expected to be at the top of the
agenda.
   On Tuesday, the State Department accused the Soviet Union of
violating the Geneva accords for the pullout of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan by sending its planes to bomb the Mujahedeen rebels
around the northern Afghan city of Kunduz.
   A government spokesman in Moscow confirmed that Soviet-based
fighter aircraft were used to aid Afghan ground troops battling for
Kunduz but denied the action violated the Geneva accords. Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov also denied another U.S.
allegation that the Kremlin had sent troops back to Kunduz, about
30 miles (50 kms) from the Soviet border, after recently
withdrawing them.
   But Mrs. Oakley dismissed Gerasimov's denial, saying, ``I'm
sticking where I was on this question yesterday. We said that these
raids came from bases inside the Soviet Union. Therefore, in our
view, it was a violation.''
   She cited a clause in the Geneva accords which she said commits
the Soviets to ``refrain from any form of interference or
intervention in the internal affairs of Afghanistan.''
   Mrs. Oakley declined to elaborate, saying only, ``obviously the
Soviets have admitted that they have used aircraft in the bombing
raids in Kunduz from areas inside Afghanistan. Let me repeat, we
wish they'd stop it.''
   Mrs. Oakley reiterated that the United States was in the process
of preparing a complaint for the U.N. Good Offices Mission which
monitors the Geneva pact. The agreement signed last April calls for
the pullout of all Soviet troops by Feb. 15.
   The Soviets have already complied with an Aug. 15 deadline for
withdrawing half of their estimated 115,000 troops following more
than eight years of occupation.
   The Soviets have repeatedly complained to the U.N. about U.S.
and Pakistani violations of the pact in connection with supplies to
the Mujahedeen.
   The United States says it will keep arming the rebels as long as
the Soviets supply the Kabul government.
</TEXT>
