<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Biaggi-Ballot     08-31 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Ballot,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Leaves Biaggi On Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's top court refused Wednesday to
consider removing former Rep. Mario Biaggi from the state's
Democratic primary ballot, despite his resignation and conviction
on corruption charges.
   The decision by the Court of Appeals not to hear the appeal by
Biaggi's primary opponents means the popular Bronx Democrat's name
will almost certainly be on the ballot Sept. 15 even though he has
said he's not a candidate.
   Biaggi, 70, was in his 10th term when he resigned his
congressional seat Aug. 5, the day after he was convicted on
federal racketeering, extortion and bribe-taking charges in
connection with the Wedtech defense scandal.
   Because of Biaggi's popularity, some Bronx Democratic leaders
believe there's a strong chance he could win the primary election.
In the heavily Democratic district, a primary victory often
guarantees a November election victory, and that's especially true
in this case because Biaggi also has the Republican nomination.
   If Biaggi is re-elected to Congress, it's expected that he would
resign again rather than face the possibility of not being seated
by his former colleagues. The House had been poised to begin
expulsion hearings against him when he resigned in August.
   In the wake of Wednesday's action, the only way Biaggi could get
off the Sept. 15 Democratic primary ballot is by death, being
nominated for a judgeship or moving out of the state.
   Biaggi's opponents in the Sept. 15 Democratic primary, state
Assemblyman Eliot Engel and former Assemblyman Vincent Marchiselli,
had tried to get the state Board of Elections and the state courts
to have Biaggi's original nominating petitions declared invalid.
The two have been rebuffed, even though Biaggi says he doesn't want
to run.
   Arnold Linhardt, a spokesman for Engle, said there probably were
no grounds for bringing the appeal to the federal courts.
   Should Biaggi be re-elected and resign again, it would be up to
Gov. Mario Cuomo to call a special election, probably in February
at the earliest.
   Linhardt said some Bronx Democratic leaders want Biaggi to be
re-elected so they can handpick a candidate for the special
election. Neither Engel nor Marchiselli are considered organization
favorites.
   Biaggi faces up to 20 years in prison on the counts for which he
was convicted Aug. 4. He has said he would appeal. Biaggi also has
been sentenced to 30 months in prison for obstructing justice and
taking a free Florida trip in an unrelated case involving alleged
favors for a Brooklyn shipyard company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
