<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-US     08-31 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Protest US Navy Ships Capable Of Launching Nuclear
Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HIROYUKI KACHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOSUKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters shouted from
hilltops and waved banners on boats Wednesday when two U.S.
warships that can launch nuclear missiles sailed into the home port
of the U.S. 7th Fleet.
   The ships are the first to be stationed in Japan with launchers
for Tomahawk missiles, which are made in both nuclear and
non-nuclear versions.
   ``Get out from Yokosuka!'' about 100 people shouted in English
at the gates of the naval base as the Ticonderoga-class guided
missile cruiser USS Bunker Hill and the destroyer USS Fife arrived
in the port 28 miles southwest of Tokyo.
   A coast guard official said the warships arrived without
incident. Forty-two coast guard patrol boats escorted the U.S.
ships into the port to prevent the approach of 28 small boats
carrying protesters and banners reading ``No Tomahawks,'' the
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Japan forbids the production, possession, or introduction into
the country of nuclear weapons.
   Nearly 200,000 people died in the Japanese cities of Hiroshima
and Nagasaki when the United States dropped the first atomic bombs
to end World War II.
   After the ships arrived, more protesters from civic and peace
groups, labor unions and the Japanese Communist Party staged
separate rallies at a park overlooking the port, outside the naval
base and elsewhere, carrying placards and shouting slogans. Police
reported no arrests.
   Protesters said the biggest rally, sponsored by the communists,
drew an estimated 1,000 people.
   On Tuesday, Yokosuka's 48-member city assembly unanimously
passed a resolution urging the government to keep out the U.S.
warships. The city's mayor and the prefectural governor also lodged
official protests Monday with the Japanese government and said it
did not do enough to ensure that the ships were not carrying
nuclear weapons.
   ``We hope our grassroot struggles will spread to a national
movement,'' said Yoshiko Saito, a leader of a citizens' group
staging a sit-in near the Yokosuka city hall.
   The 9,600-ton Bunker Hill and the 7,810-ton Fife both are
capable of deploying Tomahawk missiles. Under the Japan-U.S.
security agreement, the United States has pledged to notify Japan
beforehand if it plans to bring nuclear arms into the country.
   But critics charge the Japanese government uses the agreement as
a way of avoiding the question of whether U.S. ships dock in the
country with nuclear weapons aboard.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita told reporters Wednesday that
the government would not ask the United States to confirm whether
the ships were carrying nuclear missiles because ``we trust each
other in such matters,'' Kyodo News Service reported.
   The U.S. military, which has about 50,000 personnel stationed in
Japan, maintains a policy of not publicly confirming or denying
nuclear weapons aboard its ships.
</TEXT>
