<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish-Germany     08-31 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish-Germany,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Capture Suspected IRA Guerrillas Headed Toward British Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police captured two heavily armed
IRA guerrilla suspects heading toward a British army barracks after
driving from the Netherlands through a remote border crossing,
officials said Wednesday.
   Their car, seized around midnight Tuesday, contained two rifles
and two pistols, said Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for the chief
federal prosecutor's office. But he could not confirm a radio
report that the men brought explosives.
   Since March 1987, attacks by suspected Irish Republican Army
guerrillas against British army installations in West Germany have
killed three people and injured 40.
   In the latest such attack, a bomb exploded at a British army
barracks in Duesseldorf on Aug. 5. Five people were injured.
   The attacks are part of an escalated IRA campaign against
British targets in Europe.
   On Wednesday, officials said the two men drove over the Dutch
border into northwestern West Germany by using a remote country
lane that is off limits to traffic between the two countries.
   German police arrested the two suspected guerrillas after they
reached the town of Waldfeucht, 45 miles northwest of Cologne on
the Dutch border, Prechtel said.
   ``There are grounds to believe that they belong to the IRA,'' he
said in a telephone interview. ``An investigation is now underway.''
   Prechtel said the pair was headed toward a small British army
barracks in the same community, but did not specify how close they
came to the military outpost.
   Police became suspicious after spotting the pair near the remote
crossing, which has come under closer watch after IRA attacks in
the area, the spokesman said.
   ``One of them has a British passport, although we do not know
yet if it is genuine,'' Prechtel said. Police have not found any
documents for the other man, he said. Prechtel refused to release
the mens' names.
   Suedwestfunk Radio in Stuttgart reported earlier Wednesday that
the suspects were carrying weapons and explosives in their car.
   So far this year, the IRA has killed 27 members of the British
security forces in gun and bomb attacks in Northern Ireland,
elsewhere in Britain and in continental Europe.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
the predominantly Protestant province of Northern Ireland and to
unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
