<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Blast     08-31 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Blast,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Rocks Anti-Apartheid Office Building, Injuring 23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pre-dawn bombing Wednesday
rocked a six-story building housing a church organization and
leading anti-apartheid groups, injuring 23 people, police said.
   Investigators said they had no information on the type of
explosive that struck Khotso House or the identity of the bombers.
The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said without
citing sources that the bomb ``was believed to be the biggest of
its kind'' in South Africa.
   ``There has been a sinister silence surrounding the solution to
these attacks (on anti-apartheid groups),'' said Rev. Frank
Chikane, general secretary of the South African Council of
Churches, main occupant of the Khotso building.
   ``When community buildings and (anti-apartheid) organizations
are attacked no one is found (responsible) in almost all the
instances,'' said Chikane, whose organization includes most of the
country's largest Protestant denominations.
   Chikane also expressed concern the council's files might be
searched by police investigating the blast.
   Authorities declared the building unsafe and police barred
journalists and the people who work in Khotso House from entering.
   However, an SABC television crew was allowed inside and the
organization broadcast extensive footage on the evening newscast.
   Khotso House _ which means ``House of Peace'' in the Zulu
language _ serves as headquarters for the council of churches and
the Black Sash civil rights group, two of the most prominent
anti-apartheid organizations not yet affected by government bans.
   Several other church and human rights groups have offices in the
building, and it housed offices of the United Democratic Front
before the nationwide coalition and 17 other groups were banned in
February.
   The church council has taken a lead role in the anti-apartheid
movement since the bannings.
   The 1 a.m. explosion in the basement of the building slightly
injured a night watchman, passers-by, and residents of nearby
apartment buildings.
   The floor of the main lobby collapsed into the basement. Cars
parked in the building's underground garage were destroyed and
adjacent buildings were heavily damaged.
   Last year, there were several unsolved bombings and arson
attacks on offices of anti-apartheid groups and militant black
labor unions. Activists suggested these attacks were carried out by
right-wing vigilantes, either within or outside the security forces.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, whose offices were
severely damaged last year, described Wednesday's bombing as part
of a ``continuous campaign against the opponents of apartheid.''
   The congress, the nation's main black labor federation, said it
had heard nothing from police about investigations of the 1987
blast at its headquarters.
   This year, there have been a series of bombings of restaurants
and other civilian targets that authorities have blamed on the
outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement, which seeks
to topple the white-dominated government.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok expressed condolences to the
23 people injured Wednesday and said police were conducting a
``comprehensive investigation.'' He said officers were hampered by
the fact that the building had been declared unsafe.

</TEXT>
