<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Space     08-31 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Space,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan, Two Soviets Join Cosmonauts In Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan cosmonaut who has flown combat missions
against rebels in his country arrived with two Soviets at a manned
space station Wednesday and appealed for peace in his homeland.
   State-run television transmitted live as the Afghan cosmonaut
and his two Soviet colleagues entered the space station and met
with the two cosmonauts already on board.
   Vladimir Titov and Musa Manarov already have spent eight months
in space and hope to break the 326-day space endurance record in
December. That record was set by Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Romanenko,
who returned to Earth on Dec. 29.
   Afghan Abdul Ahad Mohmand, in a message addressed to his
countrymen from the Soviet space station Mir, which means
``peace,'' said violence could not be seen from outer space.
   ``I would like to believe that such will be the situation on the
land inhabited by my brothers and sisters, on the land of our
fathers and mothers who have suffered so much during the years of
the war,'' he said during the live transmission by state-run Soviet
television.
   Mohmand's presence on the flight represents an effort by the
Kremlin to boost the prestige of Afghanistan's pro-Soviet
government as Soviet troops withdraw. The Soviets have agreed to
withdraw all soldiers, who were sent to bolster that government, by
Feb. 15, 1989.
   Mohmand, 29, has flown combat missions against the
anti-government rebels in Afghanistan as a pilot in its air force.
   The three additional cosmonauts traveled into space aboard their
Soyuz TM-6 capsule, which blasted off Monday from the Baikonur
space center in Soviet Central Asia.
   It docked with the Mir space station 9:41 a.m. Moscow time (1:41
a.m. EDT).
   ``The cosmonauts feel well,'' the official Soviet news agency
Tass said.
   The five cosmonauts, wearing navy blue flight suits, were shown
by state television hugging, shaking hands and smiling aboard Mir.
One of them demonstrated an unusual position weightlessness makes
possible by standing horizontally.
   State-run television showed Mohmand reading portions of the
Koran, the holy book of Islam, on the space station Wednesday.
   ``This is the first prayer to be made in Mir,'' Tass reported.
The Soviet Union is an officially atheist nation.
   The Afghan was accompanied by Soviets Vladimir Lyakhov and Dr.
Valery Polyakov, who will stay aboard Mir to monitor the health of
Titov and Manarov as they try to break the endurance record.
   The efforts are a step toward determining whether a manned
flight to Mars, which will taken an estimated three years, is
feasible.
   Titov, 40, and Manarov, 37, have been in space since Dec. 21.
Their last visitors were a Soviet-Bulgarian crew that came aboard
in June.
   Mohmand and Lyakhov are to return to Earth on Tuesday.
   Two dozens experiments are planned during the visit of the joint
Soviet-Afghan Soyuz crew. Mohmand is to take part in experiments to
identify oil, gas and other mineral deposits in Afghanistan and
predict runoff of snow and ice in efforts to alleviate water
shortages.
   Polyakov underwent an operation before the flight to remove bone
marrow. When he returns to Earth, more marrow will be removed and
the samples compared.
   Scientists are trying to determine how to counter bone marrow
depletion, which results from prolonged space flight. Polyakov also
will study motion sickness.
  
</TEXT>
