<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TallTownHouse     08-31 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tall Town House,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town House Owner Fighting Fifth-Story Cap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court has ordered a town house owner in one of
Boston's most elegant neighborhoods to lop off a fifth-story
addition under construction that officials fear will disturb the
atmosphere of posh Beacon Hill.
   ``It's a piece of architecture that is going to be with us for a
long time if it's not done,'' David Buckley, chairman of the Beacon
Hill Architectural Commission, said Wednesday. ``These things don't
just come and go like flowers in a planting bed.''
   But the owner's attorney, Guy Carbone, said his client is being
treated unfairly because the city decreed that the original
119-year-old row house be torn down during renovations because of a
rotting foundation, then rebuilt with the facade restored to its
original condition.
   ``The whole issue here is that once the city ordered the
building torn down, can the architectural commission order us to
rebuild it as it was in 1869,'' Carbone said.
   ``That's an interesting opinion,'' said Buckley, who responded
by pointing to court decisions backing the commission's stand.
   The commission in 1985 approved some renovation for Parker's
house, but did not approve an additional floor, Buckley said. The
commission allowed him to take down the facade, but said bricks had
to be removed by hand, numbered and put back in place.
   Court papers said in addition to the extra floor, many of the
bricks were tossed into a pile and broken and some instructions on
maintaining the facade were not followed.
   The owner, Chase F. Parker, declined to comment Wednesday.
   Carbone said Parker planned to build a town house that would fit
in with other structures in the area. ``We tried very, very hard to
satisfy the commission,'' he said.
   The Beacon Hill Historic District was established in 1955 to
preserve the neighborhood as an example of old Boston, said John
Devereaux, an attorney for the commission.
   Much of the area, home to the well-heeled of 18th-century
Boston, has been transformed inwardly into condominium
developments. But the outward facades remain for the most part town
houses of dark-red brick, some with ornate windows and entryways.
   Zoning regulations in the area would allow a fifth floor, but
the architectural commission, a five-member panel appointed by the
mayor, has final say on any structural changes visible to the
public.
   Suffolk County Superior Court Judge Catherine White on June 21
upheld the commission's decision forbidding the fifth floor and
ordered Parker to tear down construction. A hearing date has not
been set in the case, currently before the state Appeals Court.
   While the case is pending, white sheets are draped over part of
the building and a temporary roof has been erected to cover initial
construction above the fourth floor.
   Carbone noted that other renovated buildings in the district are
taller than the original structures.
   The commission does not try to maintain strict preservation, and
allows new materials to be used and changes to be made if they are
judged to be in keeping with the area, Buckley said.
   But adding a floor to a building would change the character of
the structure, he said.
   ``There hasn't been an enormous problem in having people
conform,'' he said. ``In fact, there's quite a bit of support for
it.''
</TEXT>
