<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Colombia-Floods     08-31 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Colombia-Floods,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100,000 Forced From Homes By Flooding In Six States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding in six northern states has
forced about 100,000 people from their homes, the president's
office said Wednesday.
   The flooding has destroyed hundreds of thousands of acres of
crops and killed thousands of farm animals, according to televised
news reports.
   President Virgilio Barco has asked Colombia's congress to
approve $8 million in disaster assistance to the states of Cordoba,
Atlantico, Sucre, Magadalena, Cesar and Bolivar.
   Heavy rain is expected to continue for the next few days,
Colombia's weather service said Wednesday.
   The biggest river in the region, the Magdalena, overflowed its
banks Saturday.
   The flooding has caused an increase in the number of mosquitoes,
the public health department for the state of Cordoba said in a
news release.
   Malaria and dengue fever, both carried by mosquitoes, is common
in the Magdalena river region.
   Twenty people have been bitten by poisonous snakes in Cordoba
since flooding began there two weeks ago, the health department
said.
</TEXT>
