<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     08-31 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4,000 Starved To Death In South, Tens of Thousands Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four thousand men, women and children
have died of starvation and tens of thousands residing in the
war-torn regions of southern Sudan face a similar fate, officials
said Wednesday.
   Angelo Beda, president of Sudan's Council for the South, said
the only way to save those starving in the Equatoria and Bahr
el-Ghazal regions was with emergency air shipments of food and
medical supplies.
   In Ireland, the Rev. Aengus Finucane, director of the
Dublin-based aid agency CONCERN said about 40 people were dying
daily at a refugee camp in el Meriam, 500 miles south of Khartoum,
and that about 2 million people faced death from the ravages of war
and starvation.
   Beda said most southerners abandoned their crops and cattle in
the countryside and fled to towns and cities because of fierce
fighting in the five-year civil war. He said residents are being
beseiged by the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army and dying of
starvation as food supplies dwindle.
   Beda, whose group includes southern political representatives
from Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's government, said record floods
in Sudan earlier this month diverted the attention of Western
relief organizations from what he called the ``catastrophe'' of the
south.
   ``Four thousand people have died of hunger in (the town of)
Aweil so far,'' he said. Aweil, in the Bahr el-Ghazal region, is
587 miles southwest of Khartoum.
   Asked about Finucane's estimates for the number of southerners
dying, Beda said he lacked exact figures, ``but, yes, you can say
the reports about people dying by thousands is correct.''
   In Torit, 787 miles south of Khartoum, about 10,000 people were
stranded without food and facing starvation, Beda said. He said the
bishop of Torit described the situation as critical.
   Beda also said Wau, 662 miles southwest of the capital, faced a
similar situation as did residents in Juba, 750 miles south of
Khartoum, and Malakal, 425 miles south of the capital.
   ``For at least four months, no food or essential commodities has
reached those towns. No medicine has reached them either, so people
die,'' Beda said.
   He said the only way to save those people was to make emergency
air drops of food and medical supplies.
   The rebel SPLA in recent years has shot down two civilian
aircrafts, killing 73 people, and several military planes. It has
accused the government of using civilian and relief planes to
transport military troops and equipment and has threatened to shoot
down any plane flying over the south.
   The civil war has forced at least 820,000 people to flee their
homes in southern Sudan and trek to neighbouring Ethiopia. They
usually head by foot or by train to southern cities and towns that
are controlled by the army, or northward to Khartoum.
   In 1986, Western relief agencies warned that up to 2 million
southerners faced starvation because they were dependent on relief
food in the cities and because the rebels controlled 90 percent of
the countryside, making it almost impossible to get supplies to
them.
   Despite the rebel attacks, relief agencies have been
sporadically flown in supplies from neighbouring countries, or used
trucks, trains and barges from Khartoum.
   The rebels, mostly Christians and animists, are seeking more
autonomy as well as economic and administrative reforms from the
Moslem majority government in the north.
</TEXT>
