<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Housing-Homeless     08-31 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing-Homeless,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HUD Official Voices `Fear and Alarm' Over Housing Sale Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Department of Housing and
Urban Development voiced concern Wednesday that recent court
decisions could cost the agency more than $3 billion a year and
bankrupt its single-family mortgage insurance fund.
   Thomas T. Demery, assistant housing secretary and commissioner
of the Federal Housing Administration, expressed what he described
as ``fear and alarm'' over a decision in U.S. District Court here
Tuesday that prevents HUD from selling any of the 47,000 foreclosed
homes in its inventory.
   U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene temporarily blocked HUD
from selling the homes to the highest bidder unless they are for
the benefit of homeless or low-income people.
   Demery, along with HUD general counsel Michael Dorsey, said
Greene's decision, if upheld, would halt FHA property sales which
provide about $3.2 billion in annual revenues. The FHA fund has
current reserves of about $6 billion.
   ``Imposing a freeze on our disposition program could well
threaten the financial solvency of FHA since our basic home
mortgage insurance program receives no congressional appropriations
and has no authority to borrow from the Treasury,'' Demery told
reporters.
   Demery and Dorsey said HUD would ask Congress to clarify whether
the department has complied with legislation last year that was
intended to benefit the homeless.
   Greene's temporary restraining order expires Sept. 14. U.S.
District Judge Oliver Gasch, who has jurisdiction over the case,
will schedule further action.
   Greene issued his order in response to a plea by the National
Housing Law Project, one of the homeless advocacy groups fighting
HUD's single-family home sales policy, because HUD planned to sell
170 homes in metropolitan Washington on Wednesday.
   Last week, the project succeeded in preventing HUD from selling
200 such homes in Michigan.
   Demery said the FHA insures more than 6 million home mortgages
with outstanding balances of nearly $230 billion. In recent years,
he said, 30 to 40 percent of all new homes sold for less than
$100,000 have been insured by the FHA.
   ``This is a program that has helped 17 million American families
obtain home ownership and has received bipartisan support from all
segments,'' he said.
   ``It would be tragic if we were to put a program like this at
risk _ especially at a time when there is a growing consensus over
over the need to do more to help reverse the recent trend toward
declining home ownership rates,'' Demery said.
   ``We need to do more to help working class families obtain home
ownership _ not less,'' he said.
   Demery said HUD has 400 homes under lease or that have been sold
to homeless persons.
   ``We want this number to grow, and are eager to work with
homeless advocates to devise ways that we can make more FHA
foreclosed homes available,'' Demery said.
   ``But what we object to is a strategy that pits the needs of
hard-working families who want to buy modestly priced homes with
the needs of the homeless,'' he said.
   ``It shouldn't be a case of one versus the other. And surely we
can find ways of doing more to help the homeless without
bankrupting the FHA fund.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
