<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hollywood-Teamsters     08-31 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood-Teamsters,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters and Producers Try to Avert Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A contract dispute between Hollywood
producers and the Teamsters union is threatening to disrupt the
film and television industry as it recovers from the five-month
scriptwriters' strike.
   The Teamsters contract with the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers expired July 30, and only day-to-day contract
extensions have prevented the Teamsters from striking.
   The union was scheduled to announce late Wednesday the results
of a vote on the producers' latest contract offer, with members
expected to reject the contract by an overwhelming margin.
   Another negotiating session was set for Thursday morning.
   A walkout by the Teamsters, representing 2,200 film and
television drivers, could put a severe crimp on Hollywood
production as it recovers from the writers' walkout, which ended
Aug. 7.
   Earl Bush, secretary-treasurer for the Teamsters Local 399, has
said that the producers' last proposal is the most ``insulting
offer'' he has seen in 43 years as a Teamster.
   The contract proposal, Bush said, would require about half the
Teamsters Local 399 members to take $2.61-per-hour pay cuts. The
producers are offering a minimum salary for those drivers of $14 an
hour, down from $16.61. Big-rig drivers earn more, and producers
plan to raise their salaries.
   The producers have said that union concessions are necessary to
keep costs down and prevent so-called ``runaway'' production, where
film and televison crews move to non-union states and countries.
   ``The issue is competitiveness,'' said Herb Steinberg, a
spokesman for the alliance. ``We want to remain competitive in this
market and keep production here.'' The producers estimate that
runaway production has cost Hollywood Teamsters $14 million in lost
wages and benefits during the last two years.
   The producers also want to redefine rules for overtime pay.
</TEXT>
