<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-Delta 2ndLd-Writethru a0739 08-31 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Delta, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Industry Analysts Say Delta's Reputation Should Survive
Intact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 13th graf, `Anthony Hatcher...' to CORRECT name to
Hatch.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines Inc. has grown from a cropduster
to the nation's third-largest airline since it began operations six
decades ago flying from Dallas to Jackson, Miss.
   A Delta Boeing 727, Flight 1141 which originated in Jackson,
crashed on takeoff Wednesday at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport.
   The crash came three years and 26 days after a Delta Lockheed
L-1011 jet crashed at the same airport, killing 137 people.
Lawsuits seeking millions of dollars in damages from that crash are
still in court, although some already have resulted in
multimillion-dollar judgments against Delta.
   Last year, Delta suffered a spate of embarrassments: Pilots
landed at the wrong airport or on the wrong runway; one plane
plummeted toward the ocean because the pilot mistakenly shut off
the engines; another plane was involved in a near miss over the
Atlantic.
   Last year, Delta also grew by acquiring Western Airlines in an
$860 million merger.
   Through it all, Delta has maintained a reputation as a well-run,
safe and financially secure airline.
   ``I don't think the reputation is undeserved,'' and it probably
won't change, said Robert Decker, an airline industry analyst with
Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
   ``If you ask people in airline maintenance who they think does
the best job, Delta's almost always the name mentioned first,''
said John Pincavage, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the airline is not afraid its
reputation will suffer greatly because of the crash.
   ``You have to realize Delta flies more flights than any airline
in the world,'' he said. ``We operate more flights so we have
greater exposure. You have to put it in perspective. .... You look
at our overall record and it's quite good.''
   Delta's common stock dropped $1 a share at news of the crash,
but recovered half the loss by the close of trading to stand at
$46.50.
   Analysts attributed the stock drop as much to a round of fare
reductions touched off Tuesday by Continental Airlines as to the
crash itself.
   Anthony Hatch, an analyst in New York with Argus Research,
called Delta ``a terrifically well run airline.'' He said Delta
survived the embarrassing incidents last year because ``it had so
much good will in the bank.''
   Eastern Airlines, Delta's chief competitor, has been rocked by
safety investigations of its aircraft and labor troubles. The
airline has cut back on its routes; a plan to lay off 4,000
employees was blocked this week by a federal judge.
   Delta began corporate life as the world's first cropdusting
service _ Huff Daland Dusters, a division of Huff Daland
Manufacturing Co. of Ogdensburg, N.Y.
   Then in 1928, the company, led by Collett Woolman, broke away
from the parent company to form Delta Air Service with headquarters
in Monroe, La. Passenger service began in 1929 with 90 mph flights
from Dallas to Jackson.
   Woolman, who ran the company until his death in 1966, set the
tone for Delta including a unique tradition of having pilots greet
passengers as they leave each flight.
   The company changed its name in 1930 to Delta Air Corp. and
later to Delta Air Lines Inc., and moved headquarters to Atlanta in
the early '40s. For the annual meeting, however, the company leaves
its headquarters at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport and
returns to Monroe.
   Delta's growth was spurred in the early years as it added routes
in the South and merged with other airlines in 1953 and 1972. But
the biggest step came in 1987, when Delta completed an $860 million
merger with Western Airlines Inc., making it the nation's third
largest airline in terms of numbers of passengers carried.
   Delta, which has 48,000 employees, posted a profit of $306.83
million on $6.92 billion in revenues during the fiscal year ended
June 30.
</TEXT>
