<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0634 08-31 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail Workers Launch 24-Hour Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with comment from union,
private mail carriers; picks up 10th pvs: `Alan Tuffin...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of government postal workers sealed mail
boxes, stopped sorting letters and walked off their routes
Wednesday to protest bonus payments that vary by region.
   Private delivery companies welcomed the extra business, saying
it will prove they can compete.
   The Union of Communication Workers called a 24-hour nationwide
strike, but the Royal Mail disputed the union's claim that nearly
all its 140,000 letter carriers and letter sorters had stopped
working.
   ``It's very patchy, a patchy situation,'' said Sally Williams, a
Royal Mail spokeswoman. ``While there's certainly support for the
strike, nevertheless quite a number of staff have turned up for
work.''
   She said the post office had repeatedly offered to continue
talks with the union and had been ``as flexible as we can.''
   The union's other 60,000 members either work for the state
telephone monopoly or for the post office in administration or
counter services, which were not involved in the dispute, said a
union spokesman.
   Ms. Williams said mail was being sorted and delivered in some
areas, particularly the southeast and southwest, although she did
not have figures for how many employees had shown up for work.
   Counter services were not disrupted at any of the striking Royal
Mail post offices in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland,
although letter boxes had been sealed, she said.
   It was the first national strike at Royal Mail since a 1971
walkout which collapsed after 47 days.
   The stoppage increased demands for Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative government to end the Royal Mail's
near-monopoly on the delivery of letters and parcels. Since she
came to power in 1979, her government has sold off to private
enterprise large sectors of state-owned assets under its
denationalization program.
   The Royal Mail has the exclusive right to collect, sort and
deliver all mail with a postal charge of less than one pound
($1.60). The cost of mailing an ordinary letter in Britain through
the Royal Mail is 18 pence (30 cents).
   TNT Mailfast, a company claiming to be the largest private
carrier in Britain, said business rose 500 percent on Wednesday and
was expected to produce long-term benefits.
   ``People are getting a bit upset about the threat of strikes all
the time,'' said general manager John Hartle. ``More and more
people who come over to us are tending to stay.''
   Alan Tuffin, general secretary of the union, said the union was
``going to throw the nation's mail into chaos.''
   The dispute concerns bonus payments for new recruits in London
and southeastern England, where living costs are higher than in the
rest of Britain and where the Royal Mail has trouble recruiting and
keeping staff because of high employment and competition for staff.
   The union wants the bonuses paid to all new recruits throughout
the country or not paid at all. Tuffin said he fears the Royal Mail
management eventually wants to introduce differentials in basic pay
for different areas and end national pay bargaining agreements.
   The bonuses range from $12.67 to $33.80 a week. The Royal Mail
said that with the bonuses, first-year recruits in central London
earn a basic $206 a week. It said the average wage for all postal
workers in central London was $405 a week.
</TEXT>
