<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     08-31 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson And Koch Meet And Make Up, Warily</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic candidate Jesse Jackson and
New York City Mayor Edward I. Koch promised Wednesday to put aside
their political animosity and work together to elect Michael
Dukakis to the presidency.
   ``April 1988 is behind us. November 8 and the elections of next
year are ahead of us,'' Jackson said after a more than two-hour
peace session convened by Gov. Mario Cuomo at his Manhattan office.
``We're moving in that direction.''
   Then Koch, who apologized for the stridency of his attacks on
Jackson during New York's primary in April, said, ``I couldn't add
a sentence that would improve'' on Jackson's words.
   Jackson and Koch said the focus of the meeting was finding a
``common ground,'' centering on their commitment to the Dukakis
campaign, voter registration and an agenda of urban policies.
   Democratic nominee Dukakis is battling Republican George Bush in
a close race for the White House.
   Last April, Koch endorsed Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee in
the Democratic primary and suggested that Jews would be ``crazy''
to vote for Jackson in light of his position on the Middle East.
   On Wednesday, Koch praised Jackson for his ``generosity of
spirit.''
   But Jackson's actions contradicted the upbeat words. At no point
during the news conference did the Democratic leader stand beside
Koch, and he kept a dour expression, despite several attempts at
levity by the mayor.
   Cuomo, who stood between the two men as they addressed a
jam-packed news conference, said it was difficult for Koch and
Jackson _ but especially for Jackson _ to sit down and discuss a
truce.
   ``We decided it is better to compromise and conciliate than
criticize. We should replace criticism with constructive
compromise,'' Cuomo said.
   Jackson told the news conference that it was ``in our best
interest to act like mature adults and stay above attacks on
integrity.''
   Jackson said he bore no animosity toward Koch, who seemed to
surprise the civil rights activist by shaking his hand after
addressing the crowd.
</TEXT>
