<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-VonFritsch     08-31 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Von Fritsch,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Dies Of Stroke At Age 82</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunther Von Fritsch, an original
director of ``The March of Time'' newsreels who later directed TV
drama including ``The Lawman'' and ``77 Sunset Strip,'' has died of
a stroke. He was 82.
   Von Fritsch died Saturday night at Huntington Memorial Hospital.
   Born in Pula, Yugoslavia, of Austrian parents, Von Fritsch came
to the United States in 1930 after graduating from The Government
Film School in Paris.
   He started his American film career as an editor of foreign
films for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
   He directed ``The March of Time'' _ a newsreel series shown in
movie theaters before the feature attraction. The series, launched
in 1935 by Time Inc., was considered revolutionary at its
introduction.
   Von Fritsch entered the U.S. Army Signal Corps in 1943, where he
remained until the end of World War II. After the war, he was
involved in the making of Army training films for the U.S. State
Department in West Berlin.
   Von Fritsch directed several television series in the 1950s and
1960s, including ``Flash Gordon,'' ``77 Sunset Strip,'' and ``The
Lawman.'' He also directed a Disney feature film called
``Snowbear.''
   Von Fritsch is survived by his wife, Hinemoa; daughters
Antoinette Beatty of Albuquerque, N.M., and Katharine Deyhimy of
Thousand Oaks; and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
