<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DroughtForecast     08-31 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Forecast,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relief For Fire-Ravaged Northwest Predicted in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire-ravaged Northwest can expect little
relief from unusually hot, dry weather until a trend toward rain
and cooler temperatures begins in October, the National Weather
Service said Wednesday.
   Above-normal temperatures will persist over much of the West
during the next five days through the Labor Day weekend, government
forecasters said, while seasonable temperatures can be expected
elsewhere. Widespread rain will fall from the Great Lakes region to
the Eastern states.
   The picture will remain pretty much the same through Sept. 10,
the service said. Most of the nation except for the East and Gulf
coasts will be dry, with high temperatures over most of the West
and Northern Plains states and cool weather east of the Mississippi
Valley.
   The Pacific Northwest, which has battled widespread forest fires
in recent weeks, will continue to suffer abnormally warm, dry
weather throughout September until a wet, cooling trend begins.
   ``Only the longer outlook through November brings cool, wet
conditions to the Northwest,'' the service said. It should be
warmer in the Southwest and California and most areas of the East,
with rain extending up the Mississippi and Ohio valleys to the
Great Lakes and mid-Atlantic regions.
   Streamflows are expected to remain below average across much of
the country. Although tropical storm Chris dumped four to six
inches of rain across the Atlantic Coast this week, the boost to
streamflows in that area will subside in a few days, the forecast
said.
   Water reserves at major reservoirs remain average to below
average for this time of year across much of the country, the
Weather Service said.
</TEXT>
