<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-Survivors 1stLd-Writethru a0712 08-31 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Survivors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Heard Aircraft Crumple Before Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to add reaction from more passengers;
CORRECTS name in 4th graf to Mona Thomason and clarifies her quote;
CORRECTS Parks to Parkes in 7th graf, `Wright's traveling ...;'
CORRECTS Hammack to Hammock in 13th graf.
^By DENNE H. FREEMAN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of Delta Flight 1141 said they
heard the jetliner crumple moments before the crash Wednesday and
escaped by leaping onto the plane's red-hot wings.
   ``You're hoping you weren't going to die,'' said Penn Waugh, a
Dallas attorney who was on the Boeing 727 when it crashed on
takeoff from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, en route to
Salt Lake City. ``It's getting smoky and you're just trying to get
the hell out of the plane.''
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said 13 people were confirmed dead
and 94 survived.
   ``We were just terrified,'' said Mona Thomason, who escaped with
scrapes and bruises. ``We jumped on the wing, but it looked like we
were jumping into a pit of fire.'' She reported seeing a woman with
two children: ``She got one of them out, but I'm afraid the other
one was caught in the fire.''
   Passenger Peter Wright of Dallas said the aircraft veered to the
right on take-off, and he heard a banging noise under the carriage.
   ``Then someone said, `We're not going to make it!''' he said.
``After the crash someone kicked the door open. I jumped on the
plane, and I was lucky because I just hurt my wrist.''
   Wright's traveling companion, Geoff Parkes, said the plane lost
power as it took off, and he saw the right wing tip hit the ground.
Flames shot past his window, and jet fuel dripped down the windows.
   ``People were saying, `Let's get out of here! Let's get out!'''
Parkes said. ``I jumped on the wing following Peter and got out.''
   Jane Wood, who is six months pregnant, and her sons, Adam, 2,
and Evan, 5, escaped without serious injury by leaping through a
crack near the bulkhead.
   ``It was a big fire,'' Evan said. ``We jumped out, but we
weren't scared.''
   Jim Hammock of Garland, a Dallas suburb, said the plane bounced
three times on takeoff and skidded off the runway.
    ``We didn't make 50 feet in the air. We skidded and then the
engine exploded. There was pandemonium,'' said Hammock, whose right
sleeve was streaked with jet fuel. ``People were jumping on the
plane's wing and burning themselves on it because it was so
red-hot.''
   Melissa Jane Lewis of Tupelo, Miss., said she remembers praying
out loud and saying, ``Oh God, here we go'' as the jet went down.
   ``I felt the engines losing power and noises like tires blowing
out on takeoff,'' said Lewis, who suffered only a bruise on her
leg. ``The fuselage filled with smoke and there was a lot of noise.
   ``I hung on until the emergency door next to me opened, then I
climbed out on the wing and hit the ground running.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-US     08-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-US,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Negotiate for Possible Return Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American oilmen are negotiating quietly in
hopes of resuming Libyan operations if the next U.S. administration
ends or modifies the economic embargo imposed on Moammar Gadhafi's
government in 1985.
   In the past two years, the chairman of Libya's state petroleum
company has met with U.S. oil company officials in Geneva, Paris
and other West European cities, a West European oil company
official said Wednesday.
   He said the two sides are discussing a possible return of the
Americans under terms of an agreement signed a few months after
President Reagan imposed the embargo on Libya in 1986.
   The agreement on July 1, 1986, froze American oil company assets
and allowed the Libyans to work their oil fields, the Western
source said, with Libya assuming all costs but also taking all the
income.
   Before the embargo, Libya got 51 percent of the oil produced by
U.S. companies. The agreement provides for the same split if the
embargo is lifted and the source said of the Americans: ``They will
return.''
   U.S. companies said to be involved are Occidental Petroleum
Corp., Oasis Oil and a consortium of Conoco, Marathon and Amerada
Hess.
   The 1986 agreement expires June 30, 1989, but if the Americans
are not back by then an extension probably will be arrianged
because both sides are eager to do business again, the source said.
   An official of the state oil company said: ``We are waiting to
see what happens at the start of next year,'' and expressed a
common Libyan opinion that restrictions might be relaxed when
Reagan leaves office.
   All those who commented did so on condition of anonymity.
   Reagan imposed the sanctions in January 1986 because of
Gadhafi's alleged support of terrorism, and forbade Americaans to
work in Libya.
   The work ban has been costly for Libya. The state oil company
official said it replaced the departing American workers by
advertising around the world for highly skilled managers and
technicians.
   He said the places were filled by Britons, Canadians, Swedes,
Indians and French workers, but at a high cost. About 400 Americans
worked in the Libyan oil industry before the embargo, he said.
   Spare parts for American equipment also had to be obtained
elsewhere at higher prices.
   Lower world prices have caused Libya's oil revenue to decline
from $22 billion in 1980 to $6 billion in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1848EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0729 08-31 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges Acid Rain Reduction; Dukakis Calls Him Election-Year
Convert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with poll results, INSERT two grafs after 8th graf
pvs, Quayle was...the kitchen,'' EDITING that graf to tighten and
picking up 9th pvs, Bush stood ... of waters; Poll results
EMBARGOED till 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush promised action to reduce acid rain on
Wednesday and declared ``I am an environmentalist.'' Rival Michael
Dukakis shot back: ``Talk about an election-year convert.''
   Seeking to gain the initiative after two weeks of moribund
campaigning, the Democratic presidential nominee delivered a broad
attack on Bush for a second day, ridiculing his statements on the
environment and demanding an explanation of his role in the
Iran-Contra debacle.
   Bush, campaigning in Michigan, avoided mention of his rival's
name _ a new course after weeks of calculated attacks. But his
Republican running mate Dan Quayle picked up the cudgel and
denounced Dukakis as a ``defeatest liberal.''
   The Republicans continued to poke fun at Dukakis's aged snow
blower that became a symbol of his frugality at the Democratic
convention.
   ``His ideas are as old as that 25-year-old snow blower,'' Quayle
said in Baton Rouge, La.
   Dukakis campaign strategists were targeting Quayle, the Indiana
senator whose selection stunned even Republican insiders. Dukakis
campaign manager Susan Estrich said they would depict his selection
as an indication of poor judgment by Bush, and would make that one
of the central themes of the fall campaign.
   ``One issue we are certain to hear more of from Democrats across
the board is the selection of Senator Quayle and his record and
qualifications,'' she said at a briefing in Boston.
   Quayle was unbowed by the prospect of two more months of
personal attack, saying, ``I can stand the heat and I'll stay in
the kitchen.''
   A new ABC-Washington Post poll released Wednesday found twice as
many voters thought the Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen was more qualified than Quayle. But two-thirds said
Quayle should remain on the ticket.
   The poll showed the presidential race a statistical dead heat _
Dukakis had 48 percent to Bush's 47 percent, within the 3.5-point
margin of error of the survey Aug. 24-30 of 1,129 registered,
likely voters.
   Bush stood on the Michigan shore of Lake Erie to deliver a
speech aimed at separating himself from the Reagan administration
with more activist positions on major environmental issues of acid
rain, the ``greenhouse'' effect and pollution of waters.
   ``Polluters should pay,'' the vice president said. ``I am an
environmentalist, always have been, from my earliest days growing
up and then as a congressman ... and I always will be.''
   Bush planned a trip onto his rival's home ground on Thursday
with a visit to Boston Harbor aimed at making the harbor's
long-standing pollution problem an embarrassment to the
Massachusetts governor.
   Attempting a pre-emptive strike, Dukakis blasted the Reagan
administraiton for cutting funding for the Clean Water Act, some of
which could have been used for the harbor cleanup.
   ``We are doing it, no thanks to Mr. Bush or the
administration,'' Dukakis said.
   He displayed scorn for Bush's promise of action on acid rain,
saying Bush really would rather spend money on the Star Wars
space-based defense program than on environmental protection.
``Talk about an election-year convert,'' Dukakis said.
   Damaging increases in the acidity of rainfall has been tied to
emissions from coal-fired power plants and other sources, including
auto exhausts.
   ``On the question of acid rain, the time for study alone has
passed,'' Bush said. ``We know enough to begin taking steps to
limit future damage ... as president, I will ask for a program to
cut millions of tons of sulfer dioxide emissions by the year 2,000
and to significantly reduce nitrogen oxide emissions as well.''
   Dukakis appeared at a news conference in Boston with Maine Sen.
George Mitchell, one of the Iran-Contra investigators and co-author
of a book that criticizes Bush's role in the missiles-for-hostages
deal with Iran.
   ``The American people would like to know the answer to a
continuing question,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Mr. Bush, you sat through five meetings, five meetings on the
subject. How can you say now that you did not know that it was a
straight arms-for-hostages deal?'' Dukakis demanded.
   Quayle campaigned before students at Louisiana State University
and toured an Exxon oil refinery. He said he and Bush ``vigorously
disagree'' with Dukakis's opposition to offshore oil exploration.
   Dukakis has called for no new offshore drilling _ and has
stressed that position in California, where it is a major issue.
Campaigning in California in the spring, Bush opposed
administration plans to lease new oil plots off the California
coast and called for more study instead.
   Dukakis left Boston for California, where he planned to campaign
Thursday before stopping in other Western states Friday and
Saturday. Bush was campaigning in the Northeast on Thursday and
Friday.
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Sen. Lloyd Bentsen was
vacationing in Wyoming. His Republican counterpart was remaining in
the South the rest of the week.
</TEXT>
