<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-POWs     08-31 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-POWs,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Urges Speedy Swap of Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran urged Wednesday that an early exchange of prisoners be
arranged with Iraq, official Tehran radio reported.
   In Paris, the daily newspaper Le Monde quoted Velayati as saying
Iraqi negotiators have dalayed progress on prisoner exchange and
other issues in a settlement of the 8-year-old war.
   He said the purpose was to force concessions from Iran on the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms their southern border
and is Iraq's only outlet to the Persian Gulf, Le Monde reported.
   Tehran radio said Velayati made the comments to Iranian
reporters in Geneva, where peace talks were stalled for the fifth
straight day.
   ``Our aim is that the exchange of prisoners of war should take
place as soon as possible,'' Velayati said. ``The very urgent
problems facing Iranian families need to be resolved (so that) our
loved ones, who have been captured, may return to their homes.''
   Iran has listed 46,098 prisoners in its camps, but U.N.
officials say many have not been unregistered and the real number
may be about 70,000.
   Iraq furnished a list of 18,139 Iranian prisoners as of Aug. 1,
but Iraqi authorities told U.N. officials many recent detainees had
not been registered. U.N. officials believe that could bring the
total to 35,000.
   Velayati also called for renewed efforts to return Iraqi
refugees to Iraq, the radio report said.
   Thousands of Kurdish civilians fled to Iran because of battles
between the Iraqi army and Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas. Other
refugees are Shiite Moslems from southern Iraq.
   Velayati declared, according to the radio: ``Fundamental
thinking must be done in order to facilitate the honorable return
of Iraqi refugees, be they Kurds or Arabs, to their own country,
and in order to restore these people's rights.''
   No official count of the refugees has been given.
   Le Monde quoted Velayati as saying the Iraqis hoped to win
sovereignty over the Shatt-al-Arab, and ``If we give in to these
Iraqi demands, nothing guarantees us that they will not draw up
other conditions just as difficult. Why would we be the only ones
to make concessions?''
   The paper also quoted Velayati as claiming in an interview that
Iraq still hold more than 380 square miles of Iranian territory,
including the towns of Khosravi and Naft Shahr, but Iran had
withdrawn from all Iraqi territory.
</TEXT>
