<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     08-31 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Being Cut Back, But Spokeswoman Says No Retreat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-abortion group said Wednesday it will
scale back the sit-ins that have led to hundreds of arrests at
Atlanta abortion clinics and will encourage jailed protesters to
identify themselves and leave jail.
   An abortion clinic official called the moves a defeat for the
New York-based anti-abortion group, Operation Rescue.
   ``In light of all the other false claims they've made, this is a
graceful way to bow out,'' said Lynne Randall, executive director
of the Feminist Women's Health Center.
   But Julie Nash, media coordinator for Operation Rescue,
answered, ``That's wishful thinking on their part. They don't know
us and they don't know what we're capable of.''
   She said the group plans to recruit and conduct training in
non-violent protest techniques for an Oct. 5-8 blitz in Atlanta
comparable to sit-ins staged at New York City abortion clinics in
May. She said 1,648 people were arrested then and some clinics were
temporarily closed.
   About 25 of the more than 700 people arrested in a month of
Atlanta sit-ins remained in jail Wednesday, down from as many as
250 earlier, Ms. Nash said.
   Police spokesman Cal Jackson said 24 protesters were in city
holding facilities at the latest count Tuesday, and a Fulton County
Sheriff's Department officer, who asked not to be identified, said
two protesters were still in the county jail Wednesday.
   Some protesters spent up to 40 days in jail, often fasting,
before giving their names and being released on bond or on their
own recognizance, Ms. Nash said.
   ``The demonstrations will be on a back burner for six weeks. We
might do one a week. ... We're getting ready for a long struggle
here,'' Ms. Nash said.
   Mass arrests of the demonstrators began during the Democratic
National Convention July 19. Many identified themselves only as
Baby John Doe or Baby Jane Doe, in symbolic solidarity with aborted
fetuses, and city officials would not release them until they
provided their real names.
   The demonstrators originally planned to remain jailed only
during the Democratic convention, Ms. Nash said. The organization
dug in and called for more people to go to jail when the city
continued to insist that the protesters identify themselves.
   She said Operation Rescue changed its tactics because of ``the
people in the jail who wanted to come out and recruit.''
   Ms. Randall said the group had to give up because it failed to
pack local jails or to shut down a clinic.
   ``People were disgusted with their tactics,'' Ms. Randall said.
``They were mean and vicious to the clients, to the police, to the
(abortion) providers.''
</TEXT>
