<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirShow-Survivors     08-31 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show-Survivors,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims To Be Hospitalized For Eight Weeks; Other Victims Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three American servicemen and an
Italian soldier will undergo up to eight weeks' treatment for
third-degree burns suffered in an air show disaster in West
Germany, doctors said Wednesday.
   The four are being treated at Brooke Army Medical Center, where
a family of three Americans also was headed Wednesday after being
put on a plane from a West German hospital.
   The four servicemen arrived early Wednesday via a C-141 cargo
plane. Three were in guarded condition, said Dr. Basil Pruitt, head
of the burn unit.
   They were identified as Air Force Master Sgt. Stephen Hull, 31,
stationed at Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio; Army 1st Lt. Kim
Strader, 41, of Salt Lake City; Army Pfc. Myron Riggs, 24, of
Pittsburgh; and Anderea, or Andrew, DelaRosa, 33, a sergeant major
assigned to the Italian Embassy.
   ``In all of the patients, the majority of the burns are
third-degree, which means that ultimately considerable skin
grafting will have to be done to close the wounds,'' Pruitt said at
a news conference.
   He said the four would be in the hospital between six and eight
weeks, but he declined to discuss each case specifically.
   Two suffered from smoke inhalation, one has a head injury and
another has a broken left leg, which may have to be amputated, he
said.
   The victims were among those injured Sunday when three Italian
jets crashed during an air show at Ramstein Air Force Base. More
than 40 people were killed and 500 were injured.
   ``During the first two-to-three-day period, the main
consideration centers on maintaining vital organ function and
preventing shock and then the care centers on the care of the wound
to remove dead tissue and effect a timely closure of the wound by
skin grafting,'' Pruitt said.
   Also on Wednesday, officials said Jeffrey McCanch, his wife,
Tammy, and their 2-year-old son, Jeffrey Jr., were put on a plane
headed to the medical center from West Germany, where they had been
undergoing treatment for injuring suffered in the air show crash.
   On Monday, a five-member team of burn specialists from the
center flew to West Germany to help treat victims.
   The center's 40-bed burn unit has 240 physicians, nurses and
support personnel and is the U.S. military's only burn-treatment
facility. Among the recent patients of the burn unit were sailors
injured during attacks in the Persian Gulf the past 15 months.
</TEXT>
