<1ST_LINE>u a AM-US-MexicoEarthquake 1stLd-Writethru a0660 08-31 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mexico Earthquake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0660,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baja California Quake Registers 5.1, No Damage or Injuries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with comments from Mexican authorities,
California seismologists</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICALI, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake jolted northern
Baja California on Wednesday, but there were no reports of damage
or injuries, officials said.
   The quake, which was felt as far north as Orange County in
Southern California, struck at 9:44 a.m. and measured 5.1 on the
Richter scale, said Hall Dailey, spokesman at the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena, Calif.
   The temblor was centered near Laguna Salada, a small
agricultural community 32 miles south of here and 90 miles
southeast of San Diego, Dailey said.
   ``All is normal,'' said Enrique Haje, a Mexicali Fire Department
training officer. ``The earthquake was very short and there were no
accidents or damage,'' he said.
   ``It was not on any major fault,'' said Jill Hammond of the
seismology laboratory at Scripps Institute of Oceanography in La
Jolla, Calif. ``It's really of very little significance. There's
really nothing much down there,'' she added, referring to the arid,
sparsely populated area where the quake was centered.
   Just north of the border in Calexico, Calif., police Cmdr.
Torivio Flores said: ``Some people in the building here felt it.
But it didn't feel like much.''
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. An earthquake of 5 on the Richter scale can cause
considerable damage in the local area.
</TEXT>
