<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     08-31 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Nuclear Delegation Tours Soviet Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commission said Wednesday the Soviet nuclear power plants he
inspected are run by businesslike workers, but he could not comment
yet on their safety.
   Lando W. Zech Jr. told a news conference his team of U.S.
nuclear experts believes it is too early to form opinions about the
state of Soviet nuclear safety.
   ``We have just started (U.S.-Soviet exchanges) so it is
inappropriate that we draw conclusions,'' he said.
   Among the plants visited was Chernobyl, where a reactor
explosion April 26, 1986, killed 31 people and sent up a huge,
invisible cloud of radioactivity that spread over Europe and
eventually worked its way around the world.
   Zech and Alexander N. Protsenko, chairman of the Soviet
Committee for Utilization of Atomic Energy, signed an agreement
promising cooperation between the Soviet and U.S. governments on
promotion of civilian nuclear safety. Nuclear experts from the two
governments will exchange information, sponsor joint seminars and
regularly visit each other's countries.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev laid the
groundwork for the exchanges at their December summit in Washington.
   ``I think and I hope that this will lead to improved nuclear
reactor safety in both of our countries,'' Zech said.
   He said the people he met at the power plants were ``dedicated
to safety.''
   Delegation members realize the American and Soviet plants have
differences in design, construction and procedures, he said, but
would not elaborate.
   ``We are still assessing these differences,'' he said.
   Protsenko said Zech's private remarks to him after visiting the
nuclear facilities were invariably polite, even when Protsenko
discussed what he believed to be inadequacies.
   ``I found his comments very useful,'' Protsenko said.
   A similar Soviet delegation will visit the United States soon,
but Zech said when and what plants they would visit had not been
decided.
</TEXT>
