<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-PlaneRecord 1stLd-Writethru a0691 08-31 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Plane Record, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Problems in Plane's History</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 6th, `Bobbie Mardis...' to UPDATE with
crew record.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Delta Air Lines Boeing 727 jet that
crashed Wednesday at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport had
only minor problems in the last five years, according to Federal
Aviation Administration records.
   A service difficulty report on file at FAA headquarters in
Oklahoma City showed a power controller actuator on a wing flap on
the jet had to be replaced in July 1987 after the aileron flap on
the plane's right wing jammed.
   A power controller actuator in the flap was removed and returned
to the manufacturer, the records show. A new controller was
installed.
   Dave Jimenez, a spokesman for Boeing in Seattle, said the
actuator is like a small pump that is activated as part of the
process of operating the flaps during takeoffs and landings.
   In August 1983, inspectors found two small cracks in the
fuselage skin, the FAA said. The first crack measured one-half inch
in length at the corner of the pilot's window. The second, found in
another inspection the same month, was three-quarters of an inch
long at the upper corner of the captain's windshield, the report
said.
   Bobbie Mardis, a spokeswoman for the FAA, described the problems
as very minor.
   Ms. Mardis said the crew was identified as pilot Larry Davis,
co-pilot Carey Wilson Kirkland Jr. and flight engineer Steven Judd.
According to FAA records, none of the crew members had a record of
an accident, incident or violation, she said.
   The aircraft was built by Boeing in 1973 and delivered new to
Delta.
   Ms. Mardis said the aircraft accident-incident report for the
plane showed that on Nov. 13, 1986, at Raleigh, N.C., the aircraft
didn't stay at the altitude assigned by air traffic controllers.
   The jetliner was was powered by JT8D engines manufactured by
Pratt & Whitney, based in East Hartford, which sent two
investigators to the scene.
   The engines are a mainstay of the airline industry, according to
David M. Long, a Pratt & Whitney spokesman. Long said the company
routinely sends its investigators to crashes in which aircraft are
powered by Pratt & Whitney engines.
   Long said it was ``way to early'' to speculate on the cause of
the crash.
   ``We're just really collecting information and trying to learn
more ourselves. We have learned to wait until the facts come
along,'' Long said.
   The JT8D received its initial certification from the FAA in 1967
and about 10,000 are now in use. It provides a thrust at takeoff of
14,000 to 18,000 pounds, according to Pratt & Whitney documents.
   Problems with JT8D engines were cited as contributing factors in
1985 airline crashes in London and Milwaukee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
