<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Thornburgh-Summons     08-31 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thornburgh-Summons,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Official Issues Summons For Attorney General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania's auditor general has issued
a summons for U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to seek
information on a 1984 state contract for dump trucks said to be bad
buys.
   The summons, filed in Commonwealth Court, orders Thornburgh, a
former Pennsylvania governor, to testify before Auditor General Don
Bailey.
   A spokesman for Thornburgh, David Runkel, said the summons was
prompted by political motives. Thornburgh is a Republican, Bailey a
Democrat.
   ``It would normally be (Thornburgh's) intent to cooperate with
any legitimate questions having to do with his administration. But
this is absurd ... and Mr. Bailey knows it,'' Runkel said.
   Bailey, who is seeking re-election, raised the contract issue
earlier this month in a statement submitted to the Senate
Judiciairy Committee, which reviewed Thornburgh's nomination to
replace Edwin Meese as attorney general.
   Runkel said the matter has been fully investigated by the FBI,
the state attorney general and the U.S. attorney's office and no
problems have been found.
   A spokesman with the state attorney general's office said the
matter was still under review. James West, acting U.S. attorney in
Harrisburg, said the case is not formally closed but officials are
not actively investigating it.
   The $23 million contract for 428 dump trucks was awarded when
Thornburgh was in his second term as Pennsylvania governor. Bailey
has previously criticized the contract, saying the state paid too
much for underpowered trucks.
   Bailey, in a telephone interview, said efforts to meet with
Thornburgh have been unsuccessful.
   As auditor general, Bailey is authorized to gather information
on state matters under his jurisdiction, such as contracts, but
cannot prosecute if he finds evidence of wrongdoing. Such
information would have to be forwarded to appropriate agencies,
such as the state attorney general.
   However, he can issue summonses to compel testimony in matters
under review.
</TEXT>
