<HEAD>Judge Approves Settlement of Challenger Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marking the final legal chapter in the
nation's worst space disaster, a federal judge has approved the
settlement of a lawsuit filed by the widow of Challenger astronaut
Michael Smith.
   Jane J. Smith filed a $1.5 billion lawsuit against Morton
Thiokol Inc., maker of the booster rocket blamed for the Jan. 28,
1986, explosion that killed seven astronauts. Terms of the
settlement were kept secret.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. approved the
settlement Tuesday.
   Morton Thiokol and the government reached a $7,735,000
settlement with four astronauts' families, those of Challenger
commander Francis Scobee, Ellison Onizuka, Bruce Jarvis and teacher
Christa McAuliffe.
   Morton Thiokol itself settled claims by relatives of Ronald
McNair and Judy Resnick. The terms of those were kept secret.
   Mrs. Smith now lives with her three children _ Scott, 19,
Alison, 17, and Erin, 11 _ south of Houston, near the Johnson Space
Center.
   ``We've had ups and downs,'' she said. ``They miss their father
terribly, just as I do.''
