<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Mandela     08-31 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Mandela,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mandela Moved To Private Clinic, Possibly Setting Stage For
Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed black nationalist
Nelson Mandela has been moved from a hospital to a private clinic
while he recuperates from tuberculosis, the government said
Thursday. The move sets the stage for a possible release from
government custody.
   Mandela, 70, was transferred on Aug. 12 from Pollsmoor Prison,
to nearby Tygerberg Hospital, where he was diagnosed with the
disease.
   Mandela, leader of the outlawed African National Congress, has
been in prison for 26 years.
   He has been making a speedy recovery from his illness, his
doctors have said, and was moved late Wednesday night to the
Constantiaberg Clinic in Cape Town, a spokesman for the prison
service, Danie Immelman, told the independent South African Press
Association.
   ``Nelson Mandela's condition has improved to such an extent that
his further treatment in the Tygerberg Hospital was no longer
necessary,'' Immelman was quoted as saying.
   The spokesman gave no indication of how long would be in the
clinic or what the conditions of his stay would be like.
   The move appears to confirm widespread speculation that Mandela
would be placed in a private clinic and gradually reintroduced to
the South African public before the government decides whether to
release him outright.
   Under this widely accepted scenario, Mandela is expected to have
access to a greater number of visitors and possibly even allowed to
conduct media interviews.
   Mandela's full recuperation is likely to at least several weeks
and after that period, the government can then choose whether to
send him back to prison or grant him freedom.
   President P.W. Botha, in a major speech two weeks ago, said he
was seriously considering releasing Mandela, the country's
best-known black leader.
   Mandela has been jailed since 1962 and is serving a life
sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-led
government. His continued imprisonment has the government in a
difficult bind.
   If Botha releases Mandela, the president risks an enormous white
backlash and the possibility of reactivating militant black
opposition that has been largely suppressed under the 26-month-old
state of emergency.
   If Botha keeps Mandela in prison, there could be widespread
black unrest if the country's preeminent black leader dies in
prison.
   Nationwide municipal elections are set for Oct. 26, further
complicating Botha's dilemma. The government is engaged in a
massive campaign to encourage blacks to vote in municipal township
elections, but it also faces a growing threat from conservative
whites.
   Mandela's release would likely encourage black voters to go to
the polls, but could harm Botha's national party in the separate
white local elections.
   The different race groups vote in separate local elections but
the nation's black majority has no vote in national affairs.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Botha has offered since 1985 to release Mandela if he will
renounce violence. However, Mandela has said that the government's
1960 decision to ban the then-peaceful African National Congress
left him no choice but to fight.
   Mandela has said he will disavow violence only if the ANC is not
longer banned, apartheid is dismantled and blacks are given a voice
in national affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
