<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LetterCarriers     08-31 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Letter Carriers,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service, Union Sign Pact To Reduce Grievances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service and the National
Association of Letter Carriers signed a ``joint commitment''
Wednesday to cut by half thousands of expensive grievance appeals,
arbitrations and employment discrimination complaints annually.
   The non-binding agreement to improve the labor-management
climate is the first ever signed by the Postal Service with a union
representing its employees.
   According to Postal Service records, 19,543 grievances were
appealed beyond the local level by members of the Letter Carriers
union in the 12 months ending Aug. 1, and 10,766 individual
disputes were taken to arbitration.
   In addition, members of the union filed 2,128 complaints of age,
sex or race discrimination against the Postal Service with the
federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
   The two-page accord said a joint employee involvement process by
the Postal Service and the 310,000-member union has improved
labor-management relations over the past five years.
   However, it added that ``tension and antagonism remain at an
intolerable level in many work locations ... and the number of
grievances filed and arbitrations conducted is unacceptable.''
   The accord was worked out after Postmaster General Anthony M.
Frank became the first person ever holding that post to address a
postal union convention when he spoke to the Letter Carriers last
month in Portland, Ore.
   ``These processes ... break down the old `them' and `us'
attitudes and promote a positive spirit of cooperation,'' he said.
``In short they save money for both sides, improve productivity
(and) reduce workplace stress.''
   Postal Service officials said the cooperation agreement does not
alter any terms of a 40-month labor contract signed last summer.
</TEXT>
