<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-USTrade     08-31 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-US Trade,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Of Commons Approves Free-Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's allies in the
House of Commons approved free-trade legislation Wednesday to
eliminate economic barriers with United States.
   But members of the opposition-dominated Senate say they will
stall the bill.
   With both sides waving Canadian flags and the opposition singing
the national anthem, the Commons voted 177-64 for the agreement
signed in January by Mulroney and President Reagan.
   The Progressive Conservatives, with 207 of the 282 seats in the
Commons, easily out-voted the combined opposition and sent the bill
to the Senate.
   The Liberals and New Democrats, who call the trade deal a
sellout of Canadian sovereignty, interrupted the final vote by
singing ``O Canada.''
   During two raucous votes on opposition amendments, Speaker John
Fraser admonished members of Parliament to settle down and asked
New Democrats and Conservatives alike to put down their Canadian
flags and pins.
   But the bill, which would amend 27 federal statutes to make
Canada's border more open to American goods and services, faces a
rough road ahead.
   Mulroney has suggested strongly that he will call a federal
election this fall before the scheduled Jan. 1 launch of the trade
treaty.
   And the Liberal majority in the Senate has promised to stall the
legislation until the issue is decided one way or another in an
election.
   U.S. legislation on the treaty has been approved by the U.S.
House of Representatives and is expected to pass the Senate later
this month.
   Gordon Ritchie, Canada's deputy chief trade negotiator over the
two years of talks with the United States, said the agreement will
not be in effect until the deal gets through the Canadian Senate
and the prime minister actually exchanges a letter of ratification
with the United States president.
   ``We're saving the champagne for the ratification,'' said
Ritchie.
   Public opinion surveys indicate Canadians are almost equally
divided on the merits of the agreement but generally agree on thing
_ the issue is confusing.
   Under the trade agreement, both countries would begin phasing
out border taxes, quotas, standards and other regulations that stop
or discourge trade.
   Future disputes could be referred to five-member panels of trade
experts from both countries for settlement.
   The Canadian government has touted the deal as a boon for
business and jobs as well as cutting the $2 billion a year in
tariffs that Canadian businesses and consumers have to pay on
imports from the United States.
   The opposition says other Canadian jobs will be lost as U.S.
business moves into the Canadian market. Consumers will only see a
fraction of the value of the tariff cuts, they say.
   The agreement was reached last fall after 18 months of talks
between the two nations.
</TEXT>
