<DOCNO> AP880831-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-31 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunshine, Dry Air Makes For A Pleasant Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Plenty of sunshine made it a wonderful day across most of the
country Wednesday, with temperatures in the 80s in the southern and
central United States and in the 60s and 70s in the north.
   A high pressure system centered over northern Ohio-Pennsylvania
border brought clear skies and dry air to an area stretching from
New England into the southern Plains.
   Another high pressure system over southwest British Columbia
provided a pleasant day in the Northwest, with afternoon
temperatures in the 60s and 70s.
   Gusty winds developed in the northern Plains, blowing from 20 to
35 mph across parts of Kansas and Nebraska.
   Rainfall was restricted to southern coastal areas along the
Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico, with showers and thunderstorms
scattered across Florida and westward along the Gulf coast as far
as southernmost Texas. There also were scattered showers in
east-central Arizona and west-central New Mexico.
   In the desert Southwest, it was anothger scorching day, with the
mercury rising over 100 in parts of Southern California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 106 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif. The nation's low early Wednesday was 35 degrees at Butte,
Mont.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the southern Atlantic states and Florida across the
Gulf coast into the Texas Panhandle and over the central and
southern Plains. Showers and thunderstorms were expected to develop
along a cold front over Michigan's Upper Peninsula and northwest
Wisconsin. The rest of the nation can expect mostly sunny skies.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 80s or 90s across
much of the nation, but in the 70s over the northern Great Lakes
and the upper Ohio Valley into New England and between 100 and 110
degrees from south-central Oregon through the valleys of California
into the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
