<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlaneCrash-Rescuers 1stLd-Writethru a0780 08-31 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash-Rescuers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Crash Revives Memories Of Earlier Delta Accident For
Rescuers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th, `Flight 191...' to include comment
from hospital worker.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the passengers who survived the
crash of a Delta Airlines jet on Wednesday may owe their lives to
another crash three years ago, rescuers said.
   ``Last time we didn't know what to expect. This time we're a
little more organized,'' said Ray Cartier, a Red Cross volunteer.
   ``Last time'' was the crash of Delta Flight 191, a Lockheed
L-1011, on the other side of Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport three years ago in which 137 people died.
   ``Flight 191 definitely gave us more experience,'' said Mike
Sympson, paramedic supervisor for the airport police and fire
department. ``When we got here, it was click, click, click.''
   ``There was a lot of preparation done because of the last one,''
said Michael Muncy, a lab technician at the 314-bed Harris
Methodist H.E.B. Hospital, where many of the injured were taken.
``Everyone was right in place. There was no wasted motion. We knew
just what to do.''
   Sympson arrived aboard one of the first three emergency vehicles
at the crash scene just three minutes after the 9:03 a.m. accident
at the airport's west end.
   Dozens of fire trucks, helicopters and police vehicles converged
on the prairie southwest of the main airport tower, and within 10
minutes some of the first victims were being transported to
hospitals, Sympson said.
   ``When we got to the plane, the majority of the survivors were
on the grass, away from the plane,'' Sympson said.
   A van driver, Eusebio Padilla, said he was several hundred yards
away when the plane cracked open and a column of flame erupted from
the tail area.
   Sympson and others in the first wave of rescuers concentrated on
establishing a triage area where survivors could be evaluated and
the most seriously injured expedited to hospitals.
   The paramedics said all they were told only that the plane was a
Boeing 727. It wasn't until thick, black smoke cleared 15 or 20
minutes later that they discovered they were working on another
Delta plane.
   When paramedic Jim Hartman arrived on the scene, ``all I heard
was screaming from the people on the ground.''
   ``Some of them (the survivors) were in severe shock, but some of
them were joking, trying to I guess make the situation easier,''
Hartman said. ``One guy laughed and said, `Boy, I'm not going to
take an airplane home.' Can't really blame him at that point.''
   Brian McKinney, an airport Department of Public Safety officer,
was off duty when he heard about the crash on the news and came in
to work about 9:40 a.m.
   ``I just helped pull bodies out _ about nine,'' said McKinney.
``They were charred. Some of them were in seats. Some of them
weren't in seats. Some had belts on we had to take off.
   ``The ones that I pulled out were in the back of the plane,'' he
said.
   Sympson said this crash was similar to the one three years ago.
   ``There was not a big difference,'' Sympson said. ``There was
fire, smoke and you didn't know what you were going to find. I'm
simply amazed there were this many survivors.''
   Paramedic Robert Seadore said he was the first paramedic to
arrive at both crashes. ``I tell you I had some flashbacks,''
Seadore said of Wednesday's disaster.
   One result of the 1985 crash was a greater emphasis on helping
rescuers cope with what they saw and had to do when they arrived to
help Wednesday.
   McKinney, still wearing his silver flame-proof coveralls and
hard hat, said those who helped pull victims from the plane were
sent to a stress center where they received tetanus shots. Then
they were taken to a stress clinic for counseling.
   ``Anyone who pulled out bodies went through that,'' he said.
``You never get used to it. But you got a job to do, and you just
go ahead and do it.''
   Hundreds of people were on hand at the crash site within an hour
after the accident. Within two hours, volunteers from charitable
agencies had arrived to provide food and beverages to workers in
what was expected to be a day-long effort.
   ``We work with relatives and victims, ensuring they've got
nurses, preachers to talk to, and we meet their transportation
needs by taking them to the hospitals and hotels,'' Cartier said.
</TEXT>
