<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RoarkHearing     08-31 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roark Hearing,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Charleston Mayor Testifies Before Bar Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Mike Roark, battling to
save his law license after pleading guilty to drug charges,
admitted to a Bar panel Wednesday that he took no action while
prosecutor against two men who sold him drugs.
   Roark, who turned 43 on Wednesday, testified for about 25
minutes before a subcommittee of the state Bar's Legal Ethics
Committee. It is considering whether sanctions should be imposed,
up to revocation of Roark's law license, because of his guilty
pleas.
   Roark pleaded guilty to six misdemeanor federal charges of
possession of cocaine and resigned as mayor as part of the plea
agreement. He was released from federal prison on July 20 after
serving 5{ months.
   Ethics panel chairman Arthur Recht said the central issue at the
hearing is whether a public official should be treated differently
in a disciplinary matter from lawyers in private practice.
   Roark's side said he should not and asked for leniency.
   But Bar disciplinary counsel Jack Marden argued that Roark used
his position to shield those supplying drugs.
   Under cross-examination, Marden asked Roark, who admitted using
drugs while Kanawha County prosecutor, whether he tried to bring
charges against two men who supplied drugs to him and were
convicted by federal prosecutors.
   ``I took no steps to prosecute either or advise anybody,'' Roark
said.
   Kanawha County Prosecutor Charlie King and Peter Brown, both top
assistants to Roark when he was prosecutor, said Roark showed no
leniency toward drug dealers. But King said he could not recall
Roark participating in any drug prosecutions.
   The state Bar rested its case against Roark without calling a
witness.
   On the stand, Roark took full blame for his actions and said he
was sorry for what had happened.
   ``I have no excuses and I offer none,'' said Roark, who has been
practicing law since his release from prison. ``I obviously knew
what I was doing was wrong at the time I was doing it.''
   But Roark said he believes that he has paid and pays daily for
his actions. He asked the panel to allow him to maintain his law
license so he can make restitution to the community for his
misbehavior.
   Recht said the panel should render a decision sometime in
October. Its recommendation goes to the full Legal Ethics
Committee, which makes its final report to the state Supreme Court.
The court can then agree to the recommendation, modify or reject it.
   Former Charleston Police Chief Jack Buckalew, called on behalf
of the Roark, testified Wednesday that Roark never attempted to
interfere with his agency.
   Buckalew said his drug officers generally worked under federal
supervision and he had little control over them anyway. But he did
say that in 1985 he was aware that Roark was being investigated
concerning drug matters.
   ``Did Roark try to curtail drug enforcement?'' asked James
McIntyre, Roark's attorney.
   ``No, he did not,'' replied Buckalew, police chief from 1983 to
1985.
   On cross-examination, Marden asked Buckalew whether Roark had
ever lied to him.
   ``Yes, he did,'' Buckalew said. ``He was not truthful as to his
plea of guilty to cocaine use. He indicated to me he was not using
it.''
</TEXT>
