<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Library     08-31 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Library,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Library Plans Raise Environmental Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Library hit a snag Wednesday when questions were raised at an
environmental hearing about the project's effects on air quality,
plant life and traffic congestion.
   The Ventura County Environmental Report Review recessed the
hearing for a week to get more information. At next week's meeting,
the committee could either approve the library project, delay a
decision again or decide that an Environmental Impact Report is
needed.
   The Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation wants to build the
library on a 100-acre site which lies partly within a greenbelt
area that is protected from large-scale development by a
decade-old, non-binding agreement among the communities of
Moorpark, Simi Valley and Thousand Oaks.
   The library, scheduled for completion in 1991, would house
President Reagan's White House papers and would contain museum
exhibits about his administration. Like the eight existing
presidential libraries, it would be built with private funds and
then operated by the National Archives.
   Chuck Thomas, who represents the county Air Pollution Control
District on the seven-member committee, asked for the delay, saying
the district had found the project inconsistent with county air
quality standards.
   ``It would bring in a lot of additional traffic that is not
projected,'' Thomas said.
   The foundation estimates that the library would attract 350,000
visitors a year.
   The Environmental Coalition, a private environmental group in
Ventura County, said, however, it believed the number of visitors
per year could exceed 425,000.
   ``I think I would have to come down against it'' if the matter
were voted on without further investigation, Thomas told the
committee.
   Other members of the committee said they needed more information
on traffic density and the effect on vegetation before making a
decision.
   Fred Worthley, regional manager of the California Department of
Fish and Game, wrote to county officials on May 12 that an
undisclosed number of specimens of three ``sensitive plant
species'' would be harmed or destroyed by construction. He
suggested a detailed site survey ``at the appropriate time of year
when these plants can be readily identified and that the project be
redesigned to avoid these areas as much as possible.''
   Philip E. Gatch, director of planning and community development
for Thousand Oaks, said in a letter written Tuesday that part of
the public road over which traffic would travel to reach the
library site ``remains a two-lane roadway operating at a level of
service beyond its current capacity.''
   Others at the hearing said they understood this section was to
be widened before the scheduled 1991 opening of the library.
   If the project is approved by the committee, critics would have
10 days in which to appeal. The committee would hear the appeal in
another 30 days.
   If an Environmental Impact Report is required, it could take a
year or more.
   The foundation, which hopes to break ground for the library this
fall, would have the right to appeal any decision to order an
Environmental Impact Report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
