<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0775,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aides Deny Reports About Campaign Request to Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To give comment from Dukakis supporter on Atlanta meeting,
INSERT two grafs after 8th pvs, In Nashville...been invited,
picking up 9th pvs, ``We don't...the matter.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top aides to Michael Dukakis denied Wednesday that
they told Jesse Jackson not to campaign in several states as
tension between the two Democrats increased.
   Sources close to Jackson said the former presidential candidate
was angered at being told to avoid campaigning in Michigan,
Louisiana, Mississippi, Georgia, Texas, New York and Alabama.
   The sources said Dukakis officials had determined Jackson could
hurt the ticket among traditionally Democratic blue collar voters
in some states who supported Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   ``I am aware of no list of states provided to him, of states he
should not or would not or we prefer he not go into,'' said Dukakis
campaign manager Susan Estrich.
   But one aide to the Democratic nominee, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the campaign conducted polling in every state for
favorable and unfavorable opinions on Jackson ``to see how well he
can do in the fall in attracting swing voters as well as blacks.''
   The results found that in some of the primary states he won,
Jackson had high negatives among those swing voters.
   Dukakis is making a strong bid to woo those so-called Reagan
Democrats back to their former allegiance to Democratic
presidential candidates.
   In Nashville, Tennessee State Rep. Roscoe Dixon of Memphis said
Jackson has invited him and other key supporters to a meeting
Thursday in Atlanta. He said he did not know how many people have
been invited.
   U.S. Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., an Atlanta congressman and former
Jackson supporter who now co-chairs Dukakis' Georgia campaign, said
Wednesday night he intended to attend the Thursday meeting, which
he understood was called to discuss voter registration and
get-out-the-vote efforts in the South.
   Although Lewis said he did not expect a discussion on tension
between Jackson and Dukakis supporters, Dixon said he planned to
bring it up.
   ``We don't feel that we have been totally involved in the
Dukakis campaign...,'' Dixon said. ``The first thing I'm going to
do is get with Reverend Jackson in Atlanta on Thursday and find out
his thinking on the matter.''
   Jackson met with Dukakis aides in Washington last week and was
reported as angered by the suggestion he stay out of several
states. According to one participant in the discussions, who asked
not to be identified, the request was withdrawn.
   Jackson agreed he would stay out of Texas, but will campaign in
the other states. The former civil rights activist won the
Democratic contests in Michigan, Alabama, Louisiana and Mississippi
and finished ahead of Dukakis in Georgia.
   Jack Corrigan, a Dukakis campaign aide who participated in that
meeting, said no suggestion was made that he stay out of those
states.
   ``States were discussed,'' said Corrigan, but he denied it was
in the context of places where Jackson could hurt the ticket.
   Estrich said Dukakis staff were working with Jackson aides to
``establish a schedule, how best to use his limited time.''
   Dukakis aide Donna Brazile, who was not in the Thursday meeting
but works on minority outreach for Dukakis, said the Dukakis forces
have been scrupulous in contacting Jackson officials in every state.
   ``In many ways our relationship and treatment of Reverend
Jackson translates into black enthusiasm ... On the other hand, we
have to have a local strategy that involves the black community,''
she said.
   Dukakis and Jackson made a pact at the Democratic convention in
Atlanta in July that essentially was designed to give the Jackson
constituency and its issues a voice in the Democratic general
election campaign, including transferring some of Jackson's aides
and advisers to Dukakis.
   Brazile acknowledged that only two Jackson aides have been
incorprated into the Dukakis national staff, but said that on the
state and local level many former Jackson officials have been
brought into the Dukakis campaign.
</TEXT>
