<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-Flight191     08-31 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Flight 191,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Accident Comes As Lawsuit Over Flight 191 Responsibility
Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN-TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after a Delta Air Lines jet crashed on
takeoff in a severe thunderstorm at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, a federal court battle continues over responsibility for
the accident.
   On Aug. 2, 1985, Delta Flight 191 crashed and burned, killing
137 people and injuring 25 others.
   In Wednesday's crash of Flight 1141 on takeoff in cloudless
skies for Salt Lake City, 13 people were killed and 94 survived.
The plane went down at the opposite end of the airport from the
1985 crash.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators ruled in July
1986 that the Delta 191 crash occurred when the L-1101 flew into a
microburst containing several wind shears. The strong, abrupt
downward shifts in wind direction at the south end of the airport
smashed the jet into the ground.
   Lawyers for Delta and the government are continuing a
6-month-old federal trial in Fort Worth to determine
responsibility. Earlier this month, testimony was postponed until
October while a federal judge tries to clear other cases.
   Delta, which initially admitted some responsibility for the
crash, claims government air traffic controllers and weather
forecasters failed to warn the flight crew of the storm.
   The trial involving Delta, its insurers and the widow of the
pilot is the first in which a major U.S. airline has gone to court
against the government to seek damages.
   Delta officials claim the government should bear responsibility
for the crash and pay all or part of more than $90 million in
death, injury and damage claims the airline already has paid.
   More than 90 lawsuits seeking more than $200 million dollars
were filed by victims' relatives.
   Lawyers for the government contend the flight crew should have
been able to avoid the crash.
   The NTSB faulted crew training for handling wind shears and the
lack of ``definitive'' weather information as contributing factors
in the accident.
   But the Atlanta-based airline maintains the board's findings
were ``incomplete, inaccurate and most painfully flawed.''
Officials said the crew operated the craft in accordance with
Federal Aviation Administration procedures and regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0715 08-31 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0715,0909</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Calls on Workers to End Their Strikes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 8th graf pvs, `Konopka said...' to
UPDATE with union reaction at Szczecin, other detail; picks up 9th
pvs `Walesa also...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa called on
Poland's striking workers Wednesday night to settle their local
grievances and end the country's worst labor unrest in seven years.
   Walesa made the appeal hours after meeting with government
leaders on the wave of strikes that began Aug. 16 calling for
higher wages and the legalization of Solidarity.
   He said the national issues of guaranteeing trade union
pluralism and legalizing his outlawed trade federation would be
taken up in round-table discussions promised by the government in
the near future, according to a statement read by an aide, Piotr
Konopka.
   Walesa said he raised the importance of Solidarity in his
three-hour meeting with Poland's interior minister, Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczak _ his first with government leaders in six years.
   ``The participants in the discussion recognize that all affairs
related to trade union movement would be discussed by the
round-table,'' Walesa said.
   ``I propose therefore that we suspend the current strikes. I
accepted further talks with central authorities and turn to the
strike committes for the actual ending of the negotiation of other
postulates and the suspension of the strikes,'' Walesa's statement
said.
   After giving the Walesa statement, Konopka added: ``I hope that
it will appear as a historical day.''
   Konopka said Walesa conferred with strikers at the idled Lenin
shipyard, where the Solidarity leader still works as an
electrician, and the strike there could end very soon. Strikes are
in effect at nine other worksites across the country.
   Solidarity spokesman Piotr Niemczyk said later in Warsaw that
all strike committees had been informed of Walesa's statement.
   However, strike committee members in Szczecin said they will not
automatically stop the strike as long their demands concerning
local issues are not met, Niemczyk said. The committee proposed
talks with management but has so far received no reply, he said.
   Walesa went to the Roman Catholic episcopate in Warsaw where he
conferred with advisers and church officials for two hours after
his talks with Kiszczak. In Roman Catholic Poland, the church is a
power rivaling the government.
   Afterward, he said: ``I am an optimist.''
   He then stepped into a car that took him and Solidarity adviser
Tadeusz Mazowiecki from the capital to the Gdansk shipyard where
Walesa founded the union in the labor turmoil of 1980.
   In Washington, the State Department called the meeting a
``welcome and significant step forward.'' It expressed hope the
communist authorities are prepared to work with Walesa and other
leaders ``widely admired and trusted by the Polish people.''
   Meetings between Walesa and ranking Polish officials last
occurred during his internment in 1982. Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's
government imposed martial law in December 1981 to suppress
Solidarity, the first free union in the Soviet bloc, and outlawed
it in 1982.
   The current round of labor trouble began two weeks ago and at
one point idled 20 plants and mines employing 100,000 people.
   The meeting with Kiszczak took place on the anniversary of the
Gdansk agreements of Aug. 31, 1980, in which the government
recognized the Independent Self-Governing Trade Union Solidarity.
Poland's current labor unrest is the worst since that summer.
   Attending the meeting in a Warsaw villa, a location kept secret
until the talks ended, were Walesa, Kiszczak, Bishop Jerzy
Dabrowski of Warsaw and Stanislaw Ciosek, an official of the
national unity organization PRON.
   PAP, the official news agency, carried only a brief report. It
listed the participants and said they discussed ``the premises for
organizing a `round-table' meeting and the procedure of holding
it.''
   A statement from the episcopate that was approved by all
involved said Walesa raised the issue of union pluralism and the
role of Solidarity.
   ``The partners (in the discussion) stated that all problems
connected with union movement will be discussed at the round
table,'' it said. ``There are no taboo subjects.''
   Kiszczak proposed on Friday that officials hold a round-table
meeting with worker representatives to discuss labor grievances,
and the Communist Party's ruling Politburo endorsed it Tuesday.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said Tuesday such a meeting
could be held as soon as the strikes ended.
   Andrzej Stelmachowski, a lawyer and senior adviser of
Solidarity, said Walesa agreed to the idea of round-table talks,
but only if the agenda included a discussion of the trade
federation's future.
   He said Wednesday's meeting represented the beginning of a
process to resolve Poland's political and economic problems. He did
not exclude the possibility of further preparatory talks before a
round-table meeting.
   Trade unions, the right to form associations and the role of
other groups in the government's reform program are core issues for
discussion, said Stelmachowski, who is president of the Warsaw Club
of Catholic Intelligentsia and a specialist in constitutional law.
   ``The procedure and shape of Solidarity-related union
organizations must be the subject of patient negotiations, which
have to take a certain time,'' he said.
   In addition to Walesa, Kiszczak met with six other political
figures Wednesday. They included Jan Dobraczynski, the head of
PRON, and Henryk Sienkiewicz, the Solidarity leader in Silesia. PAP
identified Sienkiewicz only as an engineer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
