<HEAD>Air Force Identifies Dead American, Adds to List of Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Show Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Air Force released the
names Wednesday of an American killed in the Ramstein air show
disaster and seven still being treated at a U.S. Army hospital in
West Germany.
   The Air Force statement identified the dead American as Army
Pfc. Genevieve Riggs, 36, of the 110th Military Police Company in
Pirmasens, West Germany.
   Her husband, Sgt. Myron Riggs, also of the 110th, was one of
four people evacuated to the Brooke Army Medical Center in San
Antonio, Texas, on Tuesday for burn treatment, the Air Force said.
   ``Private Riggs is also survived by her father, Ernest W.
Hendricks, of Kearneysville, W. Va.,'' the Air Force statement said.
   The Pentagon has said six Americans died but no identities had
been released. Dozens of people were killed and scores injured
Sunday when three Italian jets collided during the air show at the
U.S. Air Base at Ramstein and one crashed in flames.
   On the list of Americans being treated at the U.S. Army's
Landstuhl hospital near Ramstein, with their conditions, were:
   _Sonya Fuller, 25, of Cheyenne, Wyo., wife of Airman Jeff Fuller
of the 66th Security Police Squadron at Sembach Air Force Base,
West Germany. Fair.
   _William Granflor, 9, son of Sgt. Guillermo Granflor of San
Gabriel, Calif., assigned to the 86th Component Repair Squadron at
Ramstein air base. Stable.
   _Sgt. Karl Heilig, 31, of San Antonio, Texas, assigned to the
86th Equipment Maintenance Squadron at Ramstein. Good.
   _Lisa A. Newton, 18, daughter of Sgt. Leon Newton of the U.S.
Army's 32nd Support Command at Worms, West Germany, no hometown
given for either. Good.
   _Roberta Nicks, 26, of Pittsburgh, Pa., wife of Army Sgt. Lonzo
Nicks, assigned to the 11th Signal Battalion, Kleber Kaserne,
Kaiserslautern, West Germany. Good.
   _David Olson, 21, son of Maj. Steven Olson of Marinette, Wis.,
assigned to the 86th Tactical Fighter Wing at Ramstein. Good.
   _Army Sgt. Alexander Tirona, 27, of Cavite, Philippines (no U.S.
address given), assigned to the 44th Signal Battalion, Kleber
Kaserne, Kaiserslautern, West Germany. Good.
   Air Force and Army officials said seven Americans who had been
hospitalized at Landstuhl were evacuated to the Brooke hospital in
San Antonio:
   _Army Sgt. Myron Riggs, 24, husband of Genevieve Riggs, no
hometown or condition given.
   _Air Force Master Sgt. Stephen Hull, 32, no hometown or
condition.
   _Army 1st Lt. Kim Strader, 30, no hometown or condition.
   _Anderea Delarosa, identified by Landstuhl officials only as a
``dependent of an American serviceman,'' no hometown or condition.
   _Air Force Sgt. Jeffrey L. McCanch, 23; his wife Tammy, 21, and
their son Jeffrey Jr., 2.
   An Air Force statement said of the McCanches: ``The child is
listed with very serious injuries. His parents are both listed in
good condition.'' It also said Sgt. McCanch graduated from high
school in Saxonburg, Pa., and entered the Air Force in Pittsburgh.
