<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Smog     08-31 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Smog,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dirty Air Prompts Emergency Measures; At Least 75 People
Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday banned half
the city's taxis and private autos from the Athens area and ordered
factories to slow down to reduce a smog cloud that sent at least 75
people to the hospital.
   The government Program for Pollution Control said the emergency
measures are to remain in effect Thursday.
   ``There is no wind and we have a high nitrogen dioxide content
in the atmosphere,'' said anti-pollution agency spokesman Dimitris
Hadjidakis.
   The agency said levels of nitrogen dioxide, a poisonous
reddish-brown gas formed from auto exhaust, reached 561 micrograms
per cubic meter Wednesday in parts of central Athens, more than
twice the danger level of 200 micrograms.
   A reading of 500 or more calls for emergency measures.
   The state-run National Center for Emergency Help said 55 people
suffering from pollution-caused heart and respiratory problems were
treated at hospital outpatient clincs in the Athens area on
Wednesday. Twenty others were hospitalized after fainting on the
capital's streets.
   A private pollution monitoring organization, the Panhellenic
Center for Ecological Studies, gave a higher figure of 309 for the
number of people requiring hospital treatment.
   Half the city's 730,000 private cars and 15,000 taxis were
banned from a 115-square mile area around the city center while
Athens' 120 biggest factories were told to reduce output by 30
percent, the Environment Ministry said.
   Only vehicles with licence plates ending in odd numbers were
allowed in the area. Both August 31 and Sept. 1 are odd-numbered
days.
   A brown smog layer forms over Athens when warm, still air
creates a temperature inversion layer in the lower atmosphere,
trapping pollutants close to the ground.
</TEXT>
