<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Air Shows,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Government Limits Air Show Stunts After German Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday it will eliminate
some stunts from military air shows after the disaster in West
Germany that killed three Italian pilots and more than 40
spectators.
   The Defense Ministry said new rules, including elimination of
certain stunts, would be in effect for an air show Sunday at Dinard
in western France. It did not elaborate on the rules.
   The ministry also pledged to look carefully at safety
precautions for celebrating the 35th anniversary of the Patrouille
de France, the nation's premier air acrobatics squad, on Oct. 9 in
Salon de Provence in southern France.
   Despite Wednesday's annoouncment, The Ministry said French
regulations on air shows ``were already more severe than in other
European countries.''
   The ministry made its statement after the collision Sunday of
three Italian airplanes during an air show at a U.S. military base
in Ramstein, West Germany. One of the airplanes hurtled into the
crowd, causing the deaths and also hundreds of injuries.
   On June 26, an Airbus 320 passenger jet crashed while making a
low pass over an air show in eastern France, killing three people.
