<1ST_LINE>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv01   08-31 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 01,0665</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Sept. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>``Value'' System For Building Savings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for a disciplined, systematic way to
build up a nest egg for college tuition or retirement?
   Consider a technique that Capt. Michael E. Edleson, an assistant
economics professor at the U.S. Military Academy in West Point,
N.Y., calls ``value averaging.''
   Edleson's idea is a new twist on the old, popular strategy known
as dollar cost averaging, which calls for investing identical
amounts at regular intervals in a vehicle such as a mutual fund.
   But unlike dollar-cost averaging, value averaging provides a
structure that tells you when to sell as well as when to buy.
   The basic idea of value averaging, described by Edleson in the
American Association of Individual Investors' AAII Journal, is to
increase the total value of your investment by a set amount each
month.
   Suppose you want to build up a mutual fund account to $24,000
over the next 10 years to help pay college costs for a child now in
second grade.
   You can pursue that goal by seeing that the account's value
increases by $200 each month through that 10-year period.
   The first month, you simply make an initial investment of $200.
Starting in the second month, you invest whatever it takes to
increase the overall value of your holdings by $200.
   If the net asset value of the fund's shares declines, you will
need to put up more than $200 in the second month. If it rises,
however, you will invest less.
   Assuming that sooner or later the fund enters a period of strong
performance, you are likely to encounter months in which price
appreciation alone increases the value of your holdings by more
than $200.
   In those instances, you don't invest any money at all. Rather,
you SELL, or redeem, enough shares to bring the monthly increase
back down to $200, perhaps by switching the surplus into a
money-market fund.
   A reserve in the money fund will help you keep the system going
in periods when the fund declines, making new monthly investments
of substantially more than $200 necessary.
   Spotted a flaw or two in this whole deal? Well yes, Edleson
concedes, there are some.
   For one thing, the monthly mathematical exercise required makes
it more complicated and time-consuming than a simple dollar-cost
averaging program.
   Investing and redeeming odd amounts regularly can incur
forbidding transaction costs _ one reason why, as Edleson says,
value averaging works best with a mutual fund that has no sales or
redemption fees and generous telephone switching privileges.
   Then there's the problem of taxes on capital gains every time
you sell. You can dodge this if you are operating inside an
individual retirement arrangement that is not subject to current
taxation.
   Otherwise, Edleson says, there is an alternative: ``Simply do
nothing when the value averaging rules indicate that you should
sell shares.''
   Under this approach, you let the surplus stand in the account
for as long as it takes to have the $200 monthly increases catch up
with it. If there is still a surplus when the 10 years are up, no
complaints _ you have exceeded your goal.
   ``This same variation lends itself well to use with dividend
reinvestment and stock purchase plans, a popular tool for
individual investors,'' Edelson notes. In such plans, selling in
small amounts is often impractical or not allowed.
   An obvious objection to this whole arrangement presents itself
readily: You are limiting what your money can achieve. The better
your fund performs, the more potential gains you will miss out on.
   ``You won't get rich quick,'' Edleson acknowledges. But the
point of the system is to encourage both buying at low prices and
selling _ or at least not buying _ at high prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Sept. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
