<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Reform-FlexibleSchools ADV04   08-31 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reform-Flexible Schools, ADV 04,0443</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Washington State Teachers Enthusiastic Over Reform Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-School Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, Reggie Sutter and fellow
teachers at Moses Lake High School had looked for ways to break the
traditional public school mold and give students the special
attention denied them in a rigid system.
   This year, Sutter and the others will get a chance to experiment
with reform, freed of state requirements under a pilot program
called ``Schools for the 21st Century'' created this year by the
state Legislature.
   He is among several hundred teachers in 21 school districts
involved in a bold plan aimed at giving the state ``a world class
education system by the 21st century,'' in the words of Gov. Booth
Gardner.
   Backed by $2.1 million in state money to pay teachers for extra
time spent planning, the program will allow the teachers to shake
up their classrooms rather than their bosses and the school boards
who've been dictating what to do.
   ``Now, with the flexibility of the 21st century program, we can
experiment. It gives us a way to create, to do something
different,'' said Sutter, who teaches Spanish and social studies in
Moses Lakes, a central Washington city about 230 miles east of
Olympia.
   Sutter says his first order of business is to expand his
homework hotline, a program in which high school students can call
peers for help with homework.
   ``We're starting a guest speaker program. We're also starting a
telephone counseling service where students can call anonymously
and get referred to places where they can get help for drug
addiction or whatever,'' Sutter said.
   Sutter's excitement can also be found at Moses Lake's Larson
Heights Elementary School. There, teachers are reorganizing
curricula and classrooms for the 300 pupils, many of whom are from
low-income families and lag in achievement.
   ``Basically, what the teachers are doing is creating
opportunities to enrich these kids, to enrich their minds,'' said
P.J. Benedetti, a district official working with the teachers on
alternative education plans.
   For example, the teachers have decided to keep Larson Heights
open until 6 p.m. each day, giving latchkey kids and others a way
to profit from free time.
   ``The kids can use the school computers. They can work on their
homework in a quiet, supervised setting. There will be storytime,
organized recreation, arts and crafts,'' Benedetti said.
   ``I don't think I've ever seen our teachers this excited or this
enthusiastic,'' said Moses Lake superintendent Ben Edlund.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
