<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview ADV00   08-31 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, ADV00,0524</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Betrayed''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa-Gavras is unique among world-class filmmakers. He alone
has made a career of polemics on such issues as military
dictatorships (``Z'') and American meddling abroad (``Missing'').
   His films have swayed world opinion while gripping audiences
with his documentary-style drama. Because no one else attacks
social ills on a regular basis, it is regrettable that he stumbles
with ``Betrayed.''
   The film begins with a Costa-Gavras imprint: a graphic depiction
of heart-pounding violence. Over the titles, an acerbic radio
talk-show host spouts insults at his favorite targets: rock music,
fat women and bigots. As he leaves the studio, he is followed by
another car, then is gunned down in a parking structure by unseen
assailants.
   The episode, obviously inspired by the murder of Denver
broadcaster Alan Berg, establishes the timeliness of ``Betrayed.''
But this early promise later dissipates in an illogical and
overstated melodrama.
   A dedicated FBI agent, Debra Winger, unwillingly accepts the
assignment of trying to infiltrate a Midwestern hate group
suspected of the broadcaster's murder. Posing as a harvester
machine driver, she quickly ingratiates herself to a good ol' boy
charmer, Tom Berenger. With his overalls, homespun manner and two
small motherless children, he seems as American as a Big Mac.
   The romance grows, and marriage is proposed. But Berenger has a
challenge for his wife-to-be: He wants her not only to approve of
his secret paramiliatry society but to participate in its robberies
and murders.
   An intriguing situation, but it is destroyed by overkill.
Winger's first trial is taking part in a midnight ``game'' in which
a young black is set loose in a thicket with a gun and 10 bullets
and hunted down by dogs and heavily armed farmers. Even ``Rambo''
fans would have trouble buying this one.
   Following the trend of recent films, Winger's FBI superiors are
portrayed as incompetents. They allow her to remain in a
life-threatening situation with no backup or support. They don't
even follow her and Berenger when the pair embark on an
assassination trip. Nor is there concern when Winger herself
commits a crime, shooting a guard during a bank robbery.
   The actors strive for credibility, but the Joe Esterhaz script
and Costa-Gavras' overzealous direction defeat them. Debra Winger's
intensity helps keep her character alive. Tom Berenger proved his
talent for portraying evil in ``Platoon,'' but he has no chance
here to reconcile the normal-seeming farmer and the hate-warped
psycho.
   The United Artists production is rated R for language and
violence. Running time: 127 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
