<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge suffered the steepest drop in eight months in July, but few
analysts expect a substantial slackening in growth anytime soon.
   The 0.8 percent decline reported Tuesday in the Commerce
Department's Index of Leading Economic Indicators was the biggest
since last November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the
aftermath of the October stock market crash.
   But economists noted that the index posted an exceptionally
strong increase in June and cautioned against reading too much into
a one-month downturn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest drop in defense orders in more
than four years contributed to a sharp decline in July orders to
U.S. factories for manufactured goods, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that orders for both
durable and non-durable goods fell 3.5 percent to $220.2 billion
last month. It was the worst drop since January 1987, when orders
fell 3.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought helped lift prices farmers got for
raw products in August by 2.1 percent from July, the Agriculture
Department says.
   The report released Tuesday said August prices averaged 13
percent higher than a year earlier. The report also included
revised figures showing the index rose only 2.9 percent in July,
compared with the preliminary reading of 3.6 percent announced a
month ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction fell 5 percent
in July after spurting higher the previous two months, according to
a new report.
   The July decline was concentrated in the public works sector,
the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co. said
Tuesday. It said construction activity has been drifting downward
since last fall.
   ``Expectations for a lasting turn-around, which were none too
high before the latest round of credit restraint, have just been
lowered,'' George Christie, chief economist of F.W. Dodge, said in
a statement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has stopped Eastern Airlines
from firing 4,000 employees but has allowed the
financially-strapped carrier to go ahead with service cutbacks to
14 cities as planned.
   ``Massive layoffs are not, and shall never be business as
usual,'' U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker said in a 50-page
opinion. ``The Railway Labor Act requires Eastern to bargain with
its unions before taking unilateral action to eliminate 12 percent
of its workforce.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes called the decision ``gravely
wrong'' and said the carrier would file an emergency appeal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flight attendants union says Carl Icahn is
using TWA as his personal cash cow to the detriment of the airline
and public safety.
   The union asked Tuesday that the U.S. Department of
Transportation block Icahn's plan to take Trans World Airlines Inc.
private and to freeze TWA assets while it investigates his fitness
to continue managing the airline.
   Through spokesman Bob Allen, Icahn called IFFA's allegations
``spurious, malicious and erroneous'' and designed ``to embarrass
the airline.''
</TEXT>
