<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     08-31 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Decline; Financial Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock, bond and currency markets showed little reaction
after the government reported a 0.8 percent drop in its main
indicator of the economy's strength, the biggest decline since
after the crash of the stock market.
   Tuesday's report actually comforted some economists and
investors who feared the economy was expanding too rapidly, raising
the danger of higher inflation, higher interest rates and
eventually a recession.
   The government also said Tuesday that factory orders fell 3.5
percent in July, the biggest monthly drop since January 1987. But
economists said the decline had little significance because it was
caused mainly by a swing in the volatile category of defense orders.
   ``For those people who were worried that we were in for a major
acceleration of inflation, these numbers probably calm some
nerves,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of the Wefa Group, a
Bala Cynwyd, Pa., economic forecasting firm.
   Stock prices generally rose Tuesday in a slow session, although
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 3.20 points to
2,038.23 after a 24-point gain on Monday.
   The dollar fell Tuesday against most major currencies, while
bond prices finished slightly higher. The yield of the Treasury's
30-year bond, which falls when the market strengthens, dipped to
9.32 percent from 9.33 percent late Monday.
   Chimerine said the reports should help encourage the Fed to hold
off on any further tightening moves unless new evidence of
inflation surfaces.
   The decline in the leading indicators was the biggest since last
November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the aftermath of
the October stock market crash.
   Economists noted the index posted an exceptionally strong
increase in June and cautioned against reading too much into a
one-month downturn.
   ``Despite the declines, we're not going to have any slowing in
the imminent future,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with
Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York.
   U.S. manufacturing, which languished earlier in the decade
because of the strong dollar, has rebounded. The weaker dollar has
fueled a resurgence in sales of American goods overseas and
businesses have responded by spending more to upgrade and replace
plant and equipment.
   But demand for U.S. goods has been so strong that some analysts
are concerned that factory capacity will be strained, pushing
prices higher.
   Factory orders, excluding the defense category, were down 0.7
percent in July following a healthy 2.9 percent gain in June.
   Samuel D. Kahan, an economist with Kleinwort Benson Government
Securities Inc. in Chicago, said that despite the overall drop in
factory orders in July, ``there is very little evidence yet that
the manufacturing sector is moderating.''
   The economy, as measured by the gross national product, grew at
a 3.3 percent annual rate in the three months ended in June and at
a 3.4 percent pace in the first quarter.
   In an effort to ease inflationary pressures, the Federal Reserve
Board has attempted to dampen economic growth by boosting
short-term interest rates since late March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
