<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-31 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have moved higher in moderate
trading, with gasoline prices advancing in pre-Labor Day weekend
activity.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, rose 5 cents per barrel Tuesday to close at $15.27.
Other contract months also rose.
   Refined petroleum products moved higher, with near-term
contracts for gasoline leading the way. Contracts for September
delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.79 cent to finish at
48.03 cents a gallon. Other contracts also finished higher.
   Wholesale heating oil for September rose 0.38 cent to 43.14
cents a gallon while other contract months also gained.
   Analysts said gasoline prices were strong in anticipation of
demand during the Labor Day weekend and helped boost crude and
other energy prices after a weak opening.
   ``Gasoline was strong but that's not surprising seeing we're
heading into Labor Day, the last hurrah of the summer driving
season,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker and analyst at E.D.&F.
Man International Futures Inc.
   Analysts said expectations that the American Petroleum
Institute's weekly report would show lower gasoline stocks helped
keep prices strong. However, traders were expecting buildups in
crude and heating oil, which helped slow the rally in crude prices,
they said.
   The API report, released after the close of trading, indicated
U.S. crude oil stocks actually dipped by 4.2 million barrels last
week while distillate stocks fell by about 3 million barrels.
Gasoline stocks rose by 699,000 barrels.
</TEXT>
