<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalSentences Bjt   08-31 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Sentences, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Continental Illinois Officials Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former bank officers sentenced to prison for
crimes that contributed to the near-collapse of Continental
Illinois National Bank and Trust Co. say they are relieved that
years of court proceedings are over.
   Sentenced in a hearing were John R. Lytle, a former Continental
vice president, and William G. Patterson, the head of energy
lending at the now-defunct Penn Square Bank of Oklahoma City.
   The two pleaded guilty to charges stemming from an alleged
scheme that left Continental Illinois holding millions of dollars
in bad energy loans from Penn Square. Penn Square failed in 1982,
and Continental Illinois nearly collapsed two years later following
an unprecedented run on its deposits.
   U.S. District Judge Milton Shadur sentenced Lytle to 3{ years in
prison, despite Lytle's pleas for probation. Shadur sentenced
Patterson, who choked back tears as he spoke in his own defense, to
a 2-year term.
   Lytle, 53, and Patterson, 38, pleaded guilty June 30 to one
criminal charge each for a scheme in which Lytle allegedly took
kickbacks in exchange for arranging to have Continental buy
millions of dollars in risky energy loans from Penn Square. The
maximum sentence allowed under their plea bargain was five years.
   ``I'm going to be able to put a red circle on my calendar which
signals the end of this affair,'' Lytle told the judge before
sentencing. He said he had lived under indictment for more than six
years.
   Patterson, who held his head and cried as he spoke, said he was
sorry for his actions and was concerned about his family. He also
had sought a sentence of probation and community service.
   ``I'm sorry for the people in Chicago and Oklahoma,'' he said.
``I think of that a lot.''
   Patterson's attorney, Burck Bailey, said after the sentencing
that ``We're relieved to have it behind us.''
   Bailey said he was convinced the ordeal had harmed Patterson's
long-term health. He said Patterson had to be carried from court
when acquitted of charges in Oklahoma related to Penn Square, only
to find out the next day he had been indicted in Chicago.
   Testifying before his sentencing, Lytle said he accepted
responsibility for his actions. He asked the judge to sentence him
to no more than six months in prison and assign him to work with
the poor on Chicago's West Side.
   But Shadur said Lytle seemed, at times, ``unwilling to confront
the realities'' of what he had done.
   ``You allowed your conduct as a bank officer...to be driven
impermissibly by your desire for personal benefits,'' the judge
told Lytle.
   Lytle pleaded guilty to misapplication of bank funds and
Patterson pleaded guilty to a charge that he aided and abetted
Lytle. The pleas came two months after a trial of the two ended
with a deadlocked ury.
   Prosecutors said Patterson had manipulated Lytle and a third
man, Oklahoma drilling contractor Jere Sturgis, in schemes to save
his own failing bank. Sturgis was acquitted of wire fraud charges.
   Defense attorneys contended Continental Illinois, which was kept
afloat by a $4.5 billion government bailout, was saddled with the
troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive lending policy.
   Bailey said his client was in over his head when assigned to
handle Penn Square's oil and gas leasing loans. He said it was a
time of seemingly endless expansion, causing bankers to ``throw
caution to the wind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Resorts-Griffin     08-31 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts-Griffin,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin Gets Resorts Stockholder Approval, But Not Nod From
Regulators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin has received
approval from a majority of Resorts International Inc. stockholders
to buy the gaming and real estate company, but state gaming
regulators have thrown up a roadblock.
   Griffin's proposed trust agreement _ needed before he can buy
the Resorts stock from Class A shareholders and controlling
stockholder Donald Trump _ failed to win approval Tuesday from the
state Casino Control Commission.
   The trust agreement is necessary in case the commission finds
Griffin ineligible for a New Jersey gaming license. In that case,
the trust would run the company until Griffin could appeal the
decision or sell off the company's assets.
   The commission voted 3-2 against the proposed trust agreement,
largely because it calls for a trustee to take control of The
Griffin Co. rather than just the Resorts stock. Griffin officials
wanted the trust agreement to cover The Griffin Co. to ensure the
firm can take advantage of prior tax losses of Resorts, potentially
worth $100 million.
   Griffin's deal to buy Resorts was to expire at midnight Tuesday,
but Robert Trump, vice president of the Trump Organization, said
after the commission meeting that he expected Griffin to extend the
offer for another 30 days.
   Griffin was present at Tuesday's hearing, but did not testify.
The former talk show host said afterward he had asked the Internal
Revenue Service for clarification on the tax issue, and he still
expects the deal to go through.
   Commissioners Carl Zeitz and W. David Waters argued that The
Griffin Co. did not do enough to satisfy the law concerning the
structure of the trust.
   Griffin also must obtain approvals from the Atlantic City
Housing Authority and the Bahamian government where a Resorts
facility is located, said Resorts President I.G. ``Jack'' Davis.
   The deal also is contingent upon settlement of shareholder
litigation now pending in the Delaware Chancery Court and another
lawsuit by Showboat Hotel Casino.
   Trump, who owns Resorts Class B stock _ which has 100 times the
voting power of the Class A stock _ will receive $135 a share, or
about $96 million. Trump will also receive another $63 million to
break his management agreement with Resorts, and he will then buy
the company's unfinished Taj Mahal casino project for $255 million.
   Holders of the 5.7 million Class A shares will receive $36 a
share under Griffin's offer, or a total of $205.2 million. On
Tuesday, holders of 2.9 million Class A shares _ just slightly over
the number needed to approve the proposal _ agreed to accept
Griffin's offer. More than 236,000 voted against the deal, and more
than 58,000 abstained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BendectinAppeals     08-31 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bendectin Appeals,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against Bendectin Class-Action Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BENTLEY BOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court panel has ruled in
favor of the maker of the drug Bendectin in a class-action suit by
some 1,150 plaintiffs who claimed the anti-nausea drug caused birth
defects.
   The attorney for Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc., maker of
Bendectin, said the decision by the U.S. 6th Circuit Court of
Appeals upholding a 1985 U.S. District Court decision was the most
important yet in Bendectin-related litigation, which has been
active for years.
   ``It shows the plaintiffs' lawyers lost fair and square,'' said
Frank Woodside III, Merrell Dow's attorney.
   A federal court jury in Cincinnati decided in March 1985 after
five weeks of testimony that the drug did not cause birth defects
when taken in prescribed doses by pregnant women.
   The three-judge appeals panel upheld the verdict, as well as
Judge Carl Rubin's decision to keep the jury from seeing all
plaintiffs who had birth defects.
   Woodside said Merrell Dow has not asked that plaintiffs be
removed in any of the individual Bendectin suits against Merrell
Dow in other courts, but was concerned that ``having hundreds of
children testify'' may have distracted the jury and attorneys in
the class-action case.
   Stanley Chesley, one of the attorneys representing more than 800
individual suits in the class action, did not return phone calls
Tuesday.
   Appeals Judge Nathaniel Jones dissented in part Tuesday by
saying the judge should have first met with the excluded plaintiffs
before denying them their day in court.
   The appeals court also affirmed Rubin's decision to split the
trial into two parts. If the jury had found that the drug caused
defects, there would have been subsequent trials to determine any
negligence or damages.
   The court also upheld Rubin's ruling that the district court did
not have jurisdiction in 80 of the 1,150 cases. Those 80 cases were
dismissed or sent back to state court.
   An estimated 32 million pregnant women worldwide took Bendectin
or its overseas version, Debendox, from 1956 to 1983. Merrell Dow
voluntarily removed it from the market in 1983, although it
maintains the drug is safe and does not cause birth defects in
children.
   Merrell Dow said in a news release that it had won 22 jury
verdicts or judgments in Bendectin birth defect suits, and was
appealing four trial verdicts won by plaintiffs.
   Woodside said dozens of lawyers across the country were awaiting
the appeals court ruling before deciding if they should file
similar claims against the company, which is based in suburban
Reading.
   ``It's going to have precedential effect all over the place,''
Woodside said. ``This opinion is a very thorough review of all the
issues presented to the court of appeals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
