<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Eastern     08-31 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Eastern Layoffs, Allows Route Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6 of Aug. 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has 140 fewer flights today, but
because of a federal judge's ruling still employs 4,000 workers it
wanted to lay off.
   Eastern is going ahead with previously announced plans to
curtail service from 14 cities in the aftermath of an order Tuesday
by U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker. The order allowed route
cuts but barred the company from making mass layoffs without
negotiating with its unions.
   ``Massive layoffs are not, and shall never be, business as
usual,'' Parker wrote in a 50-page opinion. ``The Railway Labor Act
requires Eastern to bargain with its unions before taking
unilateral action to eliminate 12 percent of its workforce.''
   Parker signed a preliminary injunction barring Eastern from
``altering in any way the status quo working condition of Eastern's
pilots, machinists and flight attendants.'' A trial will be
scheduled later.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes called the decision ``gravely
wrong'' and said the carrier would file an emergency appeal.
   ``Eastern, like any American business, must be allowed to prune
money-losing operations,'' Bakes said in a statement released at
Eastern's headquarters here. ``We must be able to take prudent,
although sometimes painful, measures in the best interests of the
company and our employees.''
   Overall, Eastern is discontinuing 204 flights, mostly in the
West and the Caribbean, with some new flights resulting in a net
reduction of 140 Eastern flights.
   Parker's opinion did not spell out what should happen to the
employees whose jobs were salvaged, even though their duties were
not. Union attorneys suggested they could be transferred, and
leaders of Eastern's three unions said they wanted to meet with
management to discuss ways to cut costs without layoffs.
   Charles E. Bryan, president of Machinists District 100,
Eastern's largest union with 12,000 workers of 32,500 Eastern
employees, called the decision an opportunity for Texas Air Corp.
Chairman Frank Lorenzo to belie his reputation as ``the No. 1
union-buster.''
   ``We're not here as laborers trying to direct the business of
the airline. We're trying to protect jobs,'' said Dan Vician,
vice-chairman of the pilots' local.
   Mary Jane Barry, local president, said the flight attendants
still were willing to offer a job-sharing and leave plan _ rejected
earlier by management _to save jobs and money.
   Lawyers for the three unions submitted financial statements, and
Parker ordered bonds of $25,000 each to indemnify the airline if
the decision is reversed.
   Meanwhile, the airline said: ``Eastern's basic fall schedule
remains intact. Travel agents and passengers can continue to book
flights with full confidence that the schedule will be as
announced.''
   Parker said the service cuts, which reduce Eastern's daily
flights from 1,225 to 1,085, were financially motivated. Eastern
says the route cuts will save $50 million monthly in operating
costs, and the layoffs would have saved another $7 million monthly.
   Eastern posted a second-quarter net loss of $89.8 million,
following a $64.5 million first-quarter loss and $182 million in
1987 losses. Houston-based Texas Air has warned it needs cash to
keep Eastern, some $2 billion in debt when bought 2{ years ago, in
operation.
   Spokesman Robin Matell said the airline has no plans to file for
federal bankruptcy protection, as it had hinted before the ruling.
   ``The only court we're headed for is the court of appeals,'' he
said.
   Union leaders say the federal courts, which have generally been
ruling in their favor this year, probably would make it difficult
for Lorenzo to repeat his 1983 move at Continental, where he used
federal Chapter 11 bankruptcy to void union contracts.
   The union leaders also noted Parker's findings that Texas Air
had worsened Eastern's financial state by taking loans and payments
totaling hundreds of millions of dollars from the Miami carrier to
Texas Air and Continental.
   Parker also said Texas Air and Lorenzo have exhibited an
anti-union bias.
   ``It confirmed what we've been saying,'' Bryan said. ``This is a
federal judge. It's not the unions anymore or our consultants
talking.''
   The cities Eastern is cutting are Albuquerque, N.M.; Fort de
France, Martinique; Las Vegas, Nev.; Minneapolis-St. Paul; Oklahoma
City; Omaha, Neb.; Dallas; Pointe-a-Pitre, Guadeloupe; Reno, Nev.;
San Antonio, Texas; San Diego; St. Lucia, West Indies; Tucson,
Ariz.; and Tulsa, Okla.
   The company and its unions still have myriad court battles under
way, including a union effort to reverse the Texas Air sale and
allow employees to buy Eastern.
   Continuing are contract talks with the Machinists and pilots.
The Machinists, in federal mediation since January, will vote Sept.
15 on a company call for $161 million in annual wage concessions.
</TEXT>
