<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0301</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today with a
boost from a strong dollar and a modest decline in interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.00 to 2,046.23 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 4 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 556 up, 319 down and
488 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.65 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The dollar climbed in foreign exchange on reports suggesting
that Japanese officials planned no immediate move to increase
interest rates.
   That, in turn, prompted slightly higher prices, and hence lower
interest rates, for U.S. government securities in the credit
markets.
   Analysts also said hopes were increasing on Wall Street that
Friday's report on the employment situation for August would show a
moderation in job growth, which would presumably ease pressure for
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve.
   With all those positives, however, the pace of trading remained
relatively light as the long Labor Day weekend approached.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone & Telegraph
rose \ to 25\; Exxon gained \ to 46~, and General Electric added [
to 40|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.51 to 149.17. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .40 at 295.31.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 0.20 to
2,038.23.
   Advances outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 in composite
trading of NYSE-listed issues, with 741 up, 644 down and 564
unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 108.72 million shares, against 99.28
million the previous session.
