<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BankBoard-S&Ls 1stLd-Writethru f0020 08-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Board-S&Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators May Make Several Big S&L Rescues Within 10 Days</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout to include Tulsa World report; Also moved on
general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators say they are planning to spend
billions of federal dollars over the next 10 days in several
transactions to rescue ailing savings and loan institutions.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
said late Tuesday the board was working on several deals. He
declined to say where the next transaction would take place and
said none of the anticipated federal rescues have received final
approval.
   However, the Tulsa World said in today's editions that the bank
board's next move likely would come in Oklahoma with the
consolidation of 14 of the state's most troubled savings
institutions into six holding companies.
   Hoyle said the board was meeting today but would not reveal what
it was considering.
   In a report attributed to unidentified officials in the office
of Rep. Jim Inhofe, R-Okla., the newspaper said regulators plan to
sell the holding companies to the highest bidder, thus placing 14
of the state's 48 S&Ls under new ownership.
   Meanwhile, The Washington Post in today's editions said the bank
board was preparing this week to spend $1.2 billion to sell or
merge ``a dozen or so'' institutions somewhere in the Southwest.
   Hoyle said that if all goes according to plan over the next week
and a half, the bank board will spend substantially more than that
in several large transactions in a number of states.
   In recent weeks, the board has announced it was spending more
than $8 billion to assist ailing S&Ls, including a major deal in
Texas, which like Oklahoma has been hard hit by the depression in
the oil drilling industry.
   On another front, the bank board was facing a self-imposed
deadline to wrap up negotiations with the Robert M. Bass Group of
Fort Worth, Texas, which is seeking federal assistance to acquire
American Savings and Loan Association of Stockton, Calif., one of
the nation's largest S&Ls.
   The board began negotiating with the Bass Group exclusively on
April 21 and twice has extended the deadline, with the most recent
extension expiring Thursday.
   Hoyle said the board would have an announcement regarding
American by Thursday. Industry sources have said between $1.3
billion and $2 billion in federal money will be required for the
rescue.
</TEXT>
