<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Iraq-OPEC     08-31 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iraq-OPEC,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subroto in Baghdad After Visit to Tehran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto as one name is correct</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secretary-General of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries arrived here after a similar visit
to Iran to discuss ways of curbing over-production by some of the
cartel's member states.
   Subroto, Indonesia's former energy minister, made no statement
on his arrival Wednesday. He was met at Baghdad Airport by Oil
Minister Issam Abdul-Rahim al-Chalabi.
   On Tuesday, Subroto met separately with Iranian President Ali
Khamenei and Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh seeking to persuade
them to allow Iraq a production quota of 2.39 million barrels a
day, the same as Iran.
   But there was no word on whether the Iranians agreed to an
increase in Iraq's present quota of 1.5 million barrels a day.
   Iraq has refused to abide by its quota, insisting on parity with
its gulf foe, Iran. The two countries recently began talks on
possibly ending the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Iraq is pumping an estimated 2.5 million barrels a day,
worsening the over-production problem by some of OPEC's 13 member
states.
   The Middle East Economic Survey, a respected oil publication
based in Cyprus, reported this week that OPEC's production in
August stood at 20 million barrels a day, or 3.5 million barrels a
day over the overall production ceiling. This was seen as a key
factor in declining oil prices.
   Since he assumed his post June 1, the secretary-general has been
trying to find a practical formula that would curb the surplus and
stabilize oil prices.
   He has visited Venezuela, Equador, Saudi Arabia, Mexico and
Kuwait and succeeded in persuading Venezuela to drop its veto
against giving Iraq a quota equal to that of Iran.
   Some OPEC members have opposed raising a member's quota because
it increases production and further weakens prices.
   Iran has been the only member opposing an increase of Iraq's
quota.
</TEXT>
