<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-Reform     08-31 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Reform,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Urges More Cautious Approach To Price Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Chinese government officials have decided
against rapid decontrol of state-set prices, a key element in the
nation's economic reforms, in an apparent move to ease unhappiness
with spiraling inflation.
   The cautious approach toward price reform disclosed Tuesday by
the State Council, China's Cabinet, differed from a more aggressive
outline adopted by the Communist Party Politburo in mid-August, and
highlighted the growing debate within the leadership over how fast
China should proceed with its reforms.
   The State Council's stand was widely reported in the official
media Wednesday, with the national evening news devoting five
minutes to explaining the decisions made.
   The council agreed not to initiate further price increases for
the remainder of this year and decided there will be no radical
reforms in the price system next year.
   The nation will continue to restrain construction projects and
other capital investments that have pushed industrial growth to
unsustainable levels and will further control credit and the
issuance of currency to cool off the overheated economy, the State
Council said.
   It also said a five-year plan of price and wage reform outlined
by the Politburo in mid-August is still tentative and subject to
revision.
   The Politburo plan called for removal of price controls on most
commodities in favor of market regulation.
   The plan, while also stressing the need to control a
near-runaway inflation rate, said China's economy ``is full of
vitality and is developing vigorously. The time is favorable to the
price and wage reforms.''
   The 17-member Politburo, the main decision-making body of the
party, is led by General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, the leading
advocate of rapid market-oriented reform.
   The State Council, meanwhile, is headed by Premier Li Peng, who
is thought to be more cautious toward change and more concerned
about the effects of reform on economic and social stability.
   There is consensus in China about the pressing need for price
reform, primarily the removal of state controls so that the value
of goods can be determined by market forces.
   Artificially low state-set prices for many products have led to
chronic shortages, corruption, influence peddling and a thriving
black market. Profiteers commonly buy up low-priced raw materials
and items from state factories and resell them for far higher
prices to producers and consumers.
   Decontrol of prices of some basic goods and foods in the past
year, coupled with the inability of producers to meet rising
consumer demand, have pushed inflation to levels never before
acknowledged in China's communist system. In June prices were 19
percent higher than a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
