<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-31 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Loan Expirations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to the Agriculture
Department's refusal to extend price-support loans scheduled to
mature today, analysts said.
   Unless the loans are extended, as was recommended Tuesday by a
federal magistrate in St. Paul, Minn., an estimated 400 million to
500 million bushels of corn will be released onto the market.
   The magistrate's recommendation is not binding but it will be
considered by the judge hearing a case brought by several farmers
who are seeking to have the loans extended.
   ``The USDA feels as though they've got a mandate to make their
own decisions with regard to extending loans, which they say they
will not do, and people are worried about an influx of old-crop
corn coming to the market,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   He said the bearish impact of the potential loan expirations was
offset by an increase in grain export business, which was keeping
prices from falling significantly.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.94{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to 1{ cents higher with September at $2.77 a bushel;
oats were 1{ cents to 3 cents lower with September at $2.51{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 4{ cents lower with September at
$8.42{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .55 cent lower to .10 cent higher with October
at 71.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .35 cent
lower with September at 81.47 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.37 cent lower with October at 39.05 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .48 cent lower to .78 cent higher with February at
50.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
