<HEAD>Hormel Issues Advance Notice of Layoffs in Nebraska Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Geo. A. Hormel & Co. on Wednesday informed
nearly half of the workers at its plant in Fremont, Neb., that they
would be laid off in a year.
   The notices, given 52 weeks in advance of anticipated layoffs,
are required by the collective bargaining agreement between the
Austin-based meatpacker and Local 22 of the United Food and
Commercial Workers union.
   Notices were issued to 324 employees in the slaughtering,
cutting and rendering operation at the Fremont plant, which
currently has about 770 workers.
   William R. Hunter, executive vice president of operations for
Hormel, said unsatisfactory gross margins and the impact of
large-volume, low-cost producers in the slaughtering end of the
business have been a deterrent to satisfactory operation of the
plant for some time.
