<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GM-DisplaySystem     08-31 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM-Display System,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Unveils New Display System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has unveiled a new display
system for cars that will enable motorists to check their speed,
fuel and lights without taking their eyes off the road.
   The design, displayed Tuesday in Chicago, is based on a system
used in fighter aircraft. It has been adapted for cars using
computerized aerospace design and analysis techniques, GM said.
   The new system, called ``Head-Up Display,'' projects key
information onto the windshield from a box mounted atop the dash.
   ``It takes awhile for people to become accustomed to HUD, but
they don't want to give it up after using it a week,'' said Ray
Lippmann, project consultant for the Delco Electronics subsidiary
of GM-owned Hughes Electronics.
   GM sold 54 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme Indy 500 ``replica'' pace
cars equipped with the system to the public this spring, and those
cars have had no problems with the system, said Robert Leggat, a GM
spokesman.
   Leggat said the system will be installed in 500 of the 1989
Cutlass Supreme International Coupes for a price in the $100 to
$300 range, and it will be standard on 2,000 specially built 1989
Pontiac Grand Prix SE Turbo models.
   ``We estimate 10,000 HUD units will be offered in 1990,''
Lippmann said.
</TEXT>
