<1ST_LINE>u f PM-UtilityInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru   08-31 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utility Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Power Tax Probe May Involve Other Individuals, Companies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after the 3rd graf with state Public Service
Commission probe.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal probe into accounting procedures at
Georgia Power Co., involving a possible attempt to avoid paying $50
million in taxes, may involve other companies and individuals, the
government says.
   Court documents made public Tuesday showed the investigation now
focuses on Georgia Power, its parent, The Southern Co., and the Big
Eight accounting firm of Arthur Andersen & Co.
   But U.S. Attorney Robert Barr, who confirmed the investigation,
said the probe is continuing and may involve others.
   Meanwhile, the state Public Service Commission said today it has
upgraded its own investigation of tax and accounting practices at
Georgia Power and specifically wants to know whether the utility
attempted to hide vital financial information from PSC scrutiny.
   Barr refused to elaborate beyond what was in the court papers
because a grand jury is still hearing details. He said the
investigation involves possible criminal wrongdoing, including
violations of the U.S. Tax Code.
   A statement issued by Arthur Andersen from the company's Chicago
headquarters denied any wrongdoing. But Georgia Power Chairman
Robert W. Scherer, speaking for the electric utility and Southern
Co., said he was shocked by the allegations and vowed to ``get to
the bottom of this matter.'' The papers raised the question of
whether the companies and their accountants sought to hide about
$61 million in spare parts to avoid paying $50 million in federal
taxes, interest and penalties.
   Key elements in that question are whether parts are classified
as emergency spares or for maintainence and when they become
expenses to the company.
   The papers also raised the question of Georgia Power's
accounting for the sale of 5 percent of the Vogtle nuclear power
plant to the Municipal Electric Authority of Georgia.
   In the documents, officials say the deal was treated as a sale
of 5 percent of the $8.87 billion plant for book value purposes,
but as 1.35 percent for tax purposes, saving the company between
$10 million and $12 million.
   The papers include excerpts of taped conversations in which
Southern Co.'s tax chief agrees with an informant that the company
misled the IRS over the tax accounting of the spare parts, but
adds, ``Don't ever say that.''
   The investigation, dating to 1982, is based largely on
information contained in taped conversations between utility and
Andersen officials and the informant, Georgia Power employee Gary
Gilman, who is getting paid for his participation and been exempted
from prosecution, the court papers show.
   The papers also include affidavits requesting search warrants at
the downtown Atlanta headquarters of Georgia Power as well as the
home of Tim Fallaw, Southern Co.'s director of taxes.
   The affidavit by IRS Criminal Investigation Division agent
Arthur D. McGovern Jr. alleges Fallaw and at least five Georgia
Power employees and four Andersen employees knowingly participated
in a scheme to hide the incorrect accounting of spare parts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0267 </DOCNO>
