<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GalloSuit     08-31 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gallo Suit,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winery Owners Win Legal Battle With Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed an attempt
by the younger brother of Ernest and Julio Gallo to gain one-third
ownership of the world's largest winery.
   However, U.S. District Judge Edward Dean Price ruled Tuesday
that E&J Gallo Winery's trademark infringement suit against Joseph
Gallo will proceed to trial on Nov. 15.
   Ernest and Julio Gallo had charged that use of Joseph Gallo's
last name on a brand of cheese he produced violated their
trademark. Joseph Gallo countersued, contending that his older
brothers comingled assets from their parents' estate to begin the
Modesto, Calif.-based Gallo Winery in 1933.
   Price said he found no legal basis for Joseph Gallo's contention.
   The judge said Joseph Gallo's allegation that Ernest and Julio
Gallo concealed part of the parents' estate ``clearly fails.''
Price said evidence presented to the court of the Gallo family
making wine before prohibition is ``mostly the stuff that family
anecdotes are made of.''
   ``The court can only conclude that Ernest's administration was
appropriate and that all of the assets of the estate were reported
and administered,'' the judge said.
   ``It was always our belief that once the true facts were known,
this ludicrous and false claim would be thrown out of court,''
Gallo Winery spokesman Dan Solomon said.
   Attorney Dennis Rice said he will continue trying to let Joseph
Gallo use his own name on his own products.
   ``I continue to believe Joseph is entitled to use his own name
in his own business,'' Rice said. ``We intend to move forward with
that phase of the case at the appropriate time.''
   Price said several issues must be resolved in the trademark
trial.
   They include a contention by Joseph Gallo that the winery made
false statements in applying for a trademark to the name Gallo,
which means rooster in Italian. Ernest and Julio Gallo contended
that their father began using the trademark in 1909.
   ``The court cannot say that a fraud was practiced upon the
trademark officials by the winery during the registration
process,'' Price said. ``It is simply the position of the court
that the record does not establish that the statements made to
secure the trademark, as a matter of law, bar the winery from the
relief it seeks.
   ``That issue remains for trial,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
