<DOCNO> AP880831-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ColaSentencing     08-31 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cola Sentencing,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Bottling Company to `Corporate Imprisonment'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said his sentence of
``corporate imprisonment'' for a soft-drink bottling company
convicted of price fixing was unprecedented, but was justified for
a company that ``did not have a conscience.''
   U.S. District Judge Robert G. Doumar suspended the sentence and
placed Allegheny Bottling Co. of Maryland on probation Tuesday,
saying any violation of probation would result in the U.S. Marshal
being sent to ``padlock every facility Allegheny owns.''
   Doumar also imposed the maximum fine of $1 million, suspending
$50,000 and ordering four top corporate officers to perform as much
as two years of full-time, unpaid community service.
   ``The corporation cannot come in here, profit to the tune of $10
million and walk away with a $1 million fine,'' Doumar said. ``I
cannot imagine any company being more tied up with illegal
activity.''
   James H. Walsh, a lawyer for Allegheny, said he would appeal the
sentence, adding that he could find no precedent of corporate
imprisonment.
   Doumar also ordered that Allegheny Bottling not sell any of its
assets without the court's permission.
   Walsh said Allegheny's parent company, Pepsico, had planned to
sell some of Allegheny's assets this week and that the sentence
could result in a ``financial fiasco.''
   Doumar said he would consider the transactions in private but
would not allow the company to be left with no one to fullfill the
terms of probation.
   The government said Allegheny, a Pepsi bottling franchise, and
its arch rival, Mid-Atlantic Coca-Cola Bottlng Co., ended years of
cola wars in 1982 by secretly rigging wholesale prices in Virginia
and Maryland.
   Prosecutors said a number of executives, including Maryland
multimillionaire Morton M. Lapides, who founded Allegheny,
orchestrated the conspiracy. Lapides later sold the company, which
is now owned by Pepsico.
   Doumar said virtually every executive at Allegheny was in on the
scheme. ``Where was there a beacon of some sanity?'' Doumar asked.
``Was there any? Did anyone care? Why didn't anyone care?''
   ``Some 200 years ago, the Lord Chancellor of England said, `You
cannot expect a corporation to have a conscience when it has no
soul to be damned and no body to be kicked ... Obviously, Allegheny
Bottling Co. did not have a conscience...''
   Doumar said he could find no similar case of corporate
imprisonment to justify his sentence, but added, ``stone walls do
not a prison make.''
   He said the sentence would discourage other potential price
fixers from making illegal agreements with competitors.
   Lapides and James Harford, former president of Mid-Atlantic
Coca-Cola, were found guilty by a federal jury in May of price
fixing.
   Last week, Lapides and Harford received three-year prison terms,
with all but six months suspended, and were fined $100,000 each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0269 </DOCNO>
