<HEAD>Maxwell Communications Reports Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communications Corp. PLC, the publishing
group headed by British media tycoon Robert Maxwell, on Wednesday
reported a slight increase in its first-half profits.
   The company said it earned 71.9 million pounds, or about $121
million before taxes in the period ended June 30, up 2 percent from
70.5 million pounds, or $118.6 million, in the first half of 1987.
   Revenue jumped 37 percent to 505.7 million pounds, or $851
million, from 370.2 million pounds, or $623 million.
   A Maxwell spokesman said most of the gains came from the
company's core publishing businesses. Professional and electronic
publishing both enjoyed an outstanding half-year, he said.
   The core businesses are now being positioned within Europe ahead
of the freeing of trade barriers within the 12-nation European
Economic Community in 1992, the spokesman said.
   The company's publishing services in Britain and the United
States are to be offered in Spain, Belgium, West Germany, Italy and
France, he said.
   Separately, Maxwell said it began talks with Macmillan Inc., the
New York-based publishing and information concern, about the
possibility of acquiring all or part of its information division.
Macmillan had rejected as inadequate Maxwell's outstanding
$80-a-share tender offer that values the company at $2.34 billion.
