<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PaulsenWinery     08-31 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Paulsen Winery,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comedian Finally Sells His Sonoma County Winery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLOVERDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deadpan comic, self-nominating
presidential candidate and vintner Pat Paulsen, who has been trying
to sell his Sonoma County winery for more than a year, has finally
made a deal on the property, the company reported Wednesday.
   Paulsen's general manager, George W. Litras, said the comedian's
name will remain on the label and he will continue as the wine's
prime promoter and consultant. He has agreed to make 40 public
appearances a year for the wine.
   ``We hope to take full advantage of Pat's marketing ability,''
said Litras, adding that the new owners hoped to raise production
to 35,000 cases in less than two years.
   No sale price was named, but Paulsen's 20,000-case winery and
other property, including the 55-acre town of Asti, first listed
for $3.7 million. The deal includes Paulsen's 3.3-acre tasting
room, delicatessen, gas station and some houses.
   The buyers are reported to be Mark Majestic of Palos Verdes, and
Neal Broidy of Transaction Securities of Oakland.
   Pat Paulsen Vineyards, whose label prominently carries Paulsen's
underscored name and sad-looking portrait, gets its grapes from 37
acres of cabernet sauvignon, sauvignon blanc and chardonnay planted
on a 500-acre Alexander Valley ranch.
   Aside from his wry, dry humor, Paulsen is well known for his TV
appearances with the Smothers Brothers, who also make wine under
their own label, and the fact that Paulsen has been ``running'' for
U.S. president for some 20 years.
   ``It's tough campaigning,'' Paulsen once said, ``kissing hands
and shaking babies.''
   Wine sales plunged when Paulsen first put the winery on the
market, as distributors feared the wine would not sell without his
name. In May, in a move to assure distributors that the label was
safe, Paulsen announced he would continue running the winery but
was looking for an investor as partner.
   ``He (Paulsen) has a national recognition and quite a large
following, and that helps sales,'' Litras said at the time, adding
that the wine itself was good enough to ``stand on its own merits.''
   In 1985 and 1986, two Paulsen generic wines, $4.25 offerings
labeled ``Refrigerator White,'' got very high marks for quality
from the wine writers, following a 1.5-liter 1984 gamay that was
lauded as superior and a buy at $6.50. All of Paulsen's wines,
including gewurztraminer and muscat canelli, are in the premium
price range, currently priced from, $6 to $11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
