<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Higher On Export Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher Wednesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade on indications that a long awaited
increase in foreign demand for U.S. grains was beginning to surface.
   ``There's been a light pickup in overall business and people
realize there's some pent-up demand in the marketplace,'' said Ted
Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Prices had opened lower and made little movement until midday,
following strong indications that East Germany had purchased
300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn.
   India was believed to have purchased 250,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices while Mexico reportedly bought 50,000
metric tons of U.S. soybeans.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was 4
cents to 7 cents higher with September at $2.83{ a bushel; soybeans
were 7 cents to 14 cents higher with September at $8.54 a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with September at $2.56{ a
bushel.
