<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BellSouth-Gateway     08-31 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BellSouth-Gateway,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BellSouth Becomes First Bell Company to Offer Information Gateway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TranstexT in 2nd graf is CQ</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BellSouth Corp. on Wednesday unveiled an
electronic gateway that will allow computer users to reach several
information services with a single local phone call.
   BellSouth, the first Bell company to offer such a service, said
its TranstexT Universal Gateway is available in the Atlanta calling
area. After the initial introduction there, BellSouth plans to make
the gateway available in other cities in its nine-state region.
   ``We believe information services are an important'' segment of
the telecommunications industry ``and it's important for our
business to be involved,'' said John R. Gunter, BellSouth vice
president for information services.
   But Gunter, alluding to several failed attempts by companies to
launch videotex services, said BellSouth will proceed slowly and
``we're going to be listening a lot'' to see how information
service providers and users respond to the gateway.
   U.S. District Judge Harold Greene, in modifying the consent
decree that stripped American Telephone & Telegraph Co. of its
local Bell operating companies, ruled last year that Bell companies
could establish gateways to transmit electronic information
supplied by others. He continued to bar them, however, from
originating any of the information themselves.
   Without a gateway, computer users with a modem must
pre-subscribe to the various information services that are
available and dial into each one separately. They also are billed
by each separately.
   Using the BellSouth gateway, a computer user needs only to
subscribe to it and can then dial one phone number to reach
multiple information services. Subscribers will be billed by
BellSouth Advanced Networks, an unregulated subsidiary, for use of
the gateway and for the information services they used.
   Currently, eight services are available through the gateway and
10 more are scheduled to be added soon, the company said.
   The services that are already on line offer information about an
Atlanta theater company, local and national news, the stock market
and travel, among other things. One service sponsored by an Atlanta
hospital provides health and fitness information and plans soon to
offer an on-line heart test. Another service allows callers to
``chat'' electronically with one another.
   Gunter said the company hoped to sign up 300 customers during
the initial offering and slowly grow to 1,000 in Atlanta before
offering the service in other areas.
   Gateway charges are $1.50 per hour from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. and $3
per hour during the other 12 hours of the day. Users would be
charged an additional fee depending on how much information they
access _ typically about 60 cents during the day and 40 cents at
night, Gunter said.
   Customers also must pay for the cost of access to any of the
information services on the gateway. A couple of the services
charge nothing, but the cost of others range up to $50 an hour.
   Computer users may pay more for some services obtained through
the gateway than if they dialed into the service directly. But,
depending on the time of day, some services may be cheaper through
the gateway.
   For example, Travel Plus, which is part of General Videotex
Corp.'s Delphi service, charges $7.80 an hour on the gateway, day
or night. But when a caller dials into Delphi and calls up Travel
Plus, it costs $7.40 per hour during the evening but $17.40 during
the day. The daytime rate reflects the higher cost of data lines
needed for computer transmissions, said Jon Gilbert, marketing
director of General Videotex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880831-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LeaseSale     08-31 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lease Sale,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Bids Total $131 Million In Federal Lease Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil companies submitted 371 bids totaling
more than $190 million Wednesday in an effort to grab up
bargain-priced leases on 270 tracts of offshore properties in the
western Gulf of Mexico.
   The high bids ran to more than $131 million.
   Sohio Petroleum Co. had the highest bid of the day with a $7.5
million offer for a tract in the High Island area off the
Texas-Louisiana coast. The bid came to $1,306.24 per acre.
   Officials of the Interior Department's Minerals Management
Service opened the bids as several hundred oil industry executives
looked on.
   It was the second offering of government-owned tracts in the
western gulf and the third gulf lease sale since the Interior
Department dropped the minimum per-acre price on the property from
$150 to $25.
   Interest was high, with 93 companies qualifying to bid.
Eighty-four qualified last March for a similar offering in the
central Gulf.
   However, when the number of submitted bids was totaled Tuesday
afternoon, it was far below the 931 bids received last March for
central Gulf properties.
   Eileen Angelico, spokeswoman for the Minerals Management
Service, said the number was down for two reasons.
   The central Gulf waters are considered better risks and the
western Gulf tracts were up for bids a year ago shortly after the
minimum bids were lowered to $25 per acre.
   Almost 520 bids were received on the first western Gulf
offerings.
   Almost 28 million acres of offshore property, mostly off the
Texas coast, were offered when the government announced the sale in
July. That property was divided into 5,080 tracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
