<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hachette-Salvat     08-31 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hachette-Salvat,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Group Hachette Acquires Majority Of Salvat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French publishing concern Hachette
SA has agreed to acquire a majority interest in the Spanish
publishing firm Salvat, the two companies announced Wednesday.
   Terms were not disclosed, although the Spanish domestic news
agency Europa Press said Hachette paid about $56.5 million for its
stake.
   The deal capped more than a year of negotations between Juan
Salvat, chairman of Salvat, and Jean Claude-Lattest, general
director of Hachette's books division. It is subject to approval by
Spanish regulators.
   The investment was viewed as a way for Hachette to increase its
presence in the Spanish-speaking world, including Spain and Latin
America.
   Hachette, one of the world's largest publishing and media
companies, has 26,000 employees in 36 countries.
   The Paris-based concern said its investment in Salvat and its
recent acquisition of Grolier Inc., a U.S.-based book publisher,
will make it one of the world's largest book publishers with annual
sales of about $1.1 billion.
   Salvat was founded more than 100 years ago in Barcelona and
employs about 1,500 people, including 500 in Spain and the rest in
15 other countries, mostly in Latin America. Its 1988 sales were
estimated at about $126 million.
   Salvat publishes dictionaries and encyclopedias, operates the
largest book distribution network in the Spanish-speaking world and
is involved in specialized medical publishing.
   In addition to books, Hachette publishes magazines and regional
newspapers, and has interests in broadcasting, television and film
production and outdoor display advertising.
</TEXT>
