<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-31 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Move Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar staged a strong advance Wednesday,
bolstered by a sharp decline in the Japanese yen.
   Gold prices also moved higher. Republic National Bank of New
York said gold was bid at $430.30 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up
from $428.35 late Tuesday.
   The dollar's gains came at the expense of the yen, which
weakened anew in overseas trading after Bank of Japan officials
hinted they would not raise their discount rate despite recent
interest rate hikes in the United States and Europe.
   ``The yen went through the floor,'' said one dealer in London.
The dollar's gains against the yen encouraged it to climb against
other currencies, dealers said.
   In New York the dollar jumped 1.59 yen to close at 136.52 yen.
Earlier in London, the dollar rose to finish at 136.50 yen. In
Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins, the
dollar rose 0.58 yen to close at 134.97 yen.
   The yen began weakening late Tuesday on rumors that the Japanese
government plans to impose a tax on certain stock-trading profits.
   ``Stories are going around left and right about what the
Japanese may or may not do,'' said Robert Ryan, a senior trader at
Irving Trust Co.
   In domestic dealings, traders noted that the dollar closed off
its session highs. ``There was some profit-taking and some
month-end squaring'' of positions, noted Jesse Torres, chief dealer
at Bank of Boston's New York office.
   ``The dollar reached the stage where (West Germany's) Bundesbank
said it would do anything to defend the mark,'' he said, prompting
traders to sell dollars.
   The central banks did not intervene to halt the dollar's rise.
But dealers in Europe said they fear the Bundesbank will enter the
market if the dollar tops the 1.8800 level against the mark.
   The dollar gained against the British pound. In London it cost
$1.6830 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6910 late Tuesday. In New
York it cost $1.6860 to buy one pound, less expensive than
Tuesday's $1.6875.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.8765 West German marks, up from 1.8664; 1.5848 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5765; 6.3740 French francs, up from 6.3385;
1,394.50 Italian lire, up from 1,386.00, and 1.2392 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2362.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.8780 West German marks, up from 1.8678; 1.5828 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5760; 6.3755 French francs, up from 6.3385;
2.1230 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080; 1,395.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,387.50, and 1.2395 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2386.
   Gold bullion for current delivery rose to $431.30 a troy ounce
on the New York Commodity Exchange, from $428.80 at Tuesday's close.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $429.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $428.10. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $429.50 an ounce, up from $428.50 late Tuesday. Earlier in Hong
Kong, gold fell $2.60 per ounce to close at a bid $429.96.
   Silver bullion for current delivery rose to $6.556 a troy ounce
on the Commodity Exchange from $6.490 on Tuesday. Silver bullion
prices fell slightly in London, where the metal was trading at a
late bid price of $6.52 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $6.55.
</TEXT>
