<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Insurance, Bjt,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadline Arrives For Rainfall Under Disputed Drought Insurance
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Chubb Corp., summer ended at midnight
Wednesday, the cutoff for measuring rainfall under the insurer's
controversial drought coverage plan that has farmers suing,
insurance departments angry and Chubb officials struggling for
damage control.
   A spokeswoman at the Warren, N.J.-based company, who spoke on
condition that she not be identified by name, said several weeks
would be needed to determine the amount of Chubb's liability. The
insurer hopes to pay all claims by early October, she said.
   Reports from 1,100 U.S. Weather Measuring Stations will filter
in to Chubb's computer. Some of the stations are remote, making
collection of the data more difficult, she said.
   Chubb officials have said that recent rainfall after dry weeks
in June and July may have relieved it having to pay roughly half
the $40 million in coverage granted.
   ``It's certainly been raining, and it's substantially reduced
our exposure,'' said the spokeswoman.
   The policies, granted to 1,160 farmers, promise payments if
rainfall is less than half _ or less than 70 percent, depending on
the policy _ of an area's average rainfall from June 1 to Aug. 31.
   A check Wednesday with weather officials in Farm Belt states
showed a range of roughly calculated rainfall levels for the eriod,
though it is difficult to estimate what the effect might be on
Chubb's liability.
   In Iowa, about 15 percent of the state had less than half normal
rainfall; 55 percent to 60 percent received less than the 70
percent threshhold. Minnesota reported that less than 10 percent of
the state fell below the halfway mark and just under half had less
than 70 percent of the average.
   Rainfall in more than two-thirds of Indiana dipped below 70
percent of the average, and one-fifth was below 50 percent.
   In Illinois, more than half the state received less than 50
percent of normal rainfall from April 1 to Aug. 1, and nearly all
of it dipped below 70 percent. Twenty-two counties in the southeast
quarter of Nebraska alone received less than 70 percent of normal
rain since January. Figures since June were not available.
   Weather officials in Louisville, Ky., said rainfall was about 22
percent shy of normal for the June 1-Aug. 31 period, and that
conditions in the rest of the state appeared similar.
   The Chubb policy became embroiled in controversy when the
company was flooded with applications that exceeded the amount of
coverage it had authorized.
   Agents offered an estimated $400 million in insurance compared
to the $30 million limit, which Chubb later increased to $40
million. About 8,700 farmers applied. Angered over the disparity,
farmers sued Chubb and the cases were consolidated in a
class-action suit in federal court in Cincinnati.
   Insurance regulators in Ohio, Indiana, Minnesota and Iowa have
scheduled hearings on the issue.
   Chubb offered to return double the premiums paid by farmers who
were denied a policy, and has sent about 6,000 checks totaling $20
million, the spokeswoman said.
   Midnight Wednesday was also the deadline for farmers to have
letters postmarked asking for the doubled refunds.
   Lawyers for farmers in the Cincinnati case said an agreement
with Chubb lawyers was filed promising that the double payments
could be requested without forfeiting the right to sue.
   The Chubb spokeswoman said the promise was part of the company's
original refund offer. She also said the deadline would not be
extended.
   She said most of the applying farmers had been contacted by
telephone about the potential refund, but an unidentified numbers
of others could not be reached and had been written.
   Chubb has reacted to the image crisis created by the
controversey not just with the refunds but with full-page newspaper
ads, toll-free numbers and a special task force staffed by 125
people.
   The volume of phone calls Wednesday was not heavier than usual,
the company said.
</TEXT>
