<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineers Leave Koppers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Brian C. Beazer continues seeking buyers
for the chemical operations of his newly acquired Koppers Co., the
Pittsburgh company's engineering department Wednesday announced it
is breaking away as a consulting firm.
   ``We did begin studying this ... prior to Beazer being
successful'' in his takeover, said Anthony Foster, president of the
new ChemTech Consultants Inc. ``We then talked to Mr. Beazer about
the idea. He said it made perfect sense and was very supportive
from day one.''
   Beazer, chairman of a British construction and construction
materials business, prevailed over a reluctant Koppers management
in a hostile takeover, acquiring the Pittsburgh construction
materials and chemicals company for $1.8 billion on June 1.
   ChemTech will employ about 30 people, 18 of whom will be
investors.
   ``We're going to concentrate on the chemical industry and
continue to provide the same engineering services to Koppers that
we have historically done,'' Foster said.
   Leaner engineering departments in the nation's chemical
companies favor consultants like ChemTech, and the new firm's
specialties, which are process controls and electricity generation
from waste energy, are in demand in the industry, he said.
   ``We are equally enthusiastic with the formation of ChemTech,''
said Beazer, who has been seeking buyers for Koppers' chemical
business since a buyout by division managers collapsed a month ago.
</TEXT>
