<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TRWPlea     08-31 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TRW Plea,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Defendant In TRW Case Pleads Guilty To Mail Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former manager for TRW Inc. pleaded guilty
Wednesday to mail fraud, completing the government's procurement
fraud criminal case against the defense contractor, U.S. Attorney
Patrick McLaughlin said.
   Charles W. Broome, 64, of Gates Mills, former product line
manager of TRW's compresser components division, pleaded guilty in
U.S. District Court to participating in a scheme to defraud the
Department of Defense and General Electric Co., McLaughlin said.
   As part of a plea bargain, the government agreed to dismiss five
remaining counts and recommend probation in line with terms given
to two other defendants already sentenced, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Christian H. Stickan said.
   Two more co-defendants are awaiting sentencing. All five
co-defendants pleaded guilty.
   Broome will be sentenced after a report is filed with the court,
Stickan said. No date for sentencing was set. The maxiumum penalty
is a five years in prison and a $1,000 fine.
   The mail fraud charge involves the falsification of labor
expenses in the manufacture of the TF-39 fan blade used in the C-5A
military cargo plane, Stickan said.
   Last Thursday, TRW paid a $3 million penalty after pleading
guilty in U.S. District Court to three counts of conspiring to
overcharge the federal government for military aircraft and M-1
tank parts.
   Willliam Lawrence, TRW vice president and assistant secretary,
had waived the company's right to a trial and entered a guilty plea
for the company before Judge George W. White.
   Lawrence said the company also paid a separate $3 million to
increase to $11.8 million the amount paid toward restitution to the
government to settle a pending civil lawsuit. The total amount of
the required restitution will be determined in the suit.
   The company had estimated it overcharged the government between
$3 million and $11 million, Lawrence said. He said the compressor
components division was sold in 1986 as part of a restructuring
plan.
</TEXT>
