<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VideoWall     08-31 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Video Wall,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bellcore: Video Wall Next Step In Teleconferencing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses could unite workers at
various locations in a telephone conference and create the illusion
they are in the same room with a ``video wall,'' Bellcore said
Wednesday in unveiling a prototype.
   Bellcore, a research concern formed after the breakup of
American Telephone & Telegraph Co., said the video wall uses
``image merging'' techniques that bring together images generated
by multiple cameras. A final single image can be the product of
transmissions from several locations, said co-inventor Lanny Smoot.
   ``The wall is 8 feet wide for a panoramic view and people appear
to be lifelike,'' he said. ``It's as if you were looking through a
wall into an adjacent room.''
   Smoot said research has shown that workers who may share common
concerns or goals do not work together as well if they are in
separate buildings or even on different floors in the same building.
   The video wall could encourage people to work more closely
together, he said.
   Bellcore, which has headquarters in Livingston, developed the
wall at its research center in Morris Township.
   The research and engineering consortium serves the telephone
companies of the seven regional Bell holding companies.
   Smoot said it will be the companies' decision to market the
video wall as a service.
   Bellcore has applied for a patent involving the video merging
technique, he said.
</TEXT>
