<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-31 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0828</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Hit 12-Year Low On Threat To International Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices tumbled to a 12-year low Wednesday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange after an official of the
world's top cocoa-producing country said an international
price-support agreement was dying.
   On other markets, pork futures fell sharply; crop futures
gained; precious metals were higher; energy futures were lower; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   The shaky price-support agreement of the International Cocoa
Organization sustained another blow Wednesday when Denis Bra Kanon,
agriculture minister of the Ivory Coast, told representatives of
other producer nations he did not believe the ICCO would survive,
analysts said.
   The Ivory Coast, which produced 29 percent of the world's cocoa
last year, has been withholding its cocoa beans from the market in
hopes of selling them for higher prices.
   The Ivory Coast also owes about $48 million in cocoa levy fees
to the ICCO to support its operations.
   Bra Kanon's remarks Wednesday to a meeting of the Cocoa
Producers Alliance in Togo, had a profound impact on the cocoa
market, which had been looking forward to the ICCO's scheduled
two-week meeting beginning Sept. 5 in London. At that meeting,
consumer and producer nations are to begin negotiations toward a
new international cocoa price-support agreement.
   ``A lot of people who may have believed the price of cocoa might
rally because of the upcoming meeting were very demoralized,'' said
Arthur Stevenson, cocoa market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   Because of the reluctance of the Ivory Coast and other producers
to pay levies, ``the ICCO is facing very, very severe financial
problems,'' he said. ``How are they going to enforce economic
provisions to support prices if they don't have the cash to keep
going?''
   In addition to those factors, a glut of cocoa is expected in the
upcoming marketing year, which begins Oct. 1.
   Cocoa settled $44 to $60 lower with the contract for delivery in
September at $1,220 per metric ton.
   Frozen pork-belly futures plunged the permitted 2-cents-a-pound
limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in a third day of sharp
declines in the pork complex.
   Hog slaughters are increasing on a seasonal basis, and the
movement of hogs to market is being accelerated by the
earlier-than-normal maturation of corn and soybean crops, analysts
said.
   ``I have a feeling that producers are getting their pens cleaned
up and getting ready to turn their attention to the harvest here
pretty quick,'' said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with Agri-Visor
Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Most cattle futures moved lower on signs of slackening demand
for beef, he said.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .63 cent lower with October at
71.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with September at 81.70 cents a pound; hogs were .48 cent to
.95 cent lower with October at 38.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.42 cents to 2 cents lower with February at 48.90
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished higher on the Chicago Board
of Trade on indications that a long-awaited increase in foreign
demand was beginning to surface, analysts said.
   Prices had opened lower and made little movement until midday,
following strong indications that East Germany had purchased
300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn.
   The Agriculture Department said India purchased 250,000 metric
tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices while Mexico reportedly
bought 50,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 2 cents higher with September at $3.97{
a bushel; corn was 4 cents to 6} cents higher with September at
$2.83 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with September
at $2.56{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cents to 14 cents higher with
September at $8.54{ a bushel.
   Platinum led the precious-metals complex higher in a bounce
inspired by technical factors, analysts said.
   Platinum on the New York Mercantile Exchange settled $7.80 to
$8.10 higher with October at $533.90 a troy ounce. On New York's
Commodity Exchange, gold was $2.20 to $2.50 higher with October at
$434.10 a troy ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 6.6 cents higher with
September at $6.556 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures settled lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, where West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 9 cents to 28
cents lower with October at $15.18 a barrel; heating oil was .19
cent to .61 cent lower with September at 42.95 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .35 cent to 1.49 cents lower with September
at 46.54 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 1.10 points lower at 261.60.
</TEXT>
