<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CruiseBuyout     08-31 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cruise Buyout,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carnival Doubles Stake In Royal Caribbean, Admiral Cruise Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carnival Cruise Lines, the world's largest cruise
line, announced agreement in principle Wednesday to buy 70 percent
interest in Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines and Admiral Cruise Lines
for about $550 million cash.
   The announcement, issued jointly with Norway's Gotaas-Larsen
Shipping Corp., I.M. Skaugen A-S, Johnson Line AB and EFFOA-Finland
Steamship Co. Ltd., effectively doubles Carnival's initial 36
percent stake in Royal Caribbean and Admiral announced two weeks
ago.
   Under terms of the agreement, Carnival will buy all shares held
by Gotaas-Larsen, I.M. Skaugen, Johnson Line and EFFOA-Finland in
the Royal Caribbean and Admiral lines once a final sales agreement
has been reached and a mandatory federal waiting period has expired.
   Carnival President Micky Arison said no merger was planned of
the Carnival, Royal Caribbean and Admiral lines.
   ``They are three very different cultures,'' Arison said, ``and
we feel that operating three brands allows us to maximize our
return that way.''
   Carnival's planned purchase of Gotaas-Larsen's 36 percent stake
in the two lines was announced Aug. 17 at a price of $260 million.
   The expanded deal disclosed Wednesday adds the purchase by
Carnival of all I.M. Skaugen A-S, Johnson Line AB and EFFOA-Finland
Steamship Co. Ltd. holdings in Royal Caribbean and Admiral.
   Carnival operates seven ships sailing on three-, four- and
seven-day cruises to the Bahamas, Caribbean and Mexican Riviera.
The company also operates a casino in the Bahamas and is building a
luxury hotel at an adjacent site.
   Royal Caribbean operates primarily in the Caribbean, while
Admiral sails in both the Caribbean and the Pacific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
