<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TRW-Trucks     08-31 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-TRW-Trucks,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TRW Announces Program To Repair Recalled Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ross Gear Division of TRW Inc. probably
will spend under $25 million repairing or replacing gears that have
been recalled on heavy-duty trucks, the company said Wednesday.
   In a news release, TRW said the division has agreed to pay for
removal, freight, repair and reinstallation of TAS 65 integral
steering gears. The division also will pay certain costs of towing
vehicles taken out of service by the recall and for some travel and
lodging costs incurred by truck drivers, TRW said.
   The gears have failed in eight instances, but no one has been
injured, TRW said. An estimated 27,000 gears have been recalled,
and about 20,000 already have been returned to TRW, the company
said.
   TRW Ross Gear has advised truck owners that the steering gear
shouldn't be used until it is replaced or repaired. Truck
manufacturers have notified operators of affected vehicles, the
division said.
   ``The company is applying its full resources to the problem,''
said Delmar O. Stanley, vice president and general manager of Ross
Gear. ``We are shipping replacement gears for the affected vehicles
at a rate of 2,000 per day.''
</TEXT>
