<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ForeignBanks     08-31 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Banks,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Gives Three Foreign Firms OK To Run Banks On U.S. Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday granted
three foreign firms permission to acquire, start or maintain banks
on U.S. territory.
   The Bank of Tokyo Ltd. was given permission to acquire Union
Bank of Los Angeles by merging it into California First Bank, which
it already owns.
   California First is the sixth-largest commerical bank in the
state, with deposits of $4.7 billion. Union Bank is the
fifth-largest, with deposits of $7.8 billion. The two combined will
rank as fifth-largest.
   Bank of Toyko is the 22nd-largest bank in the world, with assets
of $183 billion.
   Board member Martha Seger, in a dissenting statement, said the
Japanese bank, because it is required by its government to have
less capital than is required in the United States, would have an
unfair advantage over U.S. institutions.
   In another action, the Fed approved an application from the Bank
of Seoul, the largest bank in South Korea and the 147th largest in
the world, to form Seoul Bank of California in Los Angeles.
   The board said the new bank would not have an adverse effect on
competition among banks in the Los Angeles area. Seger also opposed
the Seoul Bank application.
   The Fed also approved an application by Banco Bilbao-Vizcaya of
Spain to own Banco Comercial de Mayaguez in Puerto Rico. Banco
Bilbao-Vizcaya is being formed by the consolidation of two Spanish
institutions, one of which already owns the Puerto Rican bank.
   The merged bank, with $57.7 billion in assets, is the largest in
Spain. It already operates a branch in New York and agencies in
Miami and San Francisco. Banco Comercial is the seventh-largest
commercial bank in Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
