<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Nomura-GNPCommodities     08-31 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nomura-GNP Commodities,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Firm Seeking Controlling Stake In Chicago Futures
Brokerage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nomura Securities Inc., the world's largest
securities firm, is seeking a controlling interest in GNP
Commodities Inc., a mid-sized futures and options brokerage based
in Chicago, a GNP official said Wednesday.
   Brian Monieson, GNP's chief executive officer and one of its two
shareholders, said GNP had held preliminary discussions with the
Japanese firm.
   ``All we've done is that we are talking and we are continuing to
talk,'' he said. ``There's no agreement at all.''
   Control of GNP, an established trading firm with clearing status
on the Chicago Board of Trade, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the
Chicago Board Options Exchange and the Philadelphia Stock Exchange,
would give Nomura an edge over other Asian companies that are
moving into the U.S. futures and options markets.
   GNP's traders already have access to favorable positions in the
best trading pits, while newcomers often must start on the fringes.
   Membership on U.S. futures and options exchanges will allow
Japanese firms to use those instruments more easily to hedge
against adverse movements in stock and bond markets.
   The U.S. units of Daiwa Securities Co. and Yamaichi Securities
Co. gained full clearing membership on the Chicago Board of Trade
two weeks ago. In April, the U.S. unit of Nikko Securities Co. was
the first Japanese-affiliated firm to become a CBOT clearing member.
   Taiyo Kobe Bank Ltd., a large Japanese commercial bank, has
purchased associate clearing status on the CBOT and membership in
the International Monetary Market division of the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</TEXT>
