<DOCNO> AP880831-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WPPSSSettlement     08-31 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WPPSS Settlement,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reached Between WPPSS, Bondholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Public Power Supply System has
settled its part of a securities fraud lawsuit brought by
bondholders after the system defaulted on $2.25 billion in bonds
sold to finance two nuclear power plants, attorneys announced
Wednesday.
   Plaintiff bondholders would drop claims against WPPSS in return
for access to power plant accounts containing millions of dollars.
   Plaintiffs' attorneys also said the deal would gain them the
cooperation of WPPSS employees, who will be leading witnesses in
the trial set to start Sept. 7 in Tucson, Ariz.
   Remaining defendants include 20 public utilities in Washington
and one in Oregon, three engineering firms and a firm that had
provided WPPSS with financial advice.
   Attorneys reached the settlement, which had been proposed by the
plaintiffs, late Tuesday. The WPPSS Executive Board was expected to
approve the agreement at a special meeting Friday in Richland,
Wash., said Carl Halvorson, board chairman.
   ``It's a very favorable settlement for the supply system,'' he
said.
   The settlement also needs approval from U.S. District Judge
William D. Browning, who is presiding over the WPPSS default case.
   Under the tentative settlement, the plaintiff bondholders agreed
to dismiss all claims against WPPSS based on securities fraud,
misrepresentation and violation of state law.
   WPPSS in turn agreed it had an obligation to pay the face value
and interest on the bonds _ which would come to about $3 billion _
even though it paid no money in the settlement. The agreement also
noted that because of limited assets pledged to secure the bonds,
there was ``no expectation'' the money would ever be paid.
   However, the agreement did give bondholders unconditional access
to an account for the terminated plants, Nos. 4 and 5, which has
been under control of New York's Chemical Bank, the trustee for
plaintiff bondholders, since 1983.
   The account now has about $75 million in it and has withdrawn a
total of about $90 million, mostly for attorneys' fees.
   Other additional funds the bondholders might realize from the
settlement could come from a pending lawsuit seeking to wrest from
two other WPPSS projects funds that were spent when those plants
were ``twinned'' with the terminated projects. That could amount to
tens of millions of dollars, but a determination is years away.
   ``Since you can't get blood out of a turnip, why not get all the
other benefits you can,'' said Mel Weiss, who represents class
action plaintiffs in the giant lawsuit.
   The abrupt pullout of WPPSS from the litigation caught other
defendants by surprise, and one said defendants were considering
seeking a trial delay.
   ``We're surprised they (WPPSS) didn't stay and defend their
actions...,'' said Chuck Shigley, administrator for the Snohomish
County Public Utility District. ``It's not clear that we need more
time (to prepare for trial). There is a good chance we will be able
to pull it together.''
   In addition to access to funds, the settlement will allow
plaintiffs to talk with supply system employees before they are put
on the stand, according to Paul Bernstein, a plaintiffs' lawyer,
   Because of rules in a civil lawsuit, there were questions on
whether the WPPSS employees even would have to testify.
   Bondholders had sued the supply system, 88 utilities, bond
underwriters, various directors and managers, engineering firms and
advisors after WPPSS defaulted on $2.25 billion worth of bonds to
build the two never-completed nuclear power plants.
   Many defendants, including bond underwriters and more than 60
utilities, have reached settlements totaling $331 million over the
past year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
