<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AmericanMedical     08-31 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Medical,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Company Ousts Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and chief executive
officer of American Medical International Inc. has resigned under
pressure from four major stockholders and an interim successor has
been named, a spokesman said Wednesday.
   Directors accepted Walter L. Weisman's resignation on Tuesday.
Royce Diener, a sitting member of the board, was named interim
successor, American Medical spokesman Mick Taylor said Wednesday.
   The shuffle had been expected since Monday, when American
Medical, the nation's third-largest publicly held hospital concern,
said a committee of 13 of the 17 directors had recommended the
resignation of Weisman, 53. He had been chairman and chief
executive since September 1985.
   Bowing to the wishes of four large stockholders who are
dissatisfied with American Medical's languishing stock price, the
board committee reversed an earlier endorsement of Weisman.
   Diener, 70, is a former chairman of the company.
   The dissident shareholders, who together control about 30
percent of the company's stock, are Miami physician-businessman M.
Lee Pearce, Sid Bass and other members of his Fort Worth, Texas,
family, the Wedge Group investment concern in Houston, and former
Bass adviser Richard Rainwater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
